<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Armenians-Christmas     12-23 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armenians-Christmas,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>America's Armenians Plan Somber Christmas To Commemorate Quake
Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE P. BAYLISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The catastrophic earthquake in Armenia has
dampened the Christmas spirit in America's Armenian community, with
many festivities canceled and money normally spent on gifts being
sent for relief efforts.
   Armenians in the United States, as well as in South America and
Europe, have canceled or postponed Christmas and New Year's parties,
weddings, dances, tree decorating and other activities to mourn the
thousands killed in the Dec. 7 quake.
   ``The earthquake has pretty much ruined Christmas for most of the
Armenians I know,'' said Jean-Marie Atamian, a New York lawyer who
had volunteered to answer phones for the Armenian General Benevolent
Union in Saddle Brook, N.J.
   ``We have canceled all of the gatherings and dances and social
functions. We felt it would be totally inappropriate.''
   The earthquake devastated the cities of Leninakan, Spitak and
Kirovakan and up to 100 rural settlements in northwest Armenia.
Official Soviet sources have put the death toll as high as 55,000
and estimated the number of homeless at over 500,000.
   Christmas is celebrated Jan. 6 by the Armenian church and Dec. 25
by Armenian Catholics and Protestants.
   Leaders of the two branches of the Armenian church in the United
States declared a 40-day period of mourning when the earthquake hit.
But many Armenians say the decision to mute celebrations was
spontaneous.
   In New York, Archbishop Torkom Manoogian, head of the Eastern
Diocese of the Armenian Church of America, will hold a requiem Mass
for children Jan. 7 instead of the Christmas party he usually holds
for youngsters, according to Adrienne Alexanian, a volunteer at St.
Vartan Armenian Cathedral. About 70,000 Armenians live in the New
York-New Jersey area.
   In California, with the largest Armenian population outside the
Soviet Union _ some 250,000 live in the Los Angeles area _ Armenians
have canceled weddings and holiday parties. Churches are holding
special requiem services after Sunday Masses.
   Armenian Protestants are preparing for a somber holiday. ``Of
course we will still observe Christ's birth,'' said Rosey Maranjian,
who answered the telephone for the Armenian Mission Association at
its headquarters in Paramus, N.J. ``But there is nothing to
celebrate even though Christ is born.''
   ``We keep asking, `Why us?''' she said. One of her cousins died
in Leninakan, she added.
   ``It's a sad way to celebrate such a joyous event,'' said the
Rev. Moses Janbazian, the association's executive director.
   ``Instead of sending out Christmas cards to friends and
exchanging gifts, we are sending the money to Armenia. And most
families are doing that,'' said Shakeh Kadehjian, a secretary in the
New York office of the Armenian Evangelical Church, which celebrates
Christmas Dec. 25.
   ``Most of the people, without asking us, are canceling their
wedding ceremonies'' until after the mourning period ends Jan. 17,
said Rev. Nareg Shrikian of St. Mary's Armenian Apostolic Church in
Glendale, Calif.
   ``The first reaction among Armenians was to cancel everything,
not even to decorate Christmas trees,'' said Ara Kalaydjian, editor
of the Armenian Mirror-Spectator, an English-language newspaper
published in Watertown, Mass. The area is home to 30,000-40,000
Armenians.
   Kalaydjian said he planned a quiet dinner with his family. ``We
won't exchange gifts. We won't have a tree,'' he siad.
   Edward Bogosian, editor of the Armenian Reporter, said his
English-language weekly, published in New York, ordinarily carries
announcements of holiday events.
   But over the past two weeks, he said, ``all the listings carried
a notation: canceled, canceled, canceled, one after another.''
</TEXT>
