<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Crash-Warning     12-23 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Warning,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legal Experts Say Crash Could Raise Liability Problems For Pan Am</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision by Pan American World Airways and
the U.S. government not to alert the public to a fairly specific
bomb threat received long before Pan Am Flight 103 crashed in
Scotland could raise liability problems for the airline but probably
not for the government, attorneys say.
   ``I don't know of any legal requirement that the U.S. go public
on a thing like that other than notifying the airline involved and
possibly the embassies,'' said Lee Kreindler, a New York lawyer who
specializes in aviation accident cases.
   ``It's a difficult area, but if the government notifies the
airline in question, I think the government position is justified,''
Kreindler said Thursday.
   Kreindler said there are ``some policy reasons from the
government's standpoint for not'' notifying the traveling public.
One of the purposes of the Federal Aviation Act is to enhance
aviation and an announcement of a specific threat which might not be
bona fide could conceivably result in travelers not flying.
   Flight 103, originating in Frankfurt, West Germany, with a change
of planes at London's Heathrow Airport, crashed in Scotland on
Wednesday, killing all 258 people aboard and more than 20 on the
ground. It was bound for New York.
   Phyllis Oakley, a State Department spokeswoman, said that an
unidentified individual telephoned the U.S. Embassy in Helsinki on
Dec. 5 and said there would be a bombing attempt within two weeks
against a Pan Am aircraft flying from Frankfurt to the United States.
   The conduit would be an ``unwitting'' passenger who would take
the device from Helsinki to Frankfurt and then board a U.S.-bound
flight, she said.
   It has not been established, however, that the telephoned tip was
related to the Pan Am crash.
   Mrs. Oakley said dozens of threats are received each day and all
are taken seriously. L. Paul Bremer, who heads the State
Department's counter-terrorism office, said there have been 87 calls
similar to the Helsinki call over the past three months.
   But the Dec. 5 call, apparently from a tipster, appeared to be
taken more seriously than most others. Many U.S. embassies were
apprised of the threat, including the American mission in Moscow,
where a notice of the threat was posted on a bulletin board.
   No word went out to the general public.
   The prior notification ``is going to raise an interesting
question'' in connection with the other passengers ``who were not
members of the State Department staff whether they should have
received similar notice from Pan Am,'' said George N. Tompkins Jr.,
a lawyer specializing in defending airlines in accident cases.
   Bremer said in an interview Thursday night that not enough is
known to conclude that sabotage caused the jumbo jet to crash.
   ``We don't know if this is a terrorist attack,'' he said.
   Asked what an airline's obligation is once it has been notified
of a specific threat, Kreindler said, ``It's a tough situation. ...
They don't have to stop operating or stop flying, but certainly they
have a duty to meticulously inspect.''
   Kreindler said that in some other instances of terrorism
involving air travel, evidence-gathering in lawsuits has focused on
airline security precautions.
   Officials said Pan Am stepped up security at key airports in the
wake of the threat.
   Anyone filing lawsuits seeking settlements in excess of a $75,000
limit in international airlines cases would have to show willful
misconduct on the part of the airline in order to be successful.
   Tompkins said willful misconduct is extremely difficult to prove,
carrying with it a heavier burden of proof than gross negligence.
   Willful misconduct is a wrongful act done intentionally or an
improper act done wantonly with knowledge of the probable
consequences.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
