<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SRPManager     12-23 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SRP Manager,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>SRP Manager Says Plant Could Be Started Immediately If Needed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The manager of the Savannah River nuclear
material production plant said Thursday the facility's reactors,
which have been shut down because of safety concerns, could be
restarted immediately if necessary.
   ``I certainly think they can be restarted safely,'' said John T.
Lowe. ``I think if the nation judged there was a need for the
materials ... they could be restarted today.''
   The plant near Aiken, S.C., is the nation's sole producer of
tritium, a crucial ingredient in nuclear weapons.
   Lowe, who works for Du Pont, the operator of the U.S. Department
of Energy plant, said in an interview Thursday with The Augusta
Chronicle and the Augusta Herald that political pressures have
contributed to recent, highly publicized problems at the plant.
   Lowe was interviewed on the same day that Energy Secretary John
Herrington announced that ultrasonic testing will be used to check
for possible cracks in reactor vessels. That could delay SRP's
restart until next summer.
   All three Savannah River reactors have been shut down since
summer for safety upgrades and maintenance.
   Lowe declined to say when he thought the plant would resume
operations.
   ``I think that remains to be defined. There has been speculation
that it would be six months or 12 months. I really think until the
... criteria are well defined ... it's sheer speculation to pick a
date,'' Lowe said.
</TEXT>
