<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TradingSecrets     12-23 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trading Secrets,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says Official Mistaken In Listing Contractors Under
Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pentagon official who told Congress eight
major defense contractors were under investigation for possible
illegal trading of classified documents was mistaken, a Pentagon
spokesman said.
   The spokesman, Dan Howard, said Thursday that only four of the
companies are being investigated.
   Howard said John F. Donnelly, director of the Defense
Investigative Service, ``made a mistake'' when he told the Joint
Economic Committee on Wednesday that Litton Systems Inc., McDonnell
Douglas Corp. Northrop Corp., and TRW Inc. remain part of the
Pentagon's investigation of alleged trafficking of department
secrets among defense contractors.
   Investigations of these companies were closed in 1986, Howard
said.
   Howard said Donnelly was correct in listing four other companies
as remaining under investigation. Those are General Dynamics Corp.,
Boeing Co., Matin Marietta Corp. and Saunders Associates Inc.
   Donnelly had insisted the eight companies remained under
investigation, even after being told by subcommittee members that
his testimony was at odds with a government report on the
investigation.
   The Pentagon also criticized the congressional panel for making
the information public. ``We do not approve of the committee making
public this type of information,'' the department said in a
statement.
</TEXT>
