<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0131EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Ray-Parole     12-23 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ray-Parole,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Halts James Earl Ray Parole Hearing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By D.A. ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Ned McWherter on Thursday blocked a
Jan. 26 parole hearing for the man convicted in the 1968 sniper
slaying of civil rights leader Martin Luther King Jr.
   McWherter exercised a law giving the governor authority to halt
early parole hearings for prisoners convicted of certain crimes.
   James Earl Ray, 60, is serving 99 years in prison for
first-degree murder of King in Memphis on April 4, 1968.
   A 1985 law designed to reduce prison overcrowding made Ray
eligible for a parole hearing in November.
   ``We've been advised that he (Ray) is among that class of inmates
who will be affected by that order,'' said Jim Kennedy, McWherter's
chief of staff.
   Kennedy said the order was effective immediately for Ray, who has
been turned down for early parole at least twice before.
   David Welles, legal counsel for the governor, said McWherter's
decision would not affect Ray's original parole eligibility date in
1998 but removes him from consideration for an early release because
of his escape record.
   Ray was a fugitive from a Missouri prison at the time of King's
murder. He is held at Brushy Mountain State Prison, from which he
escaped in June 1977 and was tracked down and placed briefly on
Death Row in Nashville.
   King was in Memphis to assist in a strike by city sanitation
workers seeking higher pay on the day he was felled by a sniper's
bullet. Ray was identified from fingerprints found on a rifle near
the Lorraine Motel, where King was standing on a balcony at the time
of his death.
   Ray pleaded guilty on the day of his trial on March 9, 1969, but
retracted his story three days later and has since maintained his
innocence.
   McWherter had said he opposed Ray's parole but would not try to
influence the state Board of Paroles, which is independent from the
administration.
</TEXT>
