<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-XmasCards     12-23 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Xmas Cards,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Denies Issuing `Kill A Rebel' Christmas Cards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippine military has denied
responsibility for issuing Christmas cards that suggest recipients
should spend the season of peace killing Communist rebels.
   The cards, which have been circulating in Manila, feature the
following message on the front: ``On Christmas Day, don't sit around
the tree.'' Inside the card it reads, ``Kill an NPA rebel,''
referring to the New People's Army.
   Another card shows a woman receiving a Christmas package, and
beneath the drawing it reads, ``On Christmas Day, express your love
to an NPA.'' Inside, a package is shown exploding, followed by this
message: ``A gift to last a lifetime.''
   Some of the cards feature facsimile signatures of Defense
Secretary Fidel Ramos and Chief of Staff Gen. Renato de Villa.
   But Brig. Gen. Honesto Isleta, chief of the civil-military
relations service, denied Thursday the military had sent the cards
and said they were aimed at discrediting the armed forces.
   ``It is aimed at creating an impression to the recepient that the
sender does not respect the season of love,'' Isleta said. ``The
card is designed to discredit us.''
