<DOCNO> AP881223-0021 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0151EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SEC-Buyouts     12-23 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SEC-Buyouts,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Questions ``Fairness Opinions'' to Company Stockholders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission has questioned the independence of financial advisers who
tell stockholders a proposed leveraged buyout of their company is a
good deal.
   David S. Ruder told a House panel Thursday that experts who write
``fairness opinions'' often get higher fees if the deal goes
through. The opinions offer conclusions on the fairness of a buyout
offer.
   Asked by Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., whether fairness opinions were
independent, Ruder said, ``All in all, I am quite suspicious in a
significant number of cases, that the fairness opinion is prepared
by somebody with an incentive to go along with management.
   ``Personally, I think that needs to be addressed.''
   Ruder said he was giving the House Energy and Commerce
telecommunications and finance subcommittee his personal opinion _
not that of the SEC, which is currently reviewing all aspects of
leveraged buyouts.
   Leveraged buyouts occur when investors borrow heavily to buy out
a company and then pay off the debt with that company's cash flow or
by the sale of its assets.
   Ruder said the commission wants to determine whether it should
issue new rules to protect investors, and predicted the review would
continue at least through February.
   Fairness opinions are primary factors in the transactions, Ruder
said, because ``shareholders accord a great degree of weight to the
fact that a favorable opinion has been issued.''
   The opinions usually attest that the price offered for shares of
a company is a fair one.
   The hired financial adviser must rely almost exclusively on the
limited information that management supplies about the company.
   Subcommittee Chairman Edward Markey, D-Mass., said an investment
bank may receive $1 million to prepare the opinion, but $1.5 million
if the deal goes through.
   ``It sounds a little bit like a kickback to outsiders,'' Markey
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0153EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-LujanProfile     12-23 0703</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lujan Profile,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lujan A Surprise Pick For Interior Job, Since He'd Declined It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush's selection of Manuel
Lujan Jr. as interior secretary surprised almost everybody, because
the veteran New Mexico congressman said earlier this month he
wouldn't take the job if it were offered.
   Lujan, 60, is a Republican who announced in January he was
retiring from the House after 10 terms because wife ``Jean and I
thought it was time to come home.''
   He changed his mind even after specifically declaring himself out
of the running for the Interior Department post. Lujan told
reporters earlier this month that Bush transition aide Chase
Untermeyer had asked him if he would take the job, and ``I told him
I would not. I said I really didn't want to go back into government,
but I might be willing to serve on a board or something like that.''
   Reaction to the appointment was mixed.
   ``It's a solid choice. He's better than most of the names we've
been hearing,'' said Paul Pritchard, president of the National Parks
and Conservation Association, a frequent critic of the Reagan
administration.
   ``He will work well with Congress, and he knows where the bodies
are buried,'' Pritchard said.
   But Brock Evans, Washington vice president of the National
Audubon Society, said, ``I have the same heavy feeling in my heart
that I did eight years ago'' when James Watt was appointed to the
post by President Reagan. Lujan was a defender of Watt during his
controversial tenure.
   ``We feel as if we had just been given a lump of coal,'' said
Jeff Webb, president of Friends of the Earth.
   A fiscally conservative mainstream Republican from a prominent
New Mexico Hispanic political family, Lujan was the second-ranking
GOP member of the House Interior and Insular Affairs Committee. He
has devoted most of his time recently to the Science, Space and
Technology Committee, where he was the senior Republican.
   Because of his withdrawal, Lujan had hardly figured in
speculation for the slot, and was not on a list of four
``acceptable'' names submitted to the Bush transition team by
Western Republican senators.
   The choice could be a signal that Bush is serious about new
energy development _ Lujan was a sponsor of the principal bill in
the last session that would have opened the Arctic National Wildlife
Refuge to oil exploration.
   Environmentalists have strongly opposed exploration in that area,
on Alaska's North Slope 65 miles east of the existing fields at
Prudhoe Bay. Congress took no action on the issue.
   The League of Conservation Voters awarded Lujan a low score, 13
out of a possible 100. Lujan voted according to the
``environmentalist'' position only twice out of 16 test votes.
   However, Pritchard said Lujan had been responsive to concerns
about parks and historic preservation.
   The Wilderness Society expressed a split view, saying in a
statement by Vice President Sydney J. Butler that though they
differed on Alaska oil development, Lujan ``has been accessible to
the conservation community.''
   Rep. Leon Panetta, D-Calif., who has led the so-far successful
fight to ban oil exploration in federal waters off central and
northern California, said Lujan ``has not stood in the way of
measures to protect the California coast'' and ``will bring an open
mind to the issue.''
   The U.S. Chamber of Commerce hailed Lujan as ``clearly a friend
of business'' with an 80 percent favorable voting record, according
to the chamber's tabulation.
   Lujan, who now lives in Albuquerque, is a 1950 graduate of the
College of Santa Fe, where he grew up and where his father served as
mayor in the 1940s.
   He will be the second Hispanic in the Bush Cabinet. Education
Secretary Lauro Cavazos has been asked by Bush to stay on.
   ``I went to Washington to balance the budget and we still haven't
done it,'' Lujan once said when asked to name his biggest
disappointment.
   In 1986, he suffered a heart attack and underwent a triple bypass
operation, but in January he said he was not leaving Congress
because of ill health _ rather, ``It was always my fear that I would
stay too long and not have my health.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0156EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ReillyProfile     12-23 0857</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reilly Profile,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Nominee for EPA Works for Consensus on Environmental Issues</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Reilly, President-elect Bush's choice
to head the Environmental Protection Agency, is a former land use
planner who has spent 15 years leading a foundation that tries to
solve environmental conflicts through consensus.
   Reilly, who turns 49 on Jan. 26, is president of the Conservation
Foundation and of the U.S. affiliate of the World Wildlife Fund, two
organizations whose merger he engineered in 1985.
   The Wildlife Fund has concentrated on preservation of wildlife
and habitat in the tropics, urging reversal of worldwide
deforestation that is clearing total acreage the size of Missouri
each year.
   The Conservation Foundation, which Reilly took over in 1973, is a
research group that has sponsored several convocations of industry
and environmentalists to try to resolve particular local issues.
   Unlike many Washington environmental groups, it does not lobby or
file lawsuits.
   The fund has been the nation's fastest-growing environmental
organization in recent years, tripling its membership to 500,000
since 1985.
   During Bush's announcement ceremony Thursday, Reilly said he
believed he was the first head of such an organization chosen to run
the EPA, and he pledged a ``new and constructive course'' on
environmental problems at home and around the world.
   In a recent interview, Reilly attributed his organization's
growth to the response to active solicitation among a population
exposed to a steady diet of nature programs on television.
   ``The public watches enormous amounts of nature films,'' Reilly
said. ``I worry about saturation, but people who know about these
things tell me not to.''
   And, he said, ``The people who elected George Bush are worried
about the international environment.''
   Reilly has paid particular attention to the ``greenhouse effect''
_ the global warming predicted to result from the use of fossil
fuels. Unlike many environmentalists, he has not ruled out nuclear
power as a benign energy source, and he was considering the
formation of another all-viewpoints study group on nuclear power.
   He serves on the board of several non-pofit organizations and of
Northeast Utilities Inc.
   He said he believed environmentalists were coming to ``two new
awarenessess,'' that ``the environment is much less under control
than we believed'' and ``the degree to which we appear to be hostage
to other countries for our health and well-being.''
   Though no defender of controversial former Interior Secretary
James Watt, he said Watt's $1 billion, four-year renovation of
national park structures ``made a lot of sense'' but ``natural
systems didn't get the same kind of attention.''
   On the parks, the Bush administration ``has got to take the
external threats issue seriously. That's a tough issue for a
conservative administration.'' Park advocates have complained that
threats of development up against park boundaries are spoiling many
parks.
   Reilly has enjoyed the confidence of the outgoing administrator
of EPA, Lee M. Thomas, and Thomas' predecessor, William D.
Ruckelshaus, who turned to the foundation for several studies.
   During the Reagan administration, the foundation has produced
three major ``state of the environment'' documents and, among other
things, major studies of groundwater contamination and national
parks. Before that, it was a pioneer in calling attention to the
dangers of excessive use of pesticides.
   In 1984, the foundation helped organize Clean Sites Inc., which
organizes cleanup of toxic waste by polluting companies themselves.
Clean Sites was begun with chemical industry money but now gets
two-thirds of its funds elsewhere.
   EPA backed a major study of wetlands by the foundation and the
National Governors Association, which recommended last month a goal
of creating enough new wetlands to more than offset the loss of
bogs, swamps, fens, marshes and estuaries to development. Bush has
endorsed the ``no net loss'' goal.
   Thomas turned to Reilly this fall to organize a study of the
Superfund toxic waste cleanup program that would bring industry and
environmentalists together. The environmentalists, however, objected
that the study could be a cover for weakening the program and
declined to participate.
   Reilly is a protege of former EPA administrator Russell Train,
for whom he worked on the staff of the White House Council on
Environmental Quality in 1970-1972. Train is now chairman of the
U.S. World Wildlife Fund affiliate and of the Conservation
Foundation.
   Train was an adviser to Bush on environmental issues and
solicited support for Bush among environmentalists.
   Thomas hailed Reilly's selection as being ``truly outstanding.''
Ruckelshaus said, ``The country, the Bush administration, the people
of EPA and our environment will all be better off.''
   ``This is a positive signal from the president-elect that he
intends to carry out his campaign commitments to environmental
protection,'' said John Adams, executive director of the Natural
Resources Defense Council.
   A graduate of Yale University who holds a law degree from Harvard
and a master's degree in planning from Columbia, Reilly was born in
Decatur, Ill., spent his childhood nearby and went to high school in
Fall River, Mass.
   After college graduation in 1962, he served in the Army,
practiced law in Chicago, attended graduate scool and served as
associate director of the Urban Policy Center before joining the
Council on Environmental Quality.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
