<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SullivanProfile     12-23 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sullivan Profile,570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sullivan Seeks Better Health Care For Poor</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Louis W. Sullivan, named to head the
Department of Health and Human Services, leads one of three
predominantly black medical schools in the nation and is a longtime
advocate of improved health care for disadvantaged Americans.
   In selecting Sullivan on Thursday, President-elect Bush fulfilled
his pledge to name a black to his Cabinet. But the much-anticipated
nomination was assured only after Sullivan quelled a last-minute
outcry from anti-abortion forces.
   Their objections were triggered by an Atlanta newspaper interview
Sunday in which Sullivan said he supports a woman's right to seek an
abortion, though he opposes federal assistance for it.
   On Monday, Sullivan wrote a letter to The Atlanta Journal and The
Atlanta Constitution saying he is ``opposed to abortion except in
cases of rape, incest and where the life of the mother is
threatened'' _ a statement mirroring Bush's views and one which he
repeated at the President-elect's side in Washington on Thursday.
   Sullivan also declared that the ``nation must address the
disparity that exists in the availability and quality of health
care'' for Americans of differing economic means.
   Similarly, Sullivan had set as the ``abiding goal'' of his
institution the training of doctors willing to establish family
practices in rural and inner-city areas.
   Sullivan, 55, a blood specialist, has been president of the
Morehouse School of Medicine in Atlanta since it became independent
from Morehouse College in 1981. He has taught medicine at Harvard,
Morehouse, the New Jersey College of Medicine and Boston University,
where he graduated with honors in 1958.
   Sullivan returned to BU as an assistant medical professor in
1966. While there, he distinguished himself as a hematologist and
implemented the first minority recruiting program at the school.
   ``Doctor Sullivan is an unusually able physician and
administrator,'' said Hugh Gloster, retired president of Morehouse
College, who hired Sullivan.
   ``He tends to delegate but he handles the important things
himself. He makes the big presentations.''
   He described Sullivan as a charismatic man whose selection to
head the school was the result of an extensive national search. ``I
doubt if there is anyone better qualified,'' he said.
   At Morehouse, Sullivan oversees a faculty and staff of about 100
and currently has no teaching assignments.
   The medical school separated from Morehouse College in 1981 when
it began offering graduate degrees. Its new campus was dedicated in
1982 in a ceremony attended by Bush, whose wife, Barbara, was named
to the medical school's board of trustees in 1983. Sullivan
accompanied the Bushes during a trip to Africa in 1982.
   Sullivan has written or co-written more than 60 technical
articles, mostly dealing with blood chemistry and diseases.
   He has directed national research on sickle cell anemia, a fatal
blood disease that primarily affects blacks. The Atlanta native is a
former president of the Foundation for Minority Health Professions,
and has often expressed concern over the low number of minorities
entering medicine.
   At the same time, he has said that Morehouse, while heavily
black, welcomes white students, especially those willing to practice
medicine in rural or urban poor areas.
   Sullivan, a 1954 honors graduate of Morehouse College and a
graduate of the Boston University Medical School, and his wife,
Ginger, have three children.
   He is active in the American Red Cross and the American Cancer
Society, and serves on the National Executive Board of the Boy
Scouts of America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
