<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DerwinskiProfile     12-23 0705</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Derwinski Profile,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Derwinski's Selection as VA Chief Surprises Vets Groups, Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward J. Derwinski, a surprise nominee to
become the first secretary of the new Department of Veterans
Affairs, is a former long-time Illinois congressman who lost his
seat at the hands of redistricting.
   Derwinski's selection Thursday by President-elect Bush surprised
advocates for veterans groups and those who deal with veterans
issues in Congress because he has dealt little with issues of
concern to veterans.
   ``I'll admit it was a surprise to me,'' said Rep. G.V.
Montgomery, D-Miss., chairman of the House Veterans Affairs
Committee. ``His name had never even surfaced.''
   One congressional aide described the Capitol Hill reaction as a
``giant shock.''
   Derwinski, 62, did not serve on veterans committees in Congress,
and since then he has worked at the State Department. However,
initial reaction among veterans and their advocates was supportive.
   ``I think he'll be a strong and balanced advocate to be sure
veterans get their share of whatever pie is available for
allocation,'' said Gen. Richard G. Stilwell, a retired Army officer
who served as deputy undersecretary of defense in the Reagan
administration.
   Montgomery, who successfully pushed legislation to upgrade the
Veterans Administration to a Cabinet level department, called him
``a fine choice.''
   ``He has a great wit that will be an asset as he tackles this
tough new job,'' Montgomery said. ``A number of us who sponsored the
Cabinet-level job were looking for a strong spokesman for veterans.
I believe we have the right person in Derwinski.''
   John Hanson, spokesman for the American Legion, said Derwinski
has spoken twice to Legion meetings on international issues.
   ``We've worked with him before,'' Hanson said. ``He's been
friendly and we look forward to seeing him again,.''
   Derwinski has been undersecretary of state for security
assistance, science and technology, a post he assumed in April 1987.
He was named counselor of the State Department in 1983 after leaving
Congress, and served as a special adviser to the secretary of state.
   In those jobs he has been in charge of State Department dealings
with the transfers of arms and sensitive technology. As the
department's international sports coordinator, he worked with Korean
authorities on security arrangements at the Seoul Olympics this year.
   In Congress, Derwinski was known for his trademark crew cut and
loud sportcoats, and for his puckish humor.
   At the VA, he will head a huge bureacuracy with 240,000
employees, a budget of more than $10 billion and the largest
hospital system in the nation.
   The VA has undergone serious financial difficulties as a result
of budget constraints at a time when more veterans are becoming
elderly and are in need of care at VA hospitals, nursing homes and
other medical facilities.
   The current administrator, Thomas Turnage, has come under fire in
Congress as a result of cutbacks in hospital care. Critics have
faulted him for failing to aggressively seek larger budget
appropriation requests within the administration.
   In hearings earlier this year, Montgomery's committee heard
testimony that 8,000 to 10,000 of the VA's 72,000 beds had been put
out of service because of money problems.
   ``It's not going to be an easy job because at the start of the
new Congress we're going to have to seek additional funds,''
Montgomery said. ``We're turning away patients now. We just never
have gotten enough money to run them. He's got his work cut out for
him.''
   Derwinski, a Chicago native, served in the Army in the Pacific
during World War II. He was a member of Congress from 1959 to 1983
from Illinois' 4th Congressional District. He served on the Foreign
Affairs and Post Office and Civil Service committees.
   Derwinski's district was combined with that of another Republican
congressman, George O'Brien, in reapportionment after the 1980
census. The two opposed each other in a Republican primary, and
Derwinski lost.
   He served in the state legislature before being elected to
Congress, and in 1964 was state chairman of Barry Goldwater's
Republican presidential campaign.
   Rep. Bob Michel, R-Ill., said Derwinski was ``always voluably
anticommunist.'' Rep. Edward R. Madigan, R-Ill., said Derwinski, who
is of Polish ancestry, was active and popular with ethnic Republican
organizations.
</TEXT>
