<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     12-23 0886</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain's Taste For American Food Boosts U.S. Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain has turned into one of the American
farmer's richest overseas markets, but Agriculture Department trade
analysts say the character of those shipments are changing rapidly.
   For example, since the entry of Spain into the European Economic
Community in 1986, U.S. exports of wheat and feed grains have fallen
dramatically, says the department's Foreign Agricultural Service.
   But other kinds of products, including many high-value items,
have taken up much of the slack. In the fiscal year that ended Sept.
30, the total value of U.S. farm exports to Spain was $848 million,
up 30 percent from $652 million in 1986-87.
   An important factor is the thriving Spanish economy, which has
helped create new and expanded demand for processed or
semi-processed foods that carry higher price tags than the
traditional bulk commodities.
   Spain's gross national product, or the sum of its goods and
services, grew 5.5 percent in 1987, the highest in Europe, and is
expected to gain nearly that much in 1988, the agency said Thursday
in a report.
   ``However, at more than 19 percent, unemployment remains the
country's most compelling economic and social problem,'' the report
added.
   The surge last fiscal year put Spain among the world's top 10
markets for U.S. agricultural exports. Leading commodities included:
soybeans and soybean meal, corn and corn gluten feed, tallow, hides,
skins, walnuts, peas, beans, lentils, seeds, yellow grease, prunes
and poultry meat.
   Further, the report said, the United States supplied all of
Spain's imported almonds and half of its imported cattle semen.
   ``Increasing disposable income, a more urban and youthful
population and larger numbers of working women have resulted in
greater interest in convenience items, fast foods and more eating
outside the home,'' the report said. ``Patronage of restaurants
traditionally is high.''
   The report added: ``Although the standard three-hour business
lunch endures, consumption of fast foods and snacks is increasing.
Numerous tourists and the growing number of Spaniards who have
traveled abroad tend to encourage greater interest in new food
ideas.''
   As an EEC member, Spain's food processing industry has become a
prime takeover target for investment by many kinds of multinational
companies, and this shows little sign of subsiding, the report said.
   Meanwhile, Spain makes up an important part of the EEC's total
market for U.S. agricultural products. Last fiscal year, U.S.
shipments to the 12-nation trading bloc totaled $7.5 billion, with
Spain accounting for more than 11 percent.
   Japan was the second-largest market (and the biggest for a single
country), with $7.3 billion in 1987-88. Others in the top 10
included: South Korea, $2.3 billion; Canada, $2 billion; Soviet
Union, $1.9 billion; Mexico, $1.7 billion; Taiwan, $1.6 billion;
Egypt, $800 million; Iraq, $700 million; and China, $600 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department says the Soviet
Union and China have added 1.4 million metric tons of U.S. grain to
their 1989 granaries, including wheat sold to Beijing at subsidized
prices.
   Moscow's order announced Thursday was for an additional 1 million
metric tons of corn for delivery under a recently extended supply
agreement between the two countries. China bought 400,000 tons of
wheat under the subsidy program.
   The latest sales by private exporting companies brought total
corn sold to the Soviets to almost 8.03 million tons in the
agreement's sixth year, which began Oct. 1. Last year, U.S. corn
sales to the Soviet Union totaled slightly less than 5.2 million
tons.
   Exporters are required to report foreign grain sales of 100,000
tons or more to the USDA within 24 hours. Smaller sales are reported
weekly.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 1 million tons of
corn would be about 39.4 million bushels.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.61 per bushel at the
farm level, according to USDA estimates, meaning that the latest
sale could have a farm value of around $103 million.
   Although no wheat has yet been sold for 1988-89 delivery under
the pact, the Soviets have ordered 500,000 tons of soybeans and
532,500 tons of soybean meal, plus 500,000 tons of grain sorghum.
   Melvin E. Sims, general sales manager for the department's
Foreign Agricultural Service, said seven export companies were
involved in the sale of 400,000 tons of wheat to China, some 14.7
million bushels having an estimated farm value of $58 million at
recent prices.
   The companies included: Cargill Inc., 90,000 tons; Central States
Enterprises, 40,000 tons; Nissho Iwai American Corp., 30,000 tons;
Bunge Corp., 40,000 tons; Tradigrain Inc., 50,000 tons; Tradecom
Inc., 30,000 tons; and Louis Dreyfus Corp., 120,000 tons.
   Sims said the sales were part of an authorized 1 million tons of
wheat announced on Dec. 7 under the Export Enhancement Program, or
EEP. With the latest sales, China now has 210,000 tons remaining
under the authorization.
   The program enables exporters to sell wheat and other designated
commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to
meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free government
surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies.
   Sims said the bonuses due the seven exporters for the latest deal
averaged $23.10 per ton of wheat, or about 63 cents per bushel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
