<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0157EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-23 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Rises Again Against Yen, Shares Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose Friday against the Japanese yen
for the second consecutive day, while share prices closed lower on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   The dollar opened higher at 124.90 yen and continued to edge up,
finishing the week's trading at 124.95 yen, up 0.33 yen from
Thursday's close. It had gained 0.40 yen on Thursday.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 76.42-point
gainer the previous day, fell 88.35 points, or 0.30 percent, closing
at 29,686.26.
   A currency dealer described trading as light due to a dearth of
news regarding exchange rates.
   ``The dollar may have moved up somewhat but it's nothing major
because market participants are sticking to the sidelines ahead of
the weekend,'' the dealer said, speaking anonymously.
   But on Thursday, Bank of Japan Gov. Satoshi Sumita said the
foreign exchange market was stabilizing in the wake of the dollar's
recent sharp decline. He also said the central bank would continue
to monitor the market.
   Securities dealers attributed the bullish Tokyo stock market to
stable currency exchange rates and a wait-and-see mood ahead of the
New Year holiday period.
   ``Most foreign players seem to be out of town for the Christmas
break and as a result, the whole market is slowing down,'' said a
trader with a Tokyo securities company.
   Another dealer said investors were trading actively ahead of the
expected demise of the 87-year-old Emperor Hirohito, who has been
seriously ill for over three months.
   ``The market will very likely slow down when the emperor passes
away,'' said the dealer at Sanyo Securities Co., speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``But on the other hand, there is apparently
a huge amount of excess money in investors' hands, so many of them
feel it is time to invest.''
   Hirohito has been bedridden since Sept. 19 when he vomited blood
due to internal hemorrhaging. Share prices have tended to dip in
recent days in reaction to reports on his worsening health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
