<DOCNO> AP881223-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0201EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-UN-Namibia Bjt   12-23 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Namibia, Bjt,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa, Angola Vow Continued Support For Each Others' Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Africa and Angola say they will
continue supporting rebels fighting each other's governments,
despite having signed a pact pledging not to interfere in each
other's domestic affairs.
   Foreign ministers of South Africa, Cuba, and Angola signed the
agreement Thursday granting independence to South-West Africa, which
will become the new nation of Namibia in 1991. It has been ruled by
South Africa since World War I.
   The pact also stated that 50,000 Cuban troops in Angola will
withdraw, under U.N. supervision.
   The signatories affirmed ``the principle of non-interference in
the internal affairs of states'' and promised not to allow their
territory to be used ``in connection with any acts of war,
aggression, or violence, against the territorial integrity,
inviolability of borders or independence of any state of
southwestern Africa.''
   Pretoria backs rebels fighting to overthrow Angola's Marxist
government, and Angola harbors bases of the African National
Congress, which is fighting South Africa's white-led government.
   Afonso van Dunem, Angola's foreign minister, told reporters ``the
ANC is carrying out a just fight in the name of all humanity against
apartheid, therefore the ANC will continue to receive the solidarity
and support from our government and our people.''
   He denied South Africa is part of ``southwestern Africa,'' saying
that region encompasses only Angola and Namibia.
   But he refused to say whether the ANC will be allowed to maintain
several bases in Angola.
   At a separate news conference, South Africa's foreign minister,
R.F. Botha, was asked if his country would suspend assistance to
Angolan rebels, known as UNITA.
   ``I would be telling you a lie if I say to you that we can
suddenly end our friendship with UNITA,'' he replied. ``We will
remain sympathetic to that organization. Friendship cannot be
terminated in this manner.''
   He promised, however, that South Africa would not violate the
accords, suggesting it will continue with political and diplomatic
support of the rebels but will not send weapons.
   Botha said if the ANC ``is allowed by Angola to continue to
operate as they've done up to now from Angolan territory ... to kill
members of the civilian population of South Africa, that would be a
clear-cut violation of the various agreements.''
   Chester A. Crocker, the U.S. assistant secretary of state who
mediated talks leading to the accords, told reporters Wednesday the
question of support for rebels was a matter between Angola and South
Africa.
   Crocker, Secretary of State George P. Shultz, U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar and other diplomats
watched the signing of the accords Thursday.
   ``With the independence of Namibia, Africa's last colonial
question will have been resolved,'' Shultz said.
   The agreement calls for a one-year transition to independence for
Namibia, beginning April 1.
   Under the pact, half the 50,000 Cuban soldiers are to pull out by
Nov. 1, when Namibia is to hold its first free elections for a
national assembly. The rest must be gone by July 1, 1991.
   Foreign ministers Isidoro Malmierca of Cuba and van Dunem of
Angola then signed an agreement under which 70 U.N. peacekeepers
will monitor the Cuban withdrawal.
   A Security Council plan for Namibia's independence calls for
about 2,000 civilian administrators and military police to back
about 7,500 U.N. peacekeepers as South African troops withdraw and a
civilian government is organized.
   The South-West African People's Organization, which has fought
South African forces in Namibia more than 20 years, was not part of
the accords but said it will honor a cease-fire.
   Angolan guerrillas also were excluded.
   South Africa has controlled Namibia, a mineral-rich territory of
about 1.2 million people, since capturing it from Germany in World
War I. It refused to leave, despite U.N. opposition to its presence
there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
