<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Assembly     12-23 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Assembly,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>43rd Assembly Ends Session Of Concord, Agreements, Peacekeeping</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-UN-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reflecting the climate of detente between
the United States and the Soviet Union, the United Nation's 43rd
General Assembly concluded its most harmonious session.
   The buoyant, sometimes tumultuous session that ended Thursday was
highlighted by President Reagan's farewell, Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
show-stopping debut and the assembly's decision for the first time
to leave New York and travel to Geneva to hear Yasser Arafat.
   The 12-week session adopted most resolutions by consensus
including, for the first time, the Afghanistan resolution
recognizing the Soviet troop withdrawal.
   It adopted the U.N. budget without a divisive note Wednesday _
the first time the financial plan was adopted without a vote since
the world body was founded 42 years ago.
   The 1990-91 budget of $1.76 billion was about $22 million less
than the last. Its adoption by consensus and the lower expenditure
were viewed as a U.S. victory.
   Dante Caputo, the General Assembly president and Argentina's
foreign minister, told the closing session the assembly had
benefited from the new international climate of detente and
cooperation between the United States and the Soviet Union and had
contributed to it.
   Caputo said the consensus within the 159-member assembly was
``unprecedented in the history of the organization.''
   The world body even charmed its most strident critic, the United
States, which committed itself during the session to repay nearly
$500 million owed to the U.N. budget and peacekeeping forces. The
money had been withheld for years for ideological, budgetary and
other reasons.
   Relations strained during most of the eight-year Reagan
administration eased considerably and when Reagan delivered his
final speech in September, he praised the world body for its
peacekeeping and peacemaking in Afghanistan, Iran and Iraq and
elsewhere.
   Before the session ended, the United Nations played host at the
signing of an agreement granting independence to South-West Africa,
better known as Namibia. It was signed Thursday by South Africa,
Angola and Cuba, which agreed to withdraw its 50,000 troops from
Angola.
   The assembly will reconvene in mid-January to discuss financial
questions and funding of a U.N. monitoring force in South-West
Africa.
   Gorbachev, the Soviet president, delivered a tour de force of
Soviet diplomacy at the assembly this month, promising unilaterally
to cut 500,000 Soviet troops and many jet fighters in Europe and
Asia.
   In December, the United States refused PLO Chairman Arafat a visa
to address the General Assembly.
   The PLO is an honored U.N. invitee and, in protest, the assembly
voted overwhelmingly to move to Geneva to hear Arafat.
   There, Arafat explicitly recognized Israel's right to exist,
renounced terrorism, and called for direct talks with Israel.
   The United States announced it would end a 13-year ban and open a
dialogue with the PLO, changing the entire Middle East landscape and
opening new possibilities for peace.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
