<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Again Against Yen, Shares Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese yen for
the second consecutive day in Tokyo today, while share prices
declined in slow trading ahead of the year-end holiday period,
traders said.
   The dollar opened higher at 124.90 yen and edged up a bit more,
finishing the week's trading at 124.95 yen, up 0.33 yen from its
close on Thursday, when it gained 0.40 yen.
   ``The dollar's not really rising all that much because there's a
lack of buy orders. The market is really weak at this time of
year,'' said an exchange dealer with a major commercial bank,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The 225-isssue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 76.42 points
the previous day, lost 88.35 points, or 0.30 percent, closing at
29,686.26.
   Volume in the first section was estimated at a light 600 million
shares, down from almost 734 million shares traded Thursday.
   ``Most foreign players seem to be out of town ... and as a
result, the whole market is slowing down,'' said a broker based with
a Tokyo securities company.
   Shipping stocks declined sharply following an announcement this
morning that Yamashita-Shinnihon Steamship Co. and Japan Line Ltd.
had agreed to merge next June to form one of the country's largest
shippers.
   In a statement, the two companies said the merger was necessary
to resolve an operational crisis caused by a slump in the shipping
sector brought on by the strong yen and the oil crises of the 1970s.
   The decline in shipping stocks also led to sell orders for steel,
non-ferrous metals, heavy electrials and auto shares, market reports
said.
   There are no foreign exchange dealings on Saturday, but the Tokyo
Stock Exchange will be open for a half-day session.
</TEXT>
