<2ND_LINE>PM-Dali,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvador Dali Hospitalized, Reported Stable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FIGUERAS, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artist Salvador Dali was in stable
condition today after being rushed to a hospital suffering from
complications from a small intestinal lesion, doctors said.
   In a morning statement, a five-doctor team said the 84-year-old
artist was taken from his Galatea Tower mansion to Figueras Hospital
late Thursday after experiencing nausea and vomiting a small amount
of blood.
   The statement said an inspection of Dali's intestinal tract
showed a ``slight superficial lesion'' in the stomach lining.
   ``Dali's condition, despite this incident, is similar to that of
previous days, and a decision has been taken to keep him under
observation'' for 48 to 72 hours, the statement said.
   On Nov. 27, Dali was admitted for treatment of pneumonia in the
same hospital in Figueras, his hometown in northeastern Spain.
   The next day he was rushed by ambulance 60 miles to Barcelona's
Quiron Clinic in critical condition, suffering from a severe heart
problem aggravated by blood clots in his left lung.
   He was released Dec. 14.
   Dali, a founding member of the surrealist movement, is the last
of an outstanding generation of Spanish painters that included Pablo
Picasso, who died in 1973, and Joan Miro, who died a decade later.
   Dali has been in poor health and in a wheelchair since August
1984 when he suffered serious burns in a fire at his home.
   He was hospitalized for three months and since then has lived in
seclusion.
   In 1986, Dali underwent surgery to receive a heart pacemaker.
</TEXT>
