<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MyersonProfile     12-23 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Profile,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bess: Not Embellished by Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Myerson Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK HAMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year before Bess Myerson went on trial for
allegedly bribing a judge to fix her lover's divorce case, an old
friend said the former Miss America was ``thinking very positively
what it means to her life.''
   ``She is saying, `I'm going to create a new Bess Myerson,'''
Marilyn Funt told a reporter.
   If a new Bess Myerson exists, she was the smiling, composed,
seemingly confident woman who strode up the steps of the federal
courthouse each weekday for the past four months.
   But once she sat down inside she was forced to listen to tales of
the old Bess Myerson, a woman who was at the least ``eccentric'' _
her lawyer's term _ and possibly dominated by what the prosecutor
called ``greed and vengeance.''
   The issue for jurors was whether Miss Myerson tried to bribe
Judge Hortense Gabel, who was handling the divorce of Miss Myerson's
lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso.
   Miss Myerson, the former commissioner of the city Department of
Cultural Affairs, allegedly hired Mrs. Gabel's daughter, Sukhreet;
in return, it was charged, the judge reduced Capasso's support
payments.
   On Thursday evening, the federal jury acquitted Miss Myerson,
Mrs. Gabel and Capasso.
   Despite the verdict, the image of Bess Myerson _ the first Jewish
Miss America, a key political ally of Mayor Edward I. Koch, a
successful consumer advocate, a popular TV personality _ was
tarnished by her trial.
   Miss Myerson never took the stand to speak for herself. But
according to the testimony of others, she was cheap, secretive and
vindictive.
   She was described as a woman worth $7 million who kept her jewels
in a toolbox and once recycled a bouquet of flowers she'd received
by changing the card and having them delivered to Mrs. Gabel.
   A witness said she made numerous telephone calls on a private
line to the judge's chambers, often using aliases, including ``Helen
Goodman'' and ``Mrs. Robinson.''
   She didn't want daytime visitors at Capasso's beachfront estate
to know she had stayed overnight, so ``she would walk out the
kitchen door and come in the front door, as if she had just
arrived,'' according to the housekeeper.
   She invited Sukhreet Gabel to accompany her to a party, but
insisted she use her former husband's name _ Ms. Gabel was divorced
in 1980 _ instead of the maiden name she shares with her mother.
   One night in June 1986, Miss Myerson went to Ms. Gabel's
apartment house dressed in a gray sweatsuit, a headband and
lavender-tinted sunglasses. She refused to give her name to the
doorman.
   On a walk around the block, Miss Myerson allegedly told Ms. Gabel
``You could be dangerous,'' and warned her to ``keep your mouth
shut.''
   Witnesses recalled how she pointed out Capasso's estranged wife
on the street one day as ``an evil woman'' and celebrated with
Capasso after his payments were reduced.
   Moreover, expectations were low when the trial began, for Miss
Myerson had been arrested for shoplifting in Williamsport, Pa. She
looked old and disheveled in newspaper photographers, and was
reported to have been arrested earlier in London on a similar charge.
   But in the end, Miss Myerson's eccentricities paled to her
accuser's.
   Sukhreet Gabel, a plump, chatty, often fatuous woman who enjoyed
the attention as much as Miss Myerson disdained it, said
electroshock therapy for depression had left her memory ``like Swiss
cheese,'' and parlayed her status as the prosecution's key witness
into at least a fleeting celebrity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0412EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MyersonTrial Bjt   12-23 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Myerson Trial, Bjt,0651</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Myerson, Co-Defendants Acquitted In Divorce-Fixing Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cheers broke out and former Miss America Bess
Myerson sobbed and kissed her co-defendant lover after their
soap-opera-like divorce-fixing trial ended in acquittals.
   ``It's over,'' Miss Myerson said after her two-year ordeal ended
with Thursday night's verdict. ``I'm grateful for the American
judicial system and I thank the jury for exonerating me.''
   The U.S. District Court jury also cleared Miss Myerson's lover,
Carl ``Andy'' Capasso, 43, and retired state Supreme Court Justice
Hortense Gabel, 76, who handled Capasso's divorce.
   Miss Myerson, seated beside Capasso, kissed and hugged him after
jury forewoman Linda Berardi announced ``not guilty'' for each
charge in the six-count indictment.
   Several people cheered, while key government witness Sukhreet
Gabel _ daughter of Miss Myerson's co-defendant _ sat dazed several
rows behind her.
   After the jury's final announcement, Miss Myerson wiped away
tears and crossed the courtroom to hug Ms. Gabel's frail mother. She
then broke down and cried into her hands as Capasso massaged her
back and neck.
   Miss Myerson, 64, who was Miss America in 1945, had stared
intently at the jury as they entered the courtroom shortly after 8
p.m. and delivered their verdict, rejecting the prosecution's
contention thatthe three were guilty of conspiracy, mail fraud and
bribe-related charges.
   The jury had been sequestered by Judge John Keenan since Monday,
when they began weighing the evidence from the 12-week trial.
   ``I really feel that given the prosecution's case, I had no other
choice but to say not guilty,'' said the forewoman.
   Jay Goldberg, Capasso's lawyer, said, ``Had it not been Bess
Myerson, (U.S. Attorney Rudolph) Giuliani would have never brought
this case.''
   But Giuliani, whose office has rarely lost a major case,
disagreed.
   ``I think we would try this case again, sure,'' said Giuliani.
``Obviously, we're disappointed with the result.''
   Miss Myerson, the city's former cultural affairs commissioner,
was accused of trying to bribe Mrs. Gabel by giving a city job to
Sukhreet, the judge's emotionally troubled daughter. In return,
prosecutors said, the judge reduced Capasso's alimony payments with
his ex-wife, Nancy.
   Capasso, a millionaire contractor, is serving a three-year
sentence in the Lewisburg, Pa., prison for pleading guilty to
federal tax evasion charges in January.
   Before he was taken back into custody by marshals, he offered a
one-word opinion: ``Outstanding.''
   Much of the trial's focus was on Ms. Gabel, who spent nine days
on the stand testifying against her mother and reveled in the
subsequent attention and publicity.
   ``Everybody's a winner. The truth came out,'' said Ms. Gabel.
   Ms. Gabel testified how Miss Myerson began cultivating her
friendship in the summer of 1983; how her mother looked ``very sad''
when she asked about her involvement in the Capasso divorce case;
and how Miss Myerson confronted her in June 1986 during the grand
jury investigation, telling her ``you could be dangerous ... keep
your mouth shut.''
   Ms. Gabel said she was ``happy for Bess and Andy,'' a sentiment
shared by another prosecution witness _ Mayor Edward I. Koch.
   The mayor, whose once close relationship with Miss Myerson
unraveled amid the corruption charges, said simply, ``I'm glad for
her as a personal friend.''
   Koch, who benefited from Miss Myerson's friendship and celebrity
when he was an unknown congressman running for mayor in 1977, was
uncharacteristically subdued and barely looked at Miss Myerson as he
testified.
   The trial, which began Oct. 4, captured the public's imagination
with its tales of high jinks and low comedy among New York's movers
and shakers.
   While prosecutors alleged Miss Myerson tried to ``buy justice in
the courts of New York,'' her lawyers ridiculed the case as ``a soap
opera, not a criminal trial.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
