<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea-Murder     12-23 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Murder,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Focus Investigation Of U.S. Teacher's Murder On
Acquaintances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said today their investigation
into the brutal slaying of a 26-year-old American teacher is
focusing on friends and students who knew her.
   Investigators said they have questioned more than 25 teachers and
students who were acquaintances and friends of Carolyn Joyce Abel,
the Lafayette, Ind., woman found stabbed to death Tuesday.
   The Korea Herald today quoted an unidentified investigator at the
Kangnam Police Station as saying,``We suspect the murder was a crime
of passion or a personal grudge in view of its savagery.''
   Violent crime is relatively uncommon in South Korea and personal
attacks on foreigners are unusual.
   Ms. Abel was found dead in her apartment of multiple stab wounds,
including a slashed throat.
   The Herald quoted police as saying investigators believe the
attacker cut her throat after inflicting the other wounds.
   ``It seems that the attacker cut her throat to make sure she was
dead because he feared her possible survival,'' police were quoted
as saying. ``It leads us to suppose the victim knew her attacker
well.''
   Police said they questioned several Korean students who had
frequented Ms. Abel's apartment, as well as two other teachers and
three Korean male students who took a trip to a resort area with the
victim last weekend.
   The autopsy showed the victim was not sexually abused and police
said they found some valuables in the apartment, which led them to
believe robbery was not a motive.
   Ms. Abel came to Seoul in October and was one of about 25
English-language teachers at a private school, the English Language
Services. The school said she had worked in Japan before coming to
South Korea.
</TEXT>
