<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0455EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-PLO     12-23 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-PLO,0289</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Majority Of Israelis Favor Negotiations With PLO</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-four percent of Israelis favor
negotiations with the PLO, while 44 percent oppose such talks under
any circumstances, according to a poll published today.
   The findings contrast with the policy of the new coalition
government, which flatly rules out talks with the Palestine
Liberation Organization. Israel says the PLO is a terrorist
organization.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of the right-wing Likud bloc said
in presenting the government Thursday that he invited the
left-leaning Labor Party to share power because Israel needed to
present a united front against the PLO.
   The poll was conducted Tuesday and Wednesday by the Dahaf
Institute, which interviewed 653 Israeli Jews. The results were
published in the Yediot Ahronot newspaper.
   People were asked: ``Based on (PLO chief) Yasser Arafat's
statement in Geneva, and on condition that he renounces terror, are
you for or against negotiations with the PLO?''
   Twenty-one percent said they definitely backed talks, while 33
percent said they favored negotiations.
   But 24 percent said they were definitely against talks, while 20
percent simply said they opposed negotiations. Two percent were
undecided.
   The margin of error was plus or minus 2.5 percent, the institute
said.
   Dahaf pollster Mina Zemach said the 54 percent approval rate was
the highest measured by her institute.
   Similar surveys in the last two years found a support rate
ranging from 48 percent to 52 percent, while the number of those
rejecting talks fluctuated between 44 percent and 47 percent, she
said.
   In October, one month before the Israeli election, 50 percent
approved talks, while 47 percent objected and 3 percent had no
opinion, Ms. Zemach said.
</TEXT>
