<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0522EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador-Extradition     12-23 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Extradition,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Court Voids Extradition Request For Suspect In Bishop's
Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former army captain accused in
the 1980 slaying of a Roman Catholic archbishop and being held in
Miami on other charges will not face extradition to El Salvador, the
Supreme Court ruled.
   The court Thursday struck down a request for the United States to
extradite Alvaro Saravia because it said there wasn't enough
evidence linking him to the murder of Archbishop Oscar Arnulfo
Romero.
   The court also said Attorney General Giron Flores did not have
the constitutional power to ask the United States to send Saravia
back to El Salvador.
   Flores had directly asked the United States for Saravia's
extradition. The case went to the Supreme Court after Saravia's
attorney requested a hearing.
   Saravia has been jailed in Miami since November 1987, when he was
arrested for a traffic violation and authorities found he had been
in the country illegally since 1985.
   It was not clear if Thursday's ruling could result in Saravia's
release. The Salvadoran court said Saravia would not be subject to
arrest if he were sent home.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte's government accused Saravia of
arranging Romero's assassination on orders of right-wing legislator
Roberto d'Aubuisson, who denied the allegation.
   Romero, an outspoken critic of right-wing death squads, was shot
by a sniper while saying Mass in San Salvador on March 24, 1980.
   The government's accusations were based on the testimony of
Amadeo Garay Reyes, who allegedly drove the sniper to the church.
   The Supreme Court said Garay's testimony was not credible, partly
because he waited more than seven years to come forward with his
story.
</TEXT>
