<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Quake     12-23 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Quake,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Say Relief Supplies Still Jammed By Clogged Railways</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of train cars are hauling relief supplies
into Soviet Armenia daily, but railway tieups are slowing urgently
needed shipments from arriving in the earthquake-devastated region,
news reports said.
   Children traumatized by the Dec. 7 quake need psychological
counseling and thousands of victims who lost limbs need prosthetics,
the reports continued.
   Officials meanwhile began planning the reconstruction of cities,
even though one report said the leveled town of Spitak was going to
be rebuilt only a half-mile from a fault line.
   A commission of the ruling Politburo ordered all possible
transport mobilized to ship trailers to the disaster area for use as
medical stations, the official Soviet news agency Tass reported
Thursday.
   The panel found rail services in particular are ``a bottleneck
slowing measures to overcome the effects of the natural calamity,''
Tass said.
   New reports said Soviet authorities had evacuated 92,000 people
from northern Armenia, a mountainous republic bordered by Turkey.
The temblor that registered 6.9 on the Richter scale killed an
estimated 55,000 people and left 500,000 homeless.
   Tass increased the official count of ``ruined'' villages to 300,
and said 58 of them were obliterated by the quake. It also said
about 10 percent of the livestock in the rural areas died.
   Freight traffic to Armenia is increasing daily as building
materials join the relief supplies pouring into the tiny republic.
But hauling cargo from the Armenian capital Yerevan to the city of
Leninakan and other stricken areas is still a problem, Tass said.
   Rail service near the disaster area is erratic; unloading of
freight cars is quickening, but still is not fast enough, even at
1,633 cars a day, it said, estimating at least 2,000 cars must pass
through daily to fill needs.
   Armenian children, meanwhile, took up their books again in 23
temporary schools in the Crimea, hundreds of miles from their ruined
homes, Tass reported.
   Psychologists are working with victims to ease the pain of their
experience, and warned that children especially could suffer for
years to come, according to the newspaper Trud. Experts suggested it
will take 15 years to psychologically rehabilitate a generation of
Armenian children, the paper said.
   Physical rehabilitation is also looming as a massive undertaking.
Thousands of people need artificial limbs and many others were
paralyzed when they were crushed under tons of concrete, according
to Richard Schubert, president of the American Red Cross, quoted by
the Novosti news service.
   Meanwhile, an article in Trud on plans for reconstruction of the
destroyed city of Spitak raised as many questions as it answered.
   ``As shown by recent events, it sits on the intersection of two
breaks in the earth's crust. Therefore, the city practically must be
built on a new square, 500 to 600 meters (yards) from the current
one.''
   Without explaining how a move of a half-mile could make much
difference in an earthquake like that of Dec. 7, which destroyed
virtually every building in the city of 25,000, the newspaper said
Spitak and Leninakan will be placed in fields less susceptible to
earthquake, on hard rock foundations.
</TEXT>
