<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-Trade     12-23 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Trade,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Bill Heading for Final Approval</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Commons is headed toward a final vote
on the free trade agreement with the United States that is scheduled
to take effect New Year's Day.
   ``The U.S.-Canada free trade agreement is going to be put before
Parliament for a final decision before Christmas and it is going to
be put in place by Jan. 1,'' Trade Minister John Crosbie said
Thursday.
   Crosbie made the comment as he opened debate in Ottawa on the
third and final reading for the trade agreement's enabling
legislation.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Progressive Conservative Party
won a second consecutive majority government in Nov. 21 elections,
clearing the way for the trade agreement he signed with President
Reagan in January.
   The party has been using its majority in the House of Commons to
speed through the passage, but even the most drastic limits would
require deputies to stay at work until about 1 a.m. Saturday,
Christmas Day.
   Some evidently homesick members sang Christmas carols during
debate that carried past midnight Wednesday.
   A delay of days, weeks or probably even several months would not
hinder the agreement, which will phase out all remaining tariffs
between the two countries over a 10-year period.
   But supporters of the agreement say it would be embarrassing for
Canada to have to ask the United States to postpone the start of
such a major undertaking.
   The approval in the House of Commons then would allow the Senate
to complete its work next week. The Senate, which is appointed, has
promised not to oppose the trade legislation.
   The United States completed all its legislation for the agreement
in September, but it was delayed in Canada by intense opposition
that forced Mulroney to call the election last fall.
   The opposition still wants Mulroney to clarify such issues as how
much government help will be available for workers who lose their
jobs as a result of plant closings linked to the trade agreement.
   Mulroney's party has 169 of the 295 seats in the House of
Commons. The opposition Liberal Party holds 82 and the socialist New
Democratic Party 43.
</TEXT>
