<HEAD>Safety Council: 350-450 May Die in Christmas Weekend Traffic
Accidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Traffic accidents on the nation's highways during
the Christmas weekend may kill between 350 and 450 people, the
National Safety Council says.
   Last year, 389 people were killed in auto accidents over the
Christmas holiday, Barbara Carraro, a council statistician, said
Thursday.
   During a normal Friday night through Monday non-holiday period in
December an estimated 380 people die in crashes, she said.
   The council, headquarted in Chicago, said millions of Americans
would drive an estimated 11.1 billion miles between 6 p.m. Friday
and 11:59 p.m. Monday.
   The council said its projection for traffic deaths over New
Year's weekend was also 350 to 450.
