<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Vietnam-Parliament     12-23 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vietnam-Parliament,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Ends Critical Parliament Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam's Parliament adjourned its
winter session after demanding greater reform and strongly
criticizing the Communist government for the country's economic
problems, official reports seen today said.
   The government not only accepted the criticism but President Do
Muoi admitted that ``sluggish, inconsistent, perfunctory''
management had worsened the crisis, official Radio Hanoi said.
   ``Few countries in the world have followed in our country's
footsteps by patterning their 1988 scientific-technical norms after
those backward trends set some 15 to 20 years ago,'' he said.
   The 10-day session adjourned Thursday after passing 10
resolutions, including resolutions on making changes and amendments
to the constitution, Radio Hanoi said. A text of the broadcast did
not specify what changes and amendments were sought.
   In a closing speech, assembly chairman Le Quang Dao said 1989 was
the ``pivotal year'' for implementing economic reforms endorsed by
the 1986 Communist Party congress, which also ushered in more
critical thinking and ``openness'' in most aspects of Vietnamese
life. The Western-style reforms are aimed at boosting production
through decentralization of management and other measures.
   ``However, our country is facing great ordeals which require the
National Assembly, the Council of Ministers (central government),
and all the people to renovate even more profoundly and
vigorously,'' he said.
   The Vietnam News Agency called the session ``the liveliest in the
life of this country's legislative body.''
   ``Many deputies were strongly critical of the Council of
Minister's weaknesses and mistakes in handling the economy and
managing society,'' it said in a report Monday.
   They demanded more economic autonomy for local areas and
reductions of agricultural taxes they said were hindering
production. Last week, Minister of Finance Hoang Qui admitted before
the Parliament that the tax system has to be ``completely revamped.''
   In Wednesday's session, Do Muoi conceded the government's
mismanagement in a speech and said: ``I admit these shortcomings
before the National Assembly and promise to draw experience from
them.''
   He acknowledged that in per capita income terms, Vietnam is
ranked one of the poorest nations on earth.
   Do Muoi said government spending has far exceeded national income
``and has even consumed our national capital and loans from foreign
countries and does not show any signs of improvement.''
</TEXT>
