<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Finland-Crash     12-23 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Finland-Crash,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Finnish Police Believe Bomb Warning Linked To Personal Dispute</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finnish police said today they have
questioned an Arab resident in connection with a telephoned bomb
warning to the U.S. Embassy against an American airliner.
   Though some details of the warning appeared to fit the crash
Wednesday of a Pan Am jumbo jet in Scotland, police said they found
no proof of a link between the warning and the tragedy that killed
all 258 people on board and 22 people in Lockerbie.
   Seppo Tiitinen, chief of the Security Police, said the call was a
message of warning, rather than a threat.
   The U.S. Embassy was warned Dec. 5 that an Arab residing in
Finland would plant a bomb aboard an American airliner originating
from Frankfurt, West Germany, ``within a couple of weeks,'' he said.
Pan Am Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt as a Boeing 727, and
continued from London as a Boeing 747.
   The caller, who spoke English with an Arabic accent, said the
bomb would be carried aboard the aircraft by a Finnish woman, but it
was not clear if she would be a willing accomplice, Tiitinen told
the Associated Press.
   The same caller had issued bomb warnings to the Israeli and U.S.
embassies earlier this year, each time naming the would-be bomber,
Tiitinen said. The caller said the Abu Nidal group, an extremist
Palestinian organization, was behind the plan.
   Tiitinen said the identity of the caller was not certain, but
officers had spoken to the man that the caller accused of preparing
the bomb.
   ``It's a man who has been living in Finland for some time and is
married to a Finnish woman,'' he said. He declined to identify him
by name, but said he had no record of trouble with the police.
   ``We have questioned this man both in connection with earlier
threats and now after the crash in Scotland, but so far we have no
reason to believe that he has anything to do with threats or the
accident,'' Tiitinen said.
   He said police thought the calls were connected to a personal
feud between the two men. ``We think it's more a case of personal
relationships than anything else,'' Tiitinen said.
   But he denied the warnings were dismissed. ``All messages have
been taken very seriously,'' he said.
   Tiitinen said the phone warnings began in the first half of this
year to the Israeli embassy, and were similarly worded. He declined
to say how many times the embassies were called.
   Israeli embassy spokesman Ehud Eytam said a check of the
embassy's records the last four months showed no evidence of
telephoned threats.
   The U.S. Embassy referred callers to the State Department in
Washington.
   Undersecretary of State Ronald Spiers said in Washington that the
Federal Aviation Administration issued an alert after a bomb threat
was received by the Helsinki embassy Dec. 5.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
