<DOCNO> AP881223-0068 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0743EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HelicopterCrash     12-23 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Crash,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Say Fog Altered Pilot's Plan for Landing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE GIRARDEAU, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of a medical helicopter that
crashed in heavy fog, killing a young patient and two medical
workers, may have been trying to head for an airport southwest of
town, officials said.
   The Bell Long Ranger Model 206L crashed in a muddy soybean field
before dawn Thursday, killing James Rhodes, 7, who had suffered a
broken neck in Marion, Ill., hours earlier and was being airlifted
to St. Francis Hospital.
   Also killed were flight nurse Karen Scherer, 26, and respiratory
therapist Julie Huttegger, 22.
   Pilot Sheldon Rudzek, 39, was in stable condition today at St.
Francis, hospital officials said. He underwent surgery for multiple
fractures, including broken legs, and suffered second- and
third-degree burns over 15 percent of his body.
   Rudzek was in radio contact with St. Francis and reported no
trouble during the 30-minute, 40-mile flight from Marion, where he
picked James up, emergency room officials said. Contact was lost
just before the aircraft went down about three miles from the
hospital around 4:30 a.m.
   A farmer found the craft's wreckage nearly three hours later.
   Skies were clear when the helicopter, owned by Air Evac in West
Plains, left Marion, said hospital spokeswoman Mary Spell.
   Cape Girardeau, a city of about 35,000 people about 110 miles
south of St. Louis on the Mississippi River, ``just got socked in
(by fog) real quick,'' said Spell. ``The last that was heard was
when Air Evac 3 was circling the Cape Girardeau airport in really
heavy fog.''
   Two Federal Aviation Administration inspectors were at the crash
site Thursday and a National Transportation Safety Board
investigator was sent to the scene, said FAA spokesman Bob
Raynesford.
   Air Evac owner Bill Chritton said the company has minimum weather
standards for its flights but that final decisions are left to
pilots.
   ``No one requires the pilot to fly. Any operator in the United
States would have flown this particular mission,'' Chritton said in
defending Rudzek's decision to make the flight.
   The accident was the third crash by an Air Evac helicopter
resulting in death or injury in three years.
</TEXT>
