<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Judge-Homosexuals     12-23 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Judge-Homosexuals,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Apologizes For Statements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apology from a judge who said he gave a killer a
lenient sentence because the victims were ``queers'' did little to
ease the demands of gay rights activists and others who want him
removed from the bench.
   ``He has cast a reasonable doubt into the minds of people across
this nation about Dallas justice,'' said William Waybourn, president
of the Dallas Gay Alliance.
   ``He has raised the question of his judicial fitness and ability
to be impartial. This question cannot be answered with a simple
apology.''
   State District Judge Jack Hampton apologized on Thursday for a
``poor choice of words.''
   Hampton told the Dallas Times Herald last week that he sentenced
Richard Lee Bednarski, 18, to 30 years in prison instead of life on
Nov. 28, in part because the two victims were homosexuals who
``wouldn't have been killed if they hadn't been cruising the streets
picking up teen-age boys.''
   ``I don't much care for queers cruising the streets picking up
teen-age boys. I've got a teen-age boy,'' the judge told the
newspaper.
   Hampton's statements outraged the gay community, which filed a
complaint with the Texas Commission on Judicial Conduct that could
lead to his removal.
   Elected officials, including State Treasurer Ann Richards and
U.S. Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., also criticized Hampton, as did
church leaders, some with large gay congregations, who asked him to
repudiate the statements.
   The judge's apology was addressed to the ministers.
   ``I did not mean to condemn the homosexual community generally
and I used a poor choice of words and I'm sorry about that,''
Hampton said. He said he ``did not intend to state that any victim
of crime was entitled to less fair treatment.''
   The judge said Thursday he considered a variety of factors in
sentencing Bednarski, including the defendant's age, his lack of a
criminal record and ``what the victims were doing out there, but not
their lifestyle.''
   Hampton is up for re-election in 1990.
   ``His apology to eight citizens is not enough. His apology to
every citizen is not enough,'' Waybourn said. ``Bednarski, the
executor-murderer, cannot get off by apologizing. Neither can Judge
Hampton.''
   About 50 sign-carrying demonstrators gathered in support of
Hampton outside the courthouse.
   ``I think that is very generous of Judge Hampton. I think that
merely shows how fair he is,'' attorney Bill McKnight said of the
apology. ``I do not know who bestowed sacred cow status on the
homosexuals of this community _ I don't think they deserve it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
