<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Palestinians     12-23 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palestinians,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Leader Calls For Military Action Against Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian leader said the yearlong uprising
against Israeli occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip should be
escalated with military action.
   Salim Zaanoun, deputy speaker of the Palestine National Council,
the PLO's parliament-in-exile, suggested Thursday night that the
uprising take ``serious action to launch military operations here
and there.''
   He differentiated between military action and terrorism, saying
military action ``is sanctioned by international law as long as our
land is occupied.''
   Zaanoun was addressing a rally at the Palestine Liberation
Organization office in Kuwait to mark the 21st anniversary of the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, a leftist guerrilla
group led by George Habash.
   The Popular Front is united with Yasser Arafat's mainstream Fatah
and other groups under the PLO umbrella.
   Zaanoun cautioned against expecting too much from the recently
initiated PLO-U.S. dialogue.
   ``The United States has lost too much and wants to compensate for
this loss by this theatrical piece,'' he said.
   ``We have to pursue an even-handed approach to avoid expecting
too much from the diplomatic moves and devote part of our effort for
struggle and perpetuation of the momentum of the uprising.''
   He said the uprising should ``continue and become more vigorous.''
   Kuwait's Al-Qabas daily quoted Arafat, the PLO chairman, as
ruling out acceptance of anywhere but Jerusalem as capital of the
Palestinian state.
   ``A Palestinian state with holy Jerusalem as its capital is our
demand, to which we will stick,'' he was quoted as saying in an
interview.
   He also rejected the notion of demilitarizing the Palestinian
state ``unless Israel is disarmed,'' the newspaper said.
   ``We should be equal,'' he was quoted as saying. ``We want a
completely sovereign state. Why should the Palestinians abandon part
of their sovereignty and Israel not be asked to do so?''
   The United States initiated dialogue with the PLO after Arafat
explicitly recognized Israel's right to exist and renounced
terrorism. Arafat said he had not ``succumbed'' to U.S. conditions
so the talks could start.
   ``I did not change my policy. It was the United States which
changed its policy,'' he said.
   Asked what prompted the U.S. government to change its stand,
Arafat said: ``Undoubtedly it was the attitude of 154 member states
of the United Nations who decided to shift the venue of the U.N.
General Assembly debate on the Palestinian question to Geneva.''
   This move was taken after Washington denied Arafat a visa, thus
barring him from addressing the General Assembly in New York.
</TEXT>
