<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Pro-Israeli Militia In South Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unidentified guerrillas attacked
Israeli-backed militiamen with rockets and machine guns in south
Lebanon today. Police said two militiamen were wounded.
   A police spokesman said the guerrillas launched two attacks at
first light against positions manned by the Israeli-armed South
Lebanon Army near the villages of Beit Leef and Beit Yahoun.
   The attackers ``withdrew to safety behind a fierce mortar
barrage,'' said the spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations.
   The two wounded South Lebanon Army men were admitted to a
hospital in Marjayoun, a Christian town inside Israel's
self-proclaimed ``security zone'' in south Lebanon, the spokesman
said.
   Israel established the 6-to-10-mile-wide strip when it withdrew
the bulk of its occupation army from south Lebanon in the summer of
1985.
   The zone, patrolled by South Lebanon Army and Israeli troops,
serves as a buffer against cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</TEXT>
