<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NotReallyDead     12-23 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Not Really Dead,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Wrongly Declared Dead in Computer Error</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXMOOR, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who survived a heart attack and
spent three months in the hospital with an infection came home to
find a letter saying she died.
   ``It doesn't seem fair that the state of Illinois keeps insisting
that I'm dead when I have fought so hard to live,'' Eugenia Konrath,
49, said Wednesday.
   The letter from the state Department of Public Aid computer said
she was no longer eligible for medical assistance because she is
dead. Despite the letter, which she opened in September, she
continues to receive benefits.
   Ms. Konrath said she received a call Wednesday that the problem
had been located and was being corrected. But she said she's heard
that story before.
   ``When I call they tell me they are sorry and that everything has
been taken care of,'' Ms. Konrath said. ``I take a deep breath and
then here comes another letter.''
   ``After I got the second letter, I thought it had to be some kind
of joke. The third letter was no joke.''
   Sandra Lynn, a spokeswoman for public aid, said she only knows of
one notice sent to Ms. Konrath. She said the letter resulted from a
computer error.
   Ms. Konrath, who has undergone surgery six times in the past
year, said her medical expenses have totaled more than $100,000
during that period.
   Ms. Konrath said she has diabetes and has been disabled by a
heart condition. Infectious arthritis required the amputation of a
toe earlier this year and the infection damaged her bones, forcing
her to use a wheelchair, she said.
</TEXT>
