<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland     12-23 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Demonstrate for Freedom for Colleague</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of students demonstrated in a
southern city to demand the release before Christmas of a peace
activist jailed for refusing to comply with a court order,
opposition spokesmen said today.
   The demonstration was held Thursday in the southern city of Opole
on behalf of Krzysztof Galinski, 23, who was taken by police from
his class at a technical college Dec. 13, spokesmen from the Freedom
and Peace group said.
   They said Galinski refused to carry out 80 hours compulsory labor
he was sentenced to in March after police searched his apartment and
found copies of leaflets connected with a planned opposition
``happening.''
   For failing to perform the work, a court in September ordered
Galinski jailed one month, leading to his December arrest, Freedom
and Peace said.
   ``All this proves that the democratization and liberalization in
Poland is a farce,'' said a statement signed by Freedom and Peace
activist Anna Niedzwiecka.
   ``The government talks to Lech Walesa and lets him go to Paris,
which is very good, but at the same time a huge majority of Peace
and Freedom participants are refused passports, imprisoned or
threatened with arrest. ... This is the real image of perestroika in
Poland.''
   Freedom and Peace is a banned nationwide group of mostly young
people opposed to the military, the draft and nuclear power.
   A spokesman for the Interior Ministry in Warsaw, asked about
Galinski's case, said he was not familiar with it.
</TEXT>
