<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Ship     12-23 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Ship,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Believed Caused By Fireworks Burns Ship; One Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire that may have been caused by
exploding fireworks swept through a ship carrying more than 120
people today, and the coast guard said one person died and at least
three people were injured.
   Passengers and crew abandoned the 1441-ton Dona Conchita five
miles off Panay island, 250 miles southeast of Manila, said coast
guard Lt. Enrico Coching. Coching said a 66-year-old woman was the
only confirmed fatality.
   He said three people were injured, two with severe burns.
   There were widely varying reports on how many people were aboard
the ship. Coching said 206 passengers and crew had been rescued.
   Bob Gothong, executive vice president of the Carlos A. Gothong
Shipping Lines, which owned the vessel, said company records
indicated the ship was carrying 107 passengers and 48 crew members.
In Cebu City, Alfredo Gothong, a company director, said the ship was
carrying 128 passengers and crew.
   Alfredo Gothong said two people, including a pregnant woman,
managed to reach shore and checked into a hospital with broken bones.
   The rest were rescued by the ship, Our Lady of Hope, which rushed
to the area to help, he said, and the company was ``90 percent
certain'' that all those aboard had been accounted for.
   The coast guard said the Dona Conchita, still afire hours after
the blaze broke out, drifted into shallow water and ran aground on
Panay island about five miles northeast of Roxas City.
   Survivors said they were roused from sleep by screams of fellow
passengers and jumped into the Sibuyan Sea. ``There was fire,'' said
Pedro Adiola, 51. We jumped into the water and swam.'' He said it
took nearly two hours for the first rescue vessels to reach the area.
   The Dona Conchita left New Washington on Panay island at 2 a.m.
today bound for Palompon on Leyte island and caught fire three hours
later, company officials said.
   Bob Gothong said the crew radioed that firecracker explosions
were heard and then a blaze started in the vessel's cargo hold. The
fireworks cargo ``must have been loaded illegally, declared as
something else,'' he said.
   He did not know how many fireworks had been aboard but said ``the
crew reported a lot of explosions.''
   The skipper radioed a distress signal and ordered passengers and
crew to abandon ship at 5 a.m., he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
