<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolygamistTrial     12-23 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polygamist Trial,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Polygamist Clan Members Convicted Of Reduced Homicide Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COALVILLE, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three polygamist clan members wept and
hugged their families after a jury convicted them on reduced
homicide charges in the shooting death of a law officer killed
during a 13-day siege.
   Clan patriarch Addam Swapp, 27, and his brother-in-law, John
Timothy Singer, 22, were convicted of manslaughter Thursday in the
death of state Corrections Lt. Fred House. Swapp's brother, Jonathan
Swapp, 21, was convicted of negligent homicide.
   House was killed during a Jan. 28 shootout that ended the clan's
armed standoff with police at their Marion farm. The impasse had
begun 13 days earlier when Addam Swapp, who said he was guided by a
divine revelation, bombed a nearby Mormon chapel.
   The three had been charged with second-degree murder in the death
of House, who was struck by a rifle bullet as he directed police
dogs to attack the Swapp brothers in an arrest attempt coordinated
by an FBI hostage rescue team.
   The maximum penalty for second-degree murder is five years to
life in prison. For manslaughter, the maximum term is five years,
and for negligent homicide one year in jail and a $2,500 fine.
   Third District Judge Michael Murphy scheduled sentencing for Jan.
20.
   The trio was somber and observers silent as the verdicts were
read. But after court adjourned, Addam Swapp wept as he leaned over
a rail to embrace his wives, sisters, sons and brother-in-law.
Jonathan Swapp also embraced his wife, whom he married in a
jailhouse ceremony in November.
   ``I'm pleased and disappointed by the verdict, disappointed
because we have an abiding conviction of the innocence of our
clients,'' said John Bucher, Addam Swapp's attorney.
   Fred Metos, Singer's attorney, said his client was relieved
because he escaped a lengthy prison term. Earl Spafford, Jonathan
Swapp's lawyer, said he ``couldn't be happier'' with the jury's
decision.
   Addam Swapp was seriously wounded by an FBI sharpshooter during
the 20-second exchange in January. He said he never fired, and
agents differed as to whether he was shouldering his rifle when he
was shot.
   Singer acknowledged firing the shot that killed House but said he
was shooting at the dogs. Jonathan Swapp also admitted firing his
rifle but said he was trying to keep officers from shooting his
brother again.
   Prosecutor Dave Schwendiman and fellow prosecutor Creighton
Horton said they were neither surprised nor disappointed by the
verdict.
   ``It was simply a tough case (for the jury),'' Horton said.
``This should put to rest the incident at Marion.''
   Ann House, widow of the slain officer, attended the nine-day
trial.
   ``What was missing in this trial about the killing of Lt. Fred
House was Fred as a real person. He was and still is a model of
character, of responsible behavior,'' she wrote in a statement
following the verdict.
   Mrs. House, whose husband had four black belts in karate, said:
``His students and fellow workers respected this dedication, loyalty
and team support. The Singer-Swapp affair is such a contrast in
values.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
