<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0904EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Namibia     12-23 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Namibia,0553</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Counterinsurgency Unit To Be Scrapped Prior To Independence</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-UN-Namibia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police counterinsurgency unit active
in the war against pro-independence guerrillas will be disbanded as
a goodwill gesture following the agreement to end South African rule
over Namibia, a police official said today.
   The unit, with a reputation for tough and sometimes controversial
tactics, is known as Koevoet _ the Afrikaans word for ``crowbar.''
   Chief Inspector Kierie du Rand said the unit would be phased out
gradually starting April 1, the beginning of a seven-month
transition process leading to elections for a Naimibian national
assembly.
   Koevoet members have been involved in numerous court cases over
the years related to allegations of brutality against black
civilians in the northern war zone. Authorities have declined to
disclose the number of men serving in the multiracial unit, but
Foreign Minister Pik Botha of South Africa said Thursday that
overall police strength in Namibia would be reduced from 8,300 to
7,000.
   Botha was speaking at a news conference after joining Angolan and
Cuban officials in signing agreements at the United Nations to bring
about independence in Namibia and remove Cuban troops from
neighboring Angola.
   Koevoet played a principal role in countering incursions by
Angola-based insurgents of the South-West African People's
Organization, which began a bush war against South African rule in
1966.
   SWAPO is favored to win the Nov. 1 elections, but it is likely to
be opposed by a multiracial coalition of parties participating in
the current, South African-installed transitional government.
   Dirk Mudge, a white moderate who serves on the transitional
Cabinet, today urged an active campaign to ``ensure that political
power remains in responsible hands.'' He said there should be no
turning back from the United Nations' independence plan, known as
Resolution 435.
   ``In spite of all the risks that may be involved in the
implementation of Resolution 435, the failure of the peace effort
will have serious, even disastrous, consequences that may include
military confrontation,'' he said.
   South Africa's defense minister, Gen. Magnus Malan, told
reporters in New York that South Africa, under the agreement signed
Thursday, would halt military assistance to UNITA _ the pro-Western
rebel movement fighting Angola's Marxist government.
   However, Malan said South Africa would maintain a friendly
relationship with UNITA and also expected Angola to close African
National Congress guerrilla bases on its territory. The ANC wages a
bombing and sabotage campaign in South Africa aimed at undermining
the white-controlled government.
   ``Should the Cubans launch a new offensive against UNITA, South
Africa would not sit back with folded arms,'' Malan said.
   SWAPO, in a statement issued in Luanda, Angola, and reported by
the Mozambican news agency AIM, hailed Thursday's agreement as a
milestone but criticized proposals by Western countries to reduce by
more than half the planned 7,500-member U.N. monitoring force for
Namibia.
   SWAPO said the smaller force would be unable to monitor the
movements of South African military and police units, including
Koevoet, which is described as ``internationally famed for its
atrocities.''
   SWAPO said South Africa would try to use these security forces
``to create a climate of intimidation and insecurity and thereby to
influence the outcome of the Namibian independence elections in
favor of its surrogates.''
</TEXT>
