<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Boycott     12-23 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Boycott,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Merchants Hit Hard By Boycott Protesting Resegregation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consumer boycott launched by
blacks to protest the revival of municipal segregation laws caused
huge Christmas-season losses for merchants in Boksburg, a local
business leader said today.
   Johan Viljoen, chairman of the Boksburg Chamber of Commerce,
estimated that shopowners lost more than $420,000 during a four-week
boycott protesting the reinstatement of ``whites only'' status at
parks and other public facilities.
   Many businesses in the industrial town east of Johannesburg would
be unable to recover their losses and some were likely to close
soon, Viljoen said in a telephone interview. Sales at some clothing
and furniture stores were down by as much as 80 percent, he said.
   The resegregation campaign was undertaken by town council members
of the far-right Conservative Party, who gained power in Boksburg
and dozens of other municipalities in Oct. 26 election.
   Residents of black and mixed-race communities neighboring
Boksburg _ who outnumber the 85,000 white residents by more than
3-to-1 _ said they would grant the town council its wish for a
``White Christmas'' by staying out of the central business district.
   On Thursday, developers of a $11 million shopping mall planned
for Boksburg announced the project was shelved because of the city's
bad business climate.
   The major tenant would have been the OK Bazaar retail company.
Its chief executive, Gordon Hood, said business at his company's
existing store in Boksburg had declined by 49 percent in the past
month.
   A week ago, developers of another proposed shopping mall for
Boksburg announced that their plans were being shelved until
conditions in the town ``return to normal.''
   The Boksburg council thus far has refused to back down, despite
intense criticism from the government and local business groups.
   The Conservatives have accused the government of hypocrisy and
challenged President P.W. Botha's National Party to repeal the
Separate Amenities Act, which allows local officials to segregate
public amenities. The government thus far has made no move to repeal
the law and has not pushed for integration of whites-only facilities
in towns controlled by National Party councils.
   ``The whole thing has been ripped out of proportion by the
misinformation campaign of the media,'' said a Conservative Party
leader, Koos van der Merwe.
   ``Our promises were made within the Separate Amenities Act and
the voters knew what they were voting for.''
</TEXT>
