<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SkinnerProfile 1stLd-Writethru a0413 12-23 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Skinner Profile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0413,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush's Transportation Nominee: `Sam The Hammer'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, Skinner headed, to show he headed Illinois
campaign.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Samuel Skinner was an assistant U.S.
attorney, says Illinois Gov. James Thompson, he didn't quite fit
into the ``velvet hammer'' school of prosecutors. Instead, Thompson
recalls, ``he was just a hammer.''
   Skinner, 50, once Thompson's top deputy and the man who succeeded
him as U.S. attorney in Chicago, was named by President-elect Bush
on Thursday to become secretary of transportation.
   Skinner headed Bush's presidential campaigns in Illinois both in
1980 and this year, and since 1984 has been chairman of the Regional
Transportation Authority of Northeastern Illinois, the nation's
second-largest transportation system.
   But the nickname ``Sam the Hammer,'' earned in those
corruption-busting days with Thompson in the 1970s, still follows
him.
   ``Usually you call someone a velvet hammer,'' Thompson said in a
recent interview. ``There was no velvet encasing Skinner.''
   ``He is very aggressive, and very determined to succeed in
whatever he does,'' Thompson said.
   ``Personally, I find him to be one of the brightest and most
hard-working individuals I've come across in government,'' said
Gregory Baise, Illinois tranportation director.
   ``What he will bring is an ability to bring to President Bush a
coherent agenda ... for a national infrastructure plan,'' Baise said.
   From the other side of the political aisle, Sen. Alan Dixon,
D-Ill., said: ``He's an absolutely honorable man of the deepest
personal integrity ... a very responsive person. He's an easy man to
deal with.''
   But Skinner, who is also a senior partner in the Chicago law
office of Sidley & Austin, has drawn fire from Sen. Howard
Metzenbaum, D-Ohio.
   Metzenbaum said Wednesday the Senate should not vote to confirm
Skinner without investigating ``why (he) failed to pursue
allegations of fraudulent testing of NutraSweet,'' the artificial
sweetener, against the G.D. Searle Co. _ and later joined the firm
that defended Searle in the case.
   Skinner's office issued a statement saying he ``conducted himself
in accordance with Department of Justice guidelines in the matter
mentioned by Sen. Metzenbaum.''
   Skinner served as first assistant U.S. attorney in Chicago from
1968 to 1975, and became Thompson's trusted friend. They hatched the
idea for the office's Special Investigations Division, and Thompson
made Skinner the division's first chief.
   Skinner built a reputation for toughness during one of Illinois'
biggest federal corruption trials: the bribery case of former Gov.
Otto Kerner, who was convicted in 1973.
   He is a two-time recipient of the Department of Justice
Outstanding Service Award.
   Skinner's current agency funnels federal and state money to local
transit agencies and oversees the Chicago Transit Authority, which
operates city buses and suways; suburban bus systems; and commuter
trains that run between Chicago and the suburbs.
   Skinner ``really runs, with the help of his board, a first class
transit system,'' Thompson said.
   In 1975, when Thompson left the office for the governor's chair,
Skinner was appointed U.S. attorney by President Ford.
   In 1983, he was appointed by President Reagan to the President's
Commission on Organized Crime, which he served as vice chairman.
   Skinner received an undergraduate degree in accounting from the
University of Illinois in 1960.
   He served in the U.S. Army and earned a law degree from DePaul
University in Chicago in 1966. Skinner, who was born in Springfield,
Ill., is married and has three children.
</TEXT>
