<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1021EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Adamson     12-23 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Adamson,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arizona Law Overturned, Sentence Reversed in Bolles Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arizona's death penalty law is
unconstitutional, a federal appeals court ruled, giving new hope to
about 85 condemned prisoners.
   The 7-4 ruling Thursday by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
reversed a death sentence in the 1976 car-bombing murder of a
Phoenix newspaper reporter.
   The ruling found that the death penalty law violated the right to
a jury trial by letting the trial judge decide whether a murder was
a capital crime. The court also said the law improperly required the
defendant to justify leniency and did not allow consideration of all
pertinent evidence favoring leniency.
   If it stands, the ruling would overturn all death sentences
issued in Arizona since the law was passed in 1973.
   In a separate 6-5 vote, the court ruled that even if the law had
been valid, John Adamson's death sentence was improper because the
sentencing judge had previously ruled that a prison sentence was
appropriate for the murder, and imposed a death sentence only after
Adamson violated a plea agreement requiring him to testify against
two other men.
   It was the second time the court overturned the death sentence of
Adamson, who admitted planting the bomb in June 1976 that killed Don
Bolles, an investigative reporter for The Arizona Republic. The
Supreme Court reversed the first ruling and reinstated Adamson's
death sentence last year.
   Arizona Attorney General Bob Corbin said he would appeal
Adamson's case to the high court, and denounced the appeals court.
   ``You cannot get a death penalty case through the 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals ... because the majority of the judges are
anti-death penalty,'' Corbin said.
   Timothy Foley, one of Adamson's lawyers, said the ruling affirms
the right to have a jury decide a defendant's fate, ``rather than a
judge who's subject to retention elections and political pressure.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1024EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--MailHoard     12-23 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Mail Hoard,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mailman Pleads Guilty to Keeping Mail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A letter carrier accused of hoarding five
tons of mostly junk mail at his home faces up to 10 years in prison
at sentencing Feb. 7.
   William E. Ryan of Milton, a 15-year postal employee, pleaded
guilty Wednesday to two counts of obstructing mail delivery.
Prosecutors dropped eight other counts in exchange. The charges also
carry fines of up to $500,000.
   The mail, mostly advertising circulars, give-away offers,
magazines, free samples and other bulk mail, was discovered in his
home, in a shed and scattered in woods nearby. Some of the mail was
two to three years old.
   ``He didn't come in to explain,'' said Pensacola Postmaster Ben
Jasek. ``He didn't appeal (his firing), nothing.''
   Officials used a front-end loader to scoop up the mail, some of
it wet and moldy and beyond delivery.
  
</TEXT>
