<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DesperateAddict     12-23 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Desperate Addict,0370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Throws Chairs Through Police Precinct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A crack cocaine addict was so desperate to be
treated for his drug dependency that he smashed the windows at two
police stations to draw attention to himself, officials say.
   ``This case smacks you in the face because here is a guy who
obviously wanted to be helped,'' said Criminal Court Judge John
Moore, who helped the addict, Alexis Vega, 34, to get treatment.
   ``This case dramatizes the critical need for treatment upon
demand for all individuals addicted to drugs,'' said Bronx District
Attorney Paul Gentile.
   Vega's efforts to find treatment began after his wife and
8-month-old son left him last summer, according to accounts today in
the New York Post and The New York Times.
   First, he visited hospitals and treatment centers, but was told
there was no room.
   Gentile and police confirmed that on one occasion the man spoke
to the desk sergeant at a station house in the Williamsbridge
section of the Bronx.
   ``I told him I had a problem and was seeking some help,'' Vega
said. ``I could see they weren't going to arrest me or help. So I
reached into my pockets and pulled out some stuff and put it on the
desk, right in front of them.''
   A hypodermic needle and two empty crack vials was enough to shock
the officers, he said.
   ``They grabbed me, roughed me up a little, put the handcuffs on a
little too tight, the usual stuff,'' Vega said.
   But when he was brought before a judge on misdemeanor charges, he
was freed and his pleas to be enrolled in a treatment program were
ignored, he said.
   Finally, breaking the windows at two police stations got him
thrown into jail, into Moore's courtroom and finally into a
treatment program after the judge made a call on his behalf.
   Luis Sierra, a staff member for the center's operator, the Way
Out Church Ministries Inc., said Vega had ``lucked out.''
   ``We have a capacity of 58 men and a waiting list of 600 and
there was one vacancy left when the judge called me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
