<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Tinbergen 1stLd-Writethru   12-23 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Tinbergen, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0504,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nobel Prize Winner For Medicine, Nikolaas Tinbergen, Dead At 81</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to ADD that Tinbergen died Wednesday.
Pickup 3rd graf pvs, ``Born in...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nikolaas Tinbergen, a Dutch-born British
zoologist who won the Nobel Prize for Medicine in 1973, has died of
an apparent stroke, his widow said today. He was 81.
   Elizabeth A. Rutten said in a telephone interview that her
husband of 56 years had ``quite reasonably recovered'' from a first
stroke in 1983. He died Wednesday shortly after apparently suffering
another stroke at his Oxford home.
   Born in The Hague in 1907, Tinbergen studied at universities in
Leiden in the Netherlands, in Vienna, Austria, and at Yale
University.
   He gained prominence in the late 1930s as one of the founders of
ethology, the branch of biology that studies animal behavior. During
World War II, he was detained by the occupying German forces at a
detention camp in the Netherlands.
   After a pre-war spell with Konrad Lorenz, the noted German
zoologist, he was appointed professor of experimental zoology at
Leiden University in 1947.
   Two years later, he became an ethology lecturer at Oxford
University, where he wrote ``The Study of Instinct,'' considered the
first handbook on ethology ever published. He was a professor in
animal behavior at Oxford from 1966 to 1974, and a professor
emeritus there until his death.
   Tinbergen, who became a British citizen in 1955, was a prolific
writer and an accomplished maker of nature films.
   He shared the 1973 Nobel Prize for Physiology or Medicine with
Lorenz and Austrian zoologist Karl von Frisch for their
``discoveries in the field of the organization and occurrence of
individual and social behavioral patterns'' in the animal world.
   The 1973 prize was a new departure for the Nobel committee,
acknowledging for the first time major advances in man's
understanding of sociobiology, especially in the behavioral science
known as ethology.
   ``At one stroke, they (the three laureates) explained some of the
most remarkable examples of the fine control of elaborate patterns
of behavior by external stimuli known to science, sometimes learned,
sometimes not, while leaving in no doubt the crucial importance of
genetic differences in understanding the development of behavior,''
the British magazine Science said of their award.
   Tinbergen's elder brother, Jan, won the first-ever Nobel Prize
for Economics in 1969.
   Tinbergen is survived by his widow, two sons and three daughters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0087 </DOCNO>
