<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AutoShowDressup     12-23 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Show Dressup,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Detroit Dresses Up Old Buildings For Auto Show Visitors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agency is spending $70,000 on awnings, flags
and other improvements to dress up dilapidated buildings for
convention visitors, but neighborhood leaders say the city should
worry more about substance than image.
   The Downtown Development Authority, funded by the city and
special taxes on businesses, is paying for the cosmetic changes to
three buildings prior to the North American International Auto Show
in early January.
   ``You always open yourself up to criticism because if these
buildings were viable and occupied this wouldn't be necessary,''
said Alex Pollock, a city planner who worked on the trimmings. ``But
if the city is going to hope to get this (auto) show repeated, we
have to make a sincere effort to correct some of the less
presentable parts of downtown.''
   The abandoned Tuller and Heritage hotels and Detroit Metropolitan
Building near Detroit's Grand Circus Park echo better days with new
awnings over blank windows, spruced up entrance canopies, paint
jobs, flags and banners. The new fixings will not be taken down
after the convention.
   Neighborhood leaders say the money could be better spent.
   ``All that glitters isn't gold,'' said Cheryl Allen, an officer
of the Michigan Avenue Community Organization. ``That $70,000 used
in our neighborhood would probably (rehabilitate) five complete
homes, top to bottom. Then you would have five families in liveable
homes and looking at a future here.''
</TEXT>
