<2ND_LINE>PM-Crack Eaters,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officers Accused of Feeding Drug Dealer Crack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police officers accused of forcing a drug
dealer to eat 20 pieces of crack have been ordered to stand trial on
assault charges.
   Ricardo Darbins, 22, and Cedric Scott, 27, were also charged
along with six fellow officers with conspiracy and entry without
permission. They were accused of breaking into crack houses without
a warrant in order to terrorize occupants.
   ``I certainly have no sympathy for dope dealers,'' District Judge
R. Patrick Donahue said Thursday after a preliminary hearing. But he
said the officers tried to do ``something legal in an illegal way.''
   Steven Johnson, 26, testified that officers with guns drawn broke
into his house, where he had 20 bags of crack on a living room
table, and forced him to eat cocaine. He testified one officer said,
``I'm going to make you addicted to crack.''
   A witness in an apartment across the hall testified to
overhearing someone say, ``Eat this. ... If you don't I'll take you
to jail,'' followed by laughter.
   Johnson was treated at a hospital for an overdose. Prosecutors
said he may have saved his life after the police left by drinking
vinegar to induce vomiting.
   The alleged unreported raids on crack houses were made just
before dawn on Feb. 21.
   Defense attorneys said the action resulted from frustation in the
battle against the city's drug trade. ``When police officers start
playing it very, very, very safe, the city becomes very unsafe,''
said Thomas Howard, Scott's attorney.
   The eight officers have been suspended without pay since August
and are free on $10,000 bail each. Darbins and Scott face up to 15\
years in prison if convicted; the rest could receive up to 5\ years.
</TEXT>
