<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Crash 1stLd-Writethru   12-23 0766</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0530,0783</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Link Pan Am Disaster To Radical Palestinians</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th graf pvs, ``In a...'' to UPDATE with
State Department comment. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``Arens,
interviewed...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Moshe Arens today linked the
crash of a Pan Am jet in Scotland to Palestinian factions. An
Israeli newspaper and terror experts blamed Syrian-backed radical
groups opposed to the U.S.-PLO talks.
   The daily English-language newspaper The Nation quoted
unidentified Western intelligence sources as saying the
Syrian-backed Ahmed Jibril group was responsible. It said
investigators believed that at least one person aboard could be
identified as belonging to Jibril's Popular Front for the Liberation
of Palestine-General Command group.
   Israeli officials bitterly opposed the U.S. decision earlier this
month to open a dialogue with the Palestine Liberation Organization
after its chief, Yasser Arafat, renounced terrorism and recognized
Israel's right to exist.
   On Thursday, a senior PLO official, Mahmoud Abbas, said in Cairo,
Egypt, that it was ``nonsensical'' to link Palestinians to the crash.
   In a report from London today, a correspondent for Israel radio's
English service said passengers aboard the Pan Am plane included two
members of a secret U.S. State Department team returning from
Lebanon where they had negotiated for the release of American
hostages.
   A State Department official in Washington said today that two
Americans on the plane were involved in diplomatic security, one at
the U.S. Embassy in Nicosia, Cyprus, and another at the U.S. Embassy
in Beirut, Lebanon, and two other diplomats from the Beirut embassy.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, denied that
two of the Americans had been involved in talks on American hostages.
   Arens, interviewed in Hebrew on Israel radio, said that ``based
on our assumptions, and those of our experts, this is an operation
of international terror, apparently Arab international terror.''
   Arens attacked the U.S.-PLO dialogue, saying ``such steps would
only strenghten the wave of terror and encourage terror groups and
activities.''
   Israel radio said two Israelis died in the crash, and Israel had
sent a top police official to London to assist in the investigation.
   Ariel Merari, a senior researcher in terrorism at Tel Aviv
University's Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies, said the attack
was apparently staged to block the U.S.-PLO talks.
   ``Radical Palestinian factions, who declared Arafat a traitor,
are the most likely candidates,'' Merari said in an interview.
``They likely had Syrian or Libyan backing.''
   He said Palestinian groups were ``responsible for half of the
mid-air plane bombings in the last 20 years'' and said Jibril's
group in particular had a ``rich history'' of such attacks.
   He said Jibril's followers were linked to the Feb. 21, 1970,
downing of Swissair plane by a in-flight explosion, and on the same
day unsuccessfully attempted to blow up an Austrian airlines plane.
   In 1971 and 1972, Jibril guerrillas made three attempts to
detonate a bomb in Israel's El-Al planes, two in Rome and one in
London. In one case, the bomb was hidden in a record player.
   ``They usually use naive carriers, people who don't suspect. In
the case of Jibril, female tourists were befriended by Jibril's men
and asked to take a parcel to Israel,'' he said.
   Merari noted that a ``barometer bomb,'' which is equipped with an
altitude-sensitive detonator and activated by air pressure, was
found concealed in a radio when 13 Palestinians were detained in
October during raids in West Germany. Officials there said the
suspects belonged to Jibril's group.
   The Nation said that the leader of the Jibril cell in West
Germany, Hafez Kassem Khalkamony, told his interrogators the group
planned attacks on civilian aircraft. A similar report was carried
by Israel Television's military correspondent Thursday.
   The paper quoted West German intelligence sources as saying they
believe a Jibril guerrilla boarded the Pan Am plane in Frankfurt.
   It said the man board the plane ``with a briefcase packed with
Syrian-supplied explosives that cannot be detected by routine
security methods'' and fled when the flight was in transit in
London, leaving the briefcase behind.
   Meanwhile, the head of the Israeli Pilots Association Yitzhak
Gonen said he warned the London-based International Pilots
Association in a telephone call earlier this month about a possible
attack by radical Palestinians.
   ``I spoke with them a day after the U.S. decision to start talks
with Arafat (Dec. 15) and warned them that we may expect an increase
in attacks by groups opposing these talks,'' Gonen said. ``It was a
general warning, because I did not have any precise information.''
</TEXT>
