<HEAD>PRECEDE: MOSCOW</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Office Confirms Son And Grandson Of President-Elect To Go To
Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush's son and grandson will
travel to Soviet Armenia on Christmas Day to help distribute
American aid to earthquake victims, Bush's office confirmed today.
   In Moscow, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov
told the official Tass news agency that John E. Bush and George P.
Bush ``will participate in a ceremony of transferring to Armenia
relief aid from the United States.''
   Jeb Bush, 35, a Miami real estate developer, and his son, George,
12, will spend about six hours in Yerevan, the Armenian capital, on
Christmas Day, said the transition office. They leave New York on
Saturday, arriving in the Soviet Union on Christman morning.
   The Bushes are traveling to Armenia as volunteers for Americares,
a relief agency that has chartered a DC-8 cargo plane to transport
supplies to the region.
   The aid will include medicine, medical equipment and toys from
the Americares charity for children who survived the Dec. 7 quake,
which killed at least 55,000 people, Tass said.
   Steve Norman, an Americares spokesman, said the Bushes are among
three people on the flight.
   Norman said the Bushes will only stay a few hours because of time
restrictions imposed by the Soviets. ``They are not allowing people
to stay much longer than that because of congestion at the
airport,'' he said.
   The plane will return to the United States after a brief layover
in Cologne, Germany, Norman said.
</TEXT>
