<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-Crash 1stLd-Writethru   12-23 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0488,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pressure-Activated Bomb Found During Palestinian Arrests In October</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with report of security lapse at airport. No
pickup.
^With PM-Crash, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A West German official said today
that police discovered an air pressure-activated bomb during the
October arrests of suspected radical Palestinians, but he emphasized
it was too soon to say whether there was any connection to the crash
of a Pan Am jet.
   ``It's pure speculation,'' said Alexander Prechtel, spokesman for
the chief federal prosecutor's office. The bomb is set off by a drop
in air pressure, such as those occurring in the luggage compartment
of an airplane, he said.
   New York-bound Pan Am Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt and
landed in London, where passengers changed from a Boeing 727 to the
ill-fated Boeing 747.
   Wednesday's crash in Scotland, which killed 258 people on board
and at least 22 people on the ground, apparently occurred after the
plane broke up for an unknown reason at an altitude of 31,000 feet.
   The Neue Presse newspaper of Frankfurt reported today on alleged
lapses in security checks at Frankfurt airport. The newspaper quoted
an unidentified expert as saying it's ``problem-free to smuggle a
bomb on board.''
   ``If the explosives and detonator are taken on board separately,
it's all child's play,'' the newspaper quoted the expert as saying.
   The paper quoted an unidentified baggage handler as saying that
not every bag is subjected to an X-ray scan, and that only random
samplings are made.
   Wolfgang Schwalm, the spokesman for the airport, declined comment
on the report, noting that security is handled by Hesse state
officials. The Associated Press called the office of security chief
Horst Harnstein, and was told he was not available to talk.
   But on Thursday, Hans Neusel, the No. 2 official in the federal
Interior Ministry, strongly defended security at Frankfurt airport.
   Arno Falk, a spokesman for the federal police office in
Wiesbaden, told The Associated Press that West German investigators
were checking details of the crash and were in contact with
investigators in London.
   Since the crash, there have been growing indications the flight
was sabotaged.
   In London, the Independent newspaper today quoted a security
source as saying investigators were taking ``very seriously'' a
pro-Iranian group's letter that it was responsible for the crash.
   However, Prechtel brought up the issue of 13 Palestinians rounded
up in a series of raids in West Germany in October. Three were later
arrested, while the others were set free but remain under
investigation.
   Prechtel said in a telephone interview that the arrested suspects
belonged to the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command.
   ``They have said they planned attacks against U.S. interests,''
Prechtel said of the suspected Popular Front members.
   The suspects allegedly set up a terrorist cell of the Popular
Front in West Germany, authorities say. The Syrian-controlled
faction is opposed to the Palestine Liberation Organization leader,
Yasser Arafat, and is headed by Ahmad Jibril, a former Syrian army
captain.
   Prechtel said officers in the town of Neuss near Duesseldorf
found in a car used by one member of the group a bomb activated by a
drop in air pressure.
   ``Naturally, you can see a connection,'' Prechtel said when asked
whether members of the group could have been involved in the crash
of the Pan Am plane. ``They may have built several of these bombs.''
   He said the bomb that was discovered was hidden inside a radio,
thus making it difficult to detect.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
