<DOCNO> AP881223-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1202EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Argentina     12-23 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Argentina,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Convictions of Rebellious Officers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court convicted
seven retired air force officers for attempting to take over an
airport following an army insurrection in January.
   The three-member court rejected the officers' arguments that they
tried to seize Jorge Newberry Airport to prevent a civil war. One
officer testified that they wanted to stop an air force attack on
rebellious army units at Monte Caseros, 310 miles northeast of the
capital.
   The army units later surrendered.
   Thursday's decision by the appeals court came after the nation's
highest military tribunal convicted the seven of mutiny and
sentenced them.
   The appeals court convicted the men on the more serious charge of
aggravated rebellion. Most received stiffer sentences.
   Under Argentine law, the appeals court can rule on any charges or
assign its own penalties independent of lower or military court
rulings.
   Retired Col. Luis Estrella's sentence of 12 years was upheld,
while the sentences of Lt. Cols. Horacio Ricciardelli, Juan Carlos
Puy and Angel Lavella were increased to 11 years each.
   Under the military tribunal, Puy had received an eight-year
sentence, and Lavella and Ricciardelli seven years each.
   Lt. Col. Ernesto Lynch, Maj. Higinio Ribles and Capt. Antonio
Eduardo all received sentences of six years, eight months; as did
Godofredo Buschiazzo, an enlisted man in the navy.
   Ribles had originally received a seven-year sentence, and Lynch
and Eduardo received five years each. Buschiazzo's term was
increased from one to five years.
   Lt. Col. Antonio Magni, who had argued he did not participate in
the takeover, was acquitted. He had received a three-year sentence
from the military tribunal.
   The convicted servicemen will spend their terms in military
custody.
   On Jan. 18, about 20 rebels seized the control tower, forcing the
cancellation of some flights and the detour of others to Ezeiza
International Airport, the largest in this city of 10 million.
Rebels surrendered peacefully after four hours.
   Estrella told the court that he and the others acted to prevent
the air force attack against the rebels in Monte Caseros.
   ``On Jan. 18, the country was heading towards a civil war and
something had to be done to prevent the repression the air force was
ready to launch on the rebels,'' Estrella said.
   The army insurrection was led by Lt. Col. Aldo Rico, now
cashiered and imprisoned at an army garrison along with about 50 of
his followers. None have been brought to trial.
   Rico also led an uprising in April 1987 to protest the trial of
officers for human rights abuses stemming from the repression of
subversion under the 1976-83 military dictatorship.
   That same concern prompted a third uprising against the civilian
government of President Raul Alfonsin earlier this month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
