<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-JetExplosion     12-23 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Jet Explosion,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldier's Souvenir Grenade Fuse Explodes In Spanish Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Spanish soldier's souvenir grenade fuse
blew up in the cargo bay of a DC-9 passenger jet today minutes after
all passengers exited the plane, and officials said one person was
slightly injured.
   The small explosion caused little damage to the interior of the
jet operated by the Spanish domestic airline Aviaco, but a cargo
handler was slightly injured, said an airport spokesman who demanded
anonymity.
   ``Two Army soldiers on holiday leave from training in Palma de
Majorca brought back as souvenirs two low-powered fuses, or caps,
used to trigger rifle-fired anti-tank grenades during instruction,''
said Defense Ministry spokesman Pedro Meyer said. ``Although only
one of the fuses exploded, both soldiers acted in a completely
irresponsible way and contravened army rules in traveling with the
fuses.''
   Civil Guard officers at the airport arrested the two unidentified
soldiers and presented them before an examining magistrate in Madrid
District Court for possible charges, Meyer said.
   The Aviaco DC-9 arrived from Palma de Majorca in Spain's
Mediterranean Balearic Islands shortly before the blast, the airport
spokesman said.
   The fuse exploded when a cargo handler moved one of the soldier's
bags in the cargo bay, he said. The handler suffered a slight injury.
</TEXT>
