<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Japan-AIDS     12-23 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-AIDS,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Approve AIDS Prevention Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislators gave final approval Friday to a law
intended to track and prevent the spread of AIDS.
   The law, to take effect next year, would require doctors to
report to local governors the name, age and sex of any AIDS patient
and how the victim contracted the disease, said an official at the
research office of the Standing Committee on Social and Labor
Affairs, a government agency.
   The law also authorize governors to fine anyone refusing to be
tested for AIDS up to $800, and to punish doctors who disclose
information about AIDS patients to anyone but the governor's office,
said the official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   He said the law provides for banning entry to any foreigner
believed likely to engage in activities that could spread acquired
immune deficience syndrome, although AIDS tests are not mandatory
for foreigners.
   Most opposition members voted against the bill, saying it would
lead to people avoiding seeing their doctors.
   The government says 50 people have died of AIDS in Japan as of
Aug. 31, with 90 confirmed AIDS patients and 1,048 known carriers of
the virus.
</TEXT>
