<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1248EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Birth     12-23 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Birth,0428</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Rebukes Catholic Clinics For Using `Test-Tube' Conception</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican said Friday that Roman Catholic
university clinics were challenging church teaching by continuing
research into test-tube conception, which the church rejects.
   An editorial in the Vatican's newspaper, L'Osservatore Romano,
said the church feels determined ``as never before'' to safeguard
the common good against ``technological manipulation of the very
fonts of life.''
   ``The oscillations and discord in the Catholic camp have
contributed to rendering the question more complex,'' said the
editorial.
   ``Above all, the gravity of the decision of several Catholic
university clinics to continue, under certain conditions, the
practive of homologous `in vitro' fertilizaton, cannot be
undervalued.''
   ``Such resolve, from the moment it was made public, has become a
challenge as well,'' the newspaper said.
   In January, a Vatican meeting failed to resolve a dispute between
the Vatican and three Catholic universities in Europe on researching
test-tube conception.
   In 1987, a Vatican document approved by Pope John II had
condemned test-tube conception, surrogate motherhood and
experimentation on live embryos.
   It also branded as immoral the freezing of embryos, cloning,
attempts to fashion animal-human hybrids and the implanation of
embryos in artificial or animal uteruses.
   Shortly after the document's publication, the Catholic University
of Lille, France, announced it will continue experiments with
``in-vitro'' fertilization to help couples who otherwise couldn't
have children.
   The January meeting was with rectors of the Lille institution,
Universite Catholique de Louvain, in Belgium, and Holland's
Katholieke Universiteit of Nijmegen.
   Roman Catholic teaching holds that the only moral way to create
human life is normal sexual acts between a married couple. In ``in
vitro'' methods, an egg is taken from a woman's ovary and united
with sperm outside the womb. When life begins to grow, the
fertilized egg is then implanted in a womb.
   Referring to the universities' decision, the editorial continued:
``The directors of this ... very serious rebellion, try still to
justify themselves by claiming to respect the Roman teaching.''
   The editorial said the clinics claim not to understand the
reasons for the stance of the Vatican's Congregation for the
Doctrine of the Faith.
   The congregation is the Vatican's watchdog for doctrinal
orthodoxy.
   The newspaper asserted that use of artificial birth control ended
up being an incentive for abortion, and that similarly ``it is
becoming evident that artifical procreation puts as its operating
premise'' discriminating cultural choices as to what kind of babies
would be born.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-Students Bjt   12-23 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Students, Bjt,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students, Teachers Mourn Classmates They Grew Close to Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bouquet of red tulips lay on the steps of
Syracuse University's study center as students and teachers ended a
memorial service Friday for classmates killed in the Pan Am crash.
   They hugged one another and wept, clustered in small groups
outside the gray stone church where the morning service was held,
and met at the elegant mansion that houses their school across the
street.
   ``They had such a passionate interest in life and a desire to
make the world better,'' Malcolm Ingrim, a Syracuse drama professor,
said as he remembered the six he taught and the other students
killed in the crash Wednesday night.
   ``When all that is snuffed out in 30 seconds it's impossible to
make any sense of it,'' he said. ``It's shattering.''
   The 35 Syracuse students were among 258 people who died when the
New York-bound Boeing 747 crashed in the Scottish village of
Lockerbie on Wednesday.
   Paul Smith, an English major from Kennett Square, Pa., heard the
news Wednesday night while in a pub with friends.
   ``It wasn't real, I couldn't believe it,'' he said.
   Smith shared a house with six friends including Amy Shapiro, a
student from Stamford, Conn., who died in the crash. Like others, he
knew just about all 270 students on the close-knit London program.
   The students were chosen for the program for their academic
ability, and studied at the 19th century mansion on fashionable
Ladbroke Grove with Syracuse and London School of Economics
professors. The term ended Dec. 17, and most had already gone home
when the crash occurred.
   After a friend got a call from the United States and went to the
pub to tell them, Smith and the others raced to the study center to
wait for news. Sometime past midnight, they learned the students had
made the flight, and that there were no survivors.
   ``It still isn't real. You keep expecting Amy to walk through the
door,'' he said, his hands in his pockets and his eyes downcast.
Asked what she was like, he said, ``She was the happiest person
alive.''
   Kristin Huffmon, a junior from Madison, N.J., said Ms. Shapiro
was studying photography and had always said, half-jokingly, that
her dream was to work for National Geographic magazine.
   ``Doesn't every photojournalism student want to work for National
Geographic? That was Amy's `joke,''' said Ms. Huffmon, a political
science major.
   Ingrim, who is originally from London, said three of his students
_ Theodora Cohen, Miriam Wolfe, and Nicole Boulanger _ were planning
to set up a theater troupe at school upon their return. Three
others, Jason Coker, Tim Cardwell and Turhan Ergin, also studied
drama under him.
   ``They were all extremely gifted,'' he said. ``When I see kids of
such promise and energy ... I cannot imagine how the parents are
feeling right now. I just can't imagine.''
   At the memorial service at St. John's church in west London,
vicar Harold Stringer and a local rabbi, Jacqueline Tabick, led the
small group through prayers and hymns.
   They read out the names of those lost and observed a moment of
silence.
</TEXT>
