<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Bomb Threat, 2nd Ld -  Writethru,a0509,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air India Flight Returns To Heathrow After Bomb Threat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Air India jet turning back.
Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``Police said...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Air India jumbo jet bound for New York with 250
people aboard returned to London today after a bomb threat.
   Also today, a terminal at Heathrow Airport was evacuated after
officials spotted a suspicious suitcase, and a British Airways
Tristar flew to Heathrow after a bomb threat forced it to make an
unscheduled stop in Rome on Thursday.
   All three incidents followed Wednesday's explosion of a New
York-bound Pan Am Boeing 747 over the Scottish village of Lockerbie.
All 258 people aboard were killed along with at least 22 people on
the ground.
   After Air India Flight 109, a Boeing 747, had taken off for New
York at 2:59 p.m. Air India in New York received a bomb threat from
an anonymous caller, said an airline spokesman, who demanded
anonymity.
   The bomb threat, as a matter of routine, was passed to the
captain of Flight 109 who decided to return to Heathrow, the
spokesman said.
   The 747 landed at 4:21 p.m. and taxied to an isolated area
southwest of the terminals where emergency services were standing
by, the British Airports Authority said.
   Passengers left the plane normally and were taken by bus to
terminal three where they were being kept in two rooms. The airline
spokesman said the plane would be thoroughly searched.
   Earlier today, an unattended suitcase prompted officials to
evacuate hundreds of Christmas travelers from terminal three, but a
bomb squad found the bag contained just clothing, airport officials
said.
   The British Airports Authority said the suitcase was found about
noon today next to an Air Canada check-in desk, just one aisle away
from the Pan Am check-in counter.
   Police said they were told that a man walked into the terminal,
left the suitcase, and drove off again.
   In the British Airways incident, authorities closed Rome's main
Leonardo da Vinci airport for 20 minutes Thursday while the plane
made an emergency landing and its 242 passengers and 12 crew
disembarked at an isolated area.
   The aircraft and the luggage were examined, but no bomb was
found, said British Airways spokesman Michael Blunt. A caller to the
airline's London office said a bomb was on board, he said.
   Flight 146 originated in New Delhi, made a stopover in Kuwait and
was flying to London when it was diverted.
   Blunt said fog had delayed the Tristar for four hours in New
Delhi. About four hours after leaving Kuwait, passengers said the
pilot told them he was landing in Rome because one of his engines
``looked suspicious.''
   Unaware of the bomb threat, most passengers sat in strained
silence while the aircraft descended, then broke into applause on
touchdown about four miles from the Rome terminal. Passengers then
were told to leave the aircraft immediately.
   Outside, the tarmac was swarming with security officials, Italian
police and firefighters, passengers said.
</TEXT>
