<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Salvador-Attack     12-23 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador-Attack,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commandos Attack Military Headquarters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commandos with explosive charges
attacked the Defense Ministry and military headquarters in the
capital today, military sources said. No casualties were immediately
reported.
   It was the first time the installation, which houses the Defense
Ministry and the joint chiefs of staff, was attacked during
Salvador's nine-year guerrilla war.
   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, gave no other
details.
   Radio reports indicated that two car bombs detonated near the
walled compound in the southwest part of the city, but the reports
could not be immediately confirmed.
   No one claimed responsibility, but the attackers were presumed to
be members of the Farabundo Marti Liberation Front, a left-wing
insurgency trying to overthrow the government. In the last year, it
has attacked installations in the capital with car bombs and
catapult-launched homemade bombs.
   Earlier in the day, unidentified terrorists killed a night
watchman and set off three bombs, destroying the interior of the
biology lab building at the National University, an official at the
institution said.
   The official told The Associated Press that unidentified
individuals cut through a metal fence before dawn to enter the
campus in the capital's northwestern sector. The official, who
commented on condition of anonymity, identified the slain watchman
as Roberto Aguirre.
   No one claimed responsibility for the attack at the university,
with 35,000 students the biggest in the country, and police said
they had no clues on the identity of the attackers.
   The university has been the scene of demonstrations recently by
leftist student unions demanding $1.2 million in additional
appropriations to pay back salaries for December owed to teachers
and workers.
   Students were also protesting the assassination last week of a
woman director of a law faculty extension in the western city of
Santa Ana.
   The interior of the building, including furniture, files,
windows, ceilings and laboratory equipment, was virtually demolished
by the blasts.
   Also today, five provincial town mayors resigned, bringing to 12
the number of mayors who quit during the past three months after
receiving death threats from leftist guerrillas fighting for power.
   The guerrillas have assassinated nine mayors in 1988. They say
the officials were ``executed'' for their part in implementing what
the rebels call ``the U.S.-imposed counterinsurgency plan.''
</TEXT>
