<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1336EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Crash-US-Rdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0531 12-23 1312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-US-Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0531,1320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane's Delayed Departure May Be Helpful Factor In Probe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 4 grafs after pvs 3rd graf bgng ``Witnesses saw ...''
to update with what investigators heard on flight recordings;
INSERTS 2 grafs after pvs 7th graf bgng ``U.S. officials...'' to
include call to AP's London office on Thursday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If a terrorist bomb brought down Pan Am Flight
103, a 25-minute delay of the jet's departure from London may
provide investigators with their biggest advantage. It kept the
wreckage on land, instead of falling into the ocean.
   The cause of Wednesday's crash that killed all 258 people on
board and more than 20 on the ground has yet to be determined, but
there were signs today pointing to an explosion.
   Witnesses saw a flash of light high in the sky as the jet
plummeted toward the ground; there was no communication from the
cockpit as would have been expected if the pilots encountered flight
control problems, and the wreckage was strewn over miles of Scottish
countryside with the cockpit section found more than three miles
from other large parts of the aircraft.
   From Scotland, officials investigating the crash said today that
the cockpit recording of the flight's last minutes ended abruptly
after a faint noise. They also said conversations among the crew
gave no clues about what caused the plane to crash.
   ``There is nothing in the conversations (of the flight crew) to
indicate anything was wrong,'' said Paul McKie, spokesman for the
British Department of Transport.
   The cockpit recording and flight data tapes from the Boeing 747
were being analyzed by the department's Air Accident Investigation
Branch.
   ``There is a faint noise at the end which needs a bit more
analysis. There is no indication what that noise is,'' said McKie.
   But none of that is conclusive evidence that a bomb detonated
aboard the jetliner.
   President Reagan said today that a public warning about the
flight after an anonymous telephone call to the U.S. Embassy in
Helsinki would ``literally have closed down air traffic in the
world.'' The president said he believes ``all precautions'' were
taken in the warning which went to the airline and U.S. embassies.
   Reagan, speaking in the rain outside the White House as he
departed for California where he will spend the holidays, offered
condolences to the families of the victims, calling for Christmas
prayers for their loss.
   U.S. officials said the caller to the embassy in Finland on Dec.
5 said that a bomb would be planted aboard a Pan Am flight from
Frankfurt, West Germany, to the United States within two weeks.
Flight 103 began in Frankfurt on a Boeing 727, then changed planes
to a Boeing 747 in London. But there has been no evidence that the
telephone tip was related to the crash of Flight 103.
   In addition, an anonymous caller to The Associated Press in
London on Thursday claimed a pro-Iranian group called Guardians of
the Islamic Revolution planted a bomb on the plane.
   The caller said the motive was revenge for the July downing of an
Iranian jetliner in the Persian Gulf by the U.S. warship Vincennes,
but Iran has denied involvement in the crash.
   The wreckage of Flight 103 is expected to provide more definitive
clues, and while it is strewn over miles of countryside, at least it
is not hundreds of feet under wintry seas, some aviation experts
noted.
   In other U.S. developments related to the Pan Am crash:
   _White House officials defended the process by which the State
Department warned U.S. embassies _ but not the general public _ that
a bomb threat had been made against Pan Am. They said the government
would review whether public notification should be considered in
future such cases.
   _President-elect Bush said that if there were ``hard evidence''
that a specific flight was threatened or that the threat could not
be averted, the public should be warned. Nevertheless, he said most
such threats ``never materialize.''
   _FBI Director William Sessions said in San Francisco there have
been ``a number of calls'' from individuals _ some claiming to speak
for various terrorist groups _ taking responsibility for the crash.
Sessions provided no specifics.
   Flight 103 had been airborne 54 minutes when it disappeared from
radar screens while cruising at 31,000 feet over Scotland. It was
about to head westbound over the Atlantic when tragedy struck.
Another half hour and the plane would have been well over water.
   ``You would have had another Air India situation,'' said Frank
Taylor, an aviation safety consultant and former longtime
investigator for the National Transportation Safety Board.
   To many investigators, the Pan Am tragedy appears to resemble the
l985 crash of an Air India Boeing 747 off the Irish coast. That
jumbo jet also plummeted from the sky from 31,000 feet without a
hint of trouble from the pilots.
   But the wreckage landed in the ocean and salvage crews struggled
for four months to gather pieces, including the ``black box''
recorders, that would provide clues. An analysis of the final split
second of the voice recorder was key to Indian officials concluding
that a bomb had exploded aboard the aircraft.
   The authorities probing the Pan Am crash clearly will have more
to work with. They already have found the critical ``black box''
recorders _ one that monitors cockpit conversation and noises and
another that records aircraft performance.
   Investigators will pay close attention to how parts of the
aircraft are bent, tangled and singed and whether there are signs of
residue from an explosion. They also will search for fragments that
might have been used as a detonator and closely examine luggage and
parts of luggage for residue from an explosive.
   The ``black box'' recorders are likely to provide, as they do in
most aviation crashes, the most critical evidence, say aviation
experts.
   The tape from the cockpit recorder may be as important for what
it doesn't say as for what it does, say veteran investigators. Is
there a fragmented sound of an explosion? Are there any exchanges
between pilots about control problems? Did the tape suddenly stop
with no evidence of an emergency or structural concern?
   If all seems normal right to the end, it will be strong evidence
that a powerful explosion might have knocked out communications,
electricity and perhaps even literally severed the cockpit from the
rest of the aircraft, says Taylor. ``If you lost all communications,
lost all electrical power on and airplane, the pilots now are
nothing more than passengers.''
   It would not take a large amount of explosives to do the job,
suggested a number of experts.
   ``If a bomb severs some major or important electrical wiring, or
hydraulic lines or cables, you could lose your ability to control
the airplane,'' noted John Mazor, a spokesman for the Air Line
Pilots Association.
   While aviation experts were reluctant to provide details that
could be used as a primer for terrorism, it is generally known that
if an explosive device _ even a small one _ can be placed in certain
areas of the baggage compartment of a Boeing 747, it could wipe out
critical computer, electrical and communications systems as well as
possibly incapacitate the flight crew.
   Some safety experts say such a scenario explains the sudden loss
of communications while the Pan Am jet was at cruise altitude and
its rapid fall and breakup while still in the sky.
   They point out that commercial jetliners have over the years been
kept aloft for some time even when encountering major structural
problems short of an explosion.
   In l985, the pilots of a Japan Air Lines Boeing 747 struggled to
keep their plane flying for about 32 minutes after a failure in the
rear cabin bulkhead caused rapid depressurization. The jet finally
crashed into a mountain, killing 520 people aboard.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
