<HEAD>Bush Son, Grandson on Mercy Flight to Armenia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush's son and grandson
are flying to Soviet Armenia over the Christmas weekend to deliver
toys and medical supplies to victims of the devastating earthquake
there, Bush's office said Friday.
   Jeb Bush, 35, a Miami real estate developer, and his son, George,
12, will spend about six hours in Yerevan, the Armenian capital, on
Christmas Day. They leave New York on Saturday, arriving in the
Soviet Union the next morning.
   The Bushes are traveling to Armenia as volunteers for Americares,
a private relief agency that has chartered a DC-8 cargo plane to
transport supplies to the region when 55,000 people were killed in
the earthquake.
   Steve Norman, an Americares spokesman, said the Bushes are among
three people on the flight, loaded primarily with toys and medical
supplies for children.
   On arrival, the Bushes will tour Yerevan, Norman said. ``They
will go into the city and view some of the distribution points,'' he
said.
   Norman said the Bushes will only stay a few hours because of time
restrictions imposed by the Soviets. ``They are not allowing people
to say much longer than that because of congestion at the airport,''
he said.
   The plane will return directly to the United States after a brief
layover in Cologne, West Germany, Norman said.
   Jeb Bush, who campaigned for his father's election and has served
as Florida's secretary of commerce, was familiar with Americares, an
organization founded by Bob Macauley, an old friend of the Bushes'
from Connecticut, Norman said.
   Americares has already flown several relief flights into Armenia.
