<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BaptistConvention     12-23 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baptist Convention,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Group Looking For Control of Baptist Convention</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A centrist coalition of Southern Baptists has
launched a bid to win over members of the nation's largest
Protestant denomination, which has been torn for a decade between
conservatives and more liberal members.
   The 14.6 million-member church has been divided since 1979 over
how literally the Bible must be accepted, with conservatives, who
believe every account in the Bible actually happened, controlling
the denomination's hierarchy.
   Last week, a group calling itself Baptists Committed to the
Southern Baptist Convention threw its hat into the ring, promoting
itself as an alternative between the two sides. Its goals, say
organizers, are to educate grass-roots Baptists about issues in the
denomination and to win control away from the conservatives.
   ``If there's an identifiable group, which believes in Southern
Baptist polity and Southern Baptist principles of the separation of
church and state, the priesthood of the believer and the
unquestioned authority of God _ well, that's who I am,'' said the
Rev. Richard Jackson, an Arizona pastor who was defeated in June in
his bid for presidency of the denomination.
   Baptist conservatives had mixed reactions to the organization.
   ``I affirm the right of Baptists to get together and discuss
anything they want to discuss,'' said the Rev. Jerry Vines, of
Jacksonville, Fla., who is the denomination's president.
   Paul Pressler, the Houston judge who has been an architect of the
conservative strategy, told the Dallas Times Herald that he wishes
dissenters would stop fighting.
   ``The Southern Baptist Convention needs healing and working
together, not an escalation of political activity,'' he said.
   Many of the participants at last week's two-day meeting have been
active in previous efforts to wrest control of the church from
current leaders. Among its plans was to launch a new publication to
provide news that does not appear in the convention's newsletter.
   The new organization is a coalition of regional groups including
Message, a Texas-based group, and Baptist Laity for the Baptist
Faith.
</TEXT>
