<DOCNO> AP881223-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1431EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Sher-Aide     12-23 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sher-Aide,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Asks Why State Department Didn't Issue Wider Bomb Alert</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neal Sher, head of the Justice Department's
Nazi-hunting unit, Friday questioned why the State Department didn't
alert all government agencies to the terrorist bomb threat prior to
the crash of the Pan Am jumbo jet in Scotland.
   Sher, director of the Office of Special Investigations, lost one
of his aides in the crash, Michael Bernstein, who was returning from
Austria after negotiating an agreement in which the Vienna
government agreed to take back a former SS concentration camp guard
living in La Puente, Calif.
   Sher was in Budapest, Hungary, on official business at the time
of the crash and flew out of Frankfurt, West Germany, on another Pan
American World Airways flight, cutting his trip short when he found
out about Bernstein's death.
   The Pan Am flight that crashed Wednesday en route to New York had
originated in Frankfurt.
   U.S. officials said Thursday a caller to the U.S. Embassy in
Helsinki, Finland, on Dec. 5 said a bomb would be planted aboard a
Pan Am flight from Frankfurt to the United States within two weeks.
   The State Department said it issued a widespread alert about the
bomb threat to airlines, airport security officials and U.S.
embassies. The department said it believed the carriers and airport
security, in particular, should be responsible for enhancing
security matters in such circumstances.
   Asked whether the rest of the government should have been
informed of the threat, which the State Department deemed serious
enough to post in a bulletin board notice at embassies, Sher said he
would have flown on another airline ``if I had known this threat was
out there on Pan Am.''
   ``I'm very upset,'' Sher added. ``People in my office travel all
over the world all the time.''
   Besides Bernstein, three State Department employees, a Peace
Corps volunteer and at least a dozen U.S. military personnel were
among the 258 passengers and crew that died in the crash.
   Sher called Bernstein ``one of the best lawyers who ever came
through'' the office of special investigations and said Bernstein
had won ``a major victory'' in his trip to Vienna.
   During negotiations, Austria agreed to accept Josef Eckert, who
admitted his membership in an SS guard unit assigned to the
Auschwitz concentration camp complex during World War II. Bernstein
informed Sher of the Austrians' agreement in a conversation shortly
before the crash.
   Bernstein, 36, who is survived by his wife and two children, took
a pay cut when he left a private law firm in 1985 and went to work
for Sher after reading a news story about OSI.
   ``There's no question that Mike was doing this out of
dedication,'' Sher said.
</TEXT>
