<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TankerExplosion 4thLd-Writethru a0584 12-23 0332</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tanker Explosion, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0584,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tanker Explodes in Downtown Memphis, Killing At Least Five</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with at least one child killed, another
missing, at least 12 injured, authorities no longer saying numerous
other deaths feared, details on accident, tanker carrying propane,
new quotes; No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A propane tanker truck exploded on an
interstate highway in downtown Memphis today, spewing a
700-foot-wide fireball that killed at least five people and engulfed
several homes and cars, authorities said.
   The explosion threw the tanker 125 yards onto a house, killing at
least one child inside, said Fire Department Deputy Director Frank
Baker. Firefighters searched for a second child who was believed to
be inside the home.
   At least a dozen people were injured, authorities said.
   ``There was a guy on fire rolling on the road and there was a
another just lying on the ground where somebody must have put him.
He was still smoking,'' said Jed Tennison, who runs a nearby
business and witnessed the accident.
   The tanker skidded off an exit on Interstate 240 and exploded,
unleashing a fireball that burned at least five houses on both sides
of the highway and three or four other vehicles, said fire Capt.
Benny McDow.
   ``He was trying to exit and lost control and hit a retaining
wall,'' McDow said. ``That exit there is short. It's one of those
tight turns.''
   Four of the dead were killed on the highway, officials said. The
identities of the dead and injured were not immediately known.
   Highway department ambulances took about a dozen people to area
hospitals and other injured were transported by helicopter or by
private vehicle, McDow said.
   The fire department was called about the explosion at 10:10 a.m,
he said.
   ``We do not know the exact cause at this time,'' McDow said.
``Our original call came in as two houses exploded. We responded and
found ... the interstate ... fire.''
</TEXT>
