<DOCNO> AP881223-0125 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1511EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Army-Helicopters     12-23 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Army-Helicopters,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Grounds Chinooks for Transmission Checks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Army said Friday it has grounded its 234
CH-47D medium-lift Chinook helicopters to allow inspection of
possibly faulty transmissions.
   Ten Chinooks have been involved in accidents since 1985, and 16
soldiers were killed in incidents involving the helicopter this
year, although there is no indication that faulty transmissions were
the cause, said Army spokeswoman Paige Eversole.
   The Army grounded the copter fleet in what it called a
``precautionary action'' after the manufacturer, the Boeing Co.,
discovered that ``certain transmissions may have been improperly
assembled,'' the announcement said.
   In the most recent Chinook accident, five servicemen were killed
in a crash in Honduras on Dec. 8.
   Last Feb. 25, 11 soldiers were killed in a Chinook crash near
Chico, Texas.
   Army officials are still investigating the Dec. 8 incident, but
there is ``no suspicion'' that it was linked to the possible
transmission problem, Ms. Eversole said.
   ``Right now we are not speculating at all on the cause of that
accident. We don't know whether there is a relationship between that
accident and this problem. The Army is very quick to ground the
fleet ... for preventive care,'' she said.
   Boeing is sending inspection teams to look at the retainer bolt
assembly, which provides for the proper alignment of internal
gearing and bearings within the main transmission, the spokeswoman
said. The inspections will require 30 days, according to the
announcement.
   The first Chinook CH-47D entered Army service in 1979, replacing
older CH-47 models. The Army is gradually replacing the remaining
146 older Chinooks with the ``D'' model, which has more powerful
engines and transmissions, fiberglass rotor blades, and advanced
flight control systems, the announcement said.
   The Chinook can carry a payload of 16,000 pounds or ferry 33
soldiers.
   The helicopter that crashed in Honduras was on a routine mission
connected with maneuvers the Army has been conducting in that
Central American country since 1982.
   In the Texas crash, ``the retainer bolt assembly was not
identified as a possible cause,'' Ms. Eversole said.
   Despite the recent crashes involving the Chinook, the fiscal year
thaty ended Sept. 30 ``was the safest year on record, with 1.8
accidents per 100,000 hours of flying time for all Army aviation,''
she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
