<HEAD>Three State Dept. Officials Among Victims</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th, 8th grafs to include age, hometown of Butler</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three State Department employees, a Justice
Department official and a Peace Corps volunteer were aboard the Pan
American World Airways flight which crashed in Scotland, it was
announced today.
   Deputy State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley identified the
victims as follows:
   Matthew K. Gannon, of Orange, Calif. He was assigned to the State
Department's Middle East bureau and was returning home upon
completion of assignment in Beirut as a political officer. He had
previously worked in North Yemen, Jordan and Syria.
   Ronald A. Lariviere of Holyoke, Mass. He had been assigned by the
State Department to Beirut as a security officer since June 1988. He
had previously served in Washington in the office of diplomatic
security after joining the department in 1987.
   Daniel E. O'Connor of Boston. He was assigned to Nicosia as a
security officer in April 1988. He had joined the foreign service in
1986 and had served in Washington in the office of diplomatic
security.
   Michael Bernstein, who worked in the criminal division, office of
special investigations, Department of Justice.
   Stephen L. Butler, 36, served as a Peace Corps volunteer in
Tunisia. Butler, originally from Denver, Colo., was returning on an
emergency leave to Trenton, N.J.
   Mrs. Oakley was unable to provide the ages of the other four
people.
   On Thursday, Mrs. Oakley said four State Department employees had
died in the crash but one of those individuals was a Pentagon
official.
