<2ND_LINE>AM-Child's Body,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Puzzled By Child's Body Found In Concrete</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYCROSS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The decomposed body of a toddler was found
stuffed in a gym bag, the bag in a suitcase encased in concrete and
dumped along a dirt road, police said Friday.
   An autopsy Thursday night was only partially conclusive, and
police do not know who the child is. Ware County Sheriff Herbert E.
Bond said there are no small children known to be missing from the
area.
   The body was found Wednesday by a trucker, 16 miles west of
Waycross.
   She had been wrapped in a blanket and stuffed in a gym bag, which
then was placed in a metal suitcase, and the suitcase sealed with
concrete. The suitcase was then placed in an abandoned TV console
and nailed shut with plywood.
   The driver, who was not identified, ``cried like a baby when he
found it,'' the sheriff said.
   The autopsy at the State Crime Lab determined her sex, race and
probable age. Bond said pathologists determined that the child had
been dead about one to two months and was about 3, who was 2-feet-9
and weighed about 30 pounds.
   ``They were able to tell us she had not been shot or stabbed,''
Bond said Friday.
   ``I don't know whether it was an abused child that was
accidentally killed, or a kidnap victim that was killed somewhere
else and brought there,'' he said. ``But somebody went to great
extremes to put it together and then leave it out there in the
open.''
