<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BullyBuffalo     12-23 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bully Buffalo,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Vows To Destroy Pet Buffalo That Gored Him</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man gored by the same 1,500-pound pet
buffalo that mauled his son a year ago said the animal will be
destroyed.
   ``I don't want anything like that around anymore,'' said Gerald
Assel, who was hospitalized in stable condition Friday, two days
after being attacked.
   ``He was a pet, but he turned against us,'' Assel, 54, said.
``You can never trust a buffalo.''
   Assel said he was sweeping refuse from a barn into a corral when
the bull, named J.R., backed him against a door and worked a horn
into his midsection.
   He managed to escape when the door became ajar, Assel said. He
walked to his house, and his wife, Edna, drove him to the hospital,
he said.
   ``If I would've been against the barn, he would've killed me,''
Assel said.
   Dr. Gilbert Gonzalez said Assel was in surgery about 3{ hours.
The attack severely damaged his bowels and lower abdomen muscles,
and even severed part of his appendix, the doctor said.
   Assel said J.R. attacked his 21-year-old son, Landen, in January.
Landen's wounds to his buttocks and face required about 70 stitches,
he said.
   Assel, whose family raises a herd of 16 buffalo on their 900-acre
ranch to supplement their income, said he has had enough of J.R.'s
attacks.
   Assel's wife said Landen will shoot the bull. The rest of the
herd may be sold, Assel said.
   Doctors expect Assel to be hospitalized two more weeks.
</TEXT>
