<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Crash-Chance     12-23 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Chance,0547</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Last-Minute Plan Changes Meant Some Victims Got on Flight 103</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ingrid Smith cut short a visit home to be with her
husband in New York, and got a last-minute seat on Pan Am Flight 103
because her husband was a pilot _ with Pan Am.
   ``The last we heard from Ingrid was when she rang from Heathrow
and said `Mum I have got on,''' said her mother, Hilda Ledgard of
North Hykeham in central England. ``We are devastated.''
   Like others rushing to be with family for the holidays or
changing their plans, the last-minute booking cost Mrs. Smith her
life.
   The jumbo jet en route to New York broke up at 31,000 feet
Wednesday night over Scotland, killing all aboard.
   Mrs. Smith, whose husband, Bruce, had previously captained the
same Boeing jet which crashed, had been visiting her parents when
she changed her plans.
   She at first wanted to stay because her mother was ill, but then
learned her husband was to be working over Christmas in New York.
With her parents' blessing, she went to Heathrow Airport hoping to
get on a flight.
   Flora Swire, a medical student, and Yvonne Owen, a social worker,
also wound up on Flight 103 by chance.
   A graduate in medicine from Oxford University, Ms. Swire was
traveling to Boston to spend Christmas and New Year with her
boyfriend, a doctor. She was studying for a doctorate at Nottingham
University.
   ``She went down to London on Monday and bought a stand-by ticket
for New York on Tuesday,'' her mother, Jane Swire, said from her
home in Bromsgrove, in eastern England.
   ``She was waved off from Heathrow by her younger sister,
Catherine, before boarding the flight,'' Mrs. Swire said.
   Yvonne Owen changed her plans to be with her boyfriend in Boston
and his sick sister.
   The 29-year-old from Bristol had planned to take her 18-month-old
daughter, Bryony, to Paris for the holidays, but decided instead
that she and Bryony would visit her boyfriend to help him take care
of his sister.
   The Stevenson family heading for Christmas holidays in the United
States also died in the crash, which left more than 20 people on the
ground in and around the Scottish village of Lockerbie missing and
presumed dead.
   John and Geraldine Stevenson and their daughters Hannah, 10, and
Rachel, 8, were to spend Christmas with relatives.
   ``We are all very shocked,'' said Fiona Wilkinson, who worked
with Stevenson at the regional office for the credit card company,
Visa International. ``He was a very popular, very effective member
of the staff.''
   A traffic jam near Frankfurt Airport proved fatal for U.S. Army
Lt. George W. Williams of Joppatowne, Md.
   His parents had surprised him with an early Christmas present of
a plane ticket home, and he was booked on a flight Tuesday. But he
missed the flight because of heavy traffic, and cajoled Pan Am
employees into giving him a seat on the next flight _ Flight 103.
   Williams, 24, ``called and told us he'd have to get on another
flight, and it turned out to be the one that crashed,'' said his
father, also named George.
</TEXT>
