<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HmongRobberies     12-23 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hmong Robberies,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Series of Robberies Plagues Southeast Asian Immigrants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robbers preying on Southeast Asian immigrants
have held up at least a dozen people in the last week, and police
and community leaders are warning Asians to be careful and not carry
a lot of money.
   In one robbery, a Hmong woman lost a purse containing $5,500.
   ``The word is out that they carry money,'' police Capt. Carl
Johnson said.
   ``The facts speak for themselves,'' said St. Paul police
spokesman Paul Adlemann. ``These people are definitely being
targeted.''
   Two men arrested in the holdup Wednesday of two Hmong women in
north Minneapolis have been linked by photographs and a stolen car
to at least one earlier robbery, in St. Paul.
   But hours after the two were captured with the help of a Hmong
man armed with a shotgun, police said another Asian man was robbed
in north Minneapolis.
   Leaders of the area's Southeast Asian community have begun
holding meetings with heads of clans and families, warning them of
the hazards of carrying money and urging them to use banks.
   Ying Vang, executive director of the Lao Family Community of
Minnesota, said the group contacted 60 Hmong leaders and asked that
they call emergency meetings to discuss taking extra precautions.
   ``We told them to make sure people are aware of this rash of
robberies and to watch each other closely and make sure more do not
happen,'' he said.
   Southeast Asians living in some public housing projects also have
formed groups to patrol at night, he said.
   Vang Cheng Nengchu, a Hmong social worker, said, ``I think that
not everybody in the community is aware of the (recent robberies)
yet because of language obstacles.''
   Ying Vang said Hmong leaders were asked to encourage members of
the 15,000-person community, one of the nation's largest
concentrations of Hmong, to use banks. He estimated that 20 to 30
percent do not because of language barriers and unfamiliarity with
banking systems.
   Detectives in Minneapolis and St. Paul, meanwhile, are
investigating possible links among the dozen robberies, and say
there may be more they don't know of. Word of the robbers' success
has spread, they say, through news accounts and word of mouth on the
street.
   ``We know there's more going on out there, and the Hmong
community should know that they're more vulnerable by virtue of a
few successful robberies,'' Johnson said.
</TEXT>
