<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MurderProbe     12-23 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Murder Probe,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Say No Prosecution Likely in 11-Year-Old Stabbing Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities say they believe a death row
inmate who says he killed a reporter but do not plan to prosecute
him.
   ``The various statements he made in his confession convinced us
he is in fact the responsible party,'' Robert Dakopolos, an
assistant Jackson County prosecutor.
   Anthony Joe LaRette, 37, of Topeka, Kan., said in a statement
that he killed Beverly Wortmann, a reporter for the Jackson County
Sentinel-Tribune in Blue Springs, in 1977. He also has been linked
to slayings of two other young women.
   LaRette has been sentenced to death for the 1980 slaying of
18-year-old Mary Fleming of St. Charles.
   Dakopolos said LaRette's statement said he was paid to kill Miss
Wortmann, 24, who was stabbed to death.
   ``He gave us absolutely no means of identifying who this second
person might be,'' Dakopolos said Friday. The prosecutor declined to
say how much LaRette claimed to have been paid.
   He said LaRette will not be charged because he is already
sentenced to die.
   Dakopolos said Kansas authorities have filed notice that they
plan to charge LaRette in the 1978 slaying of Tracey Miller, 26,
Manhattan, Kan. If it appears he might escape the death penalty in
the Fleming death or avoid prosecution in the Miller slaying,
Jackson County prosecutors would file charges in Wortmann's death,
Dakopolos said.
</TEXT>
