<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Dali     12-23 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dali,0193</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surrealist Painter Dali Stable After Return to Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Carles is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>FIGUERAS, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvador Dali remained in stable condition
Friday, one day after a slight intestinal lesion caused him to vomit
blood and suffer nausea, forcing the 84-year-old surrealist painter
back into a hospital, doctors said.
   Dali, last of a generation of famous Spanish artists that
included Pablo Picasso and Joan Miro, has been in frail health and
confined to a wheelchair since he was badly burned in a bedroom fire
in August 1984.
   He entered a local hospital with pneumonia on Nov. 27 and was
sent to a Barcelona hospital after his condition worsened with heart
trouble and blood clots in his left lung. Doctors had allowed the
artist to return to his mansion home in this town near the French
border on Dec. 14.
   Dr. Carles Punsati of the Figueras Hospital told Spanish
Television the painter was resting in stable condition Friday, with
no further bleeding, and maintained constant vital signs.
   ``If no complications arise, he should be able to go home within
three days or so,'' Punsati said.
</TEXT>
