<DOCNO> AP881223-0153 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1722EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MyersonTrial     12-23 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Myerson Trial,0668</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurors At First Leaned Toward Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDIE GLAVE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors in the Bess Myerson divorce-fixing trial
voted 9-3 in favor of conviction early on but finally decided the
prosecution's case wasn't strong enough, the panel's forewoman said.
   ``When we looked the other way and presumed innocence, it forced
us to realize that the (prosecution's) evidence didn't bear out,''
said Linda Berardi, the forewoman in the 12-week trial in U.S.
District Court.
   ``There was some feeling among us that something did happen _ but
it wasn't borne out by the prosecution,'' said Nelson Marty, another
juror.
   Late Thursday, the jury acquitted the former Miss America, her
lover, Carl ``Andy'' Capasso and retired judge Hortense Gabel on
charges they conspired to lower Capasso's alimony payments in return
for a $19,000-a-year city job for the judge's down-and-out daughter,
Sukhreet. Mrs. Gabel was handling the Capasso divorce case.
   The jury deliberated for four days before clearing the three on
all six counts of conspiracy, mail fraud, bribery and obstruction of
justice.
   Sukhreet Gabel's dramatic, comical and often contradictory
testimony as the prosecution's star witness wound up hurting the
government's case, Michael Feldberg, who represented her 76-year-old
mother, said Friday.
   ``I think the prosecution would have been better off if they
didn't call her,'' he said at a news conference. ``I don't think
they would have won anyway, but I think they would have been better
off without her because she turned the case into daytime television,
which is something far different than criminal law.''
   If U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani had taken the time to
scrutinize what would happen to Sukhreet Gabel on cross-examination,
``he may have had second, third or perhaps, fourth thoughts about
bringing this case,'' Feldberg said.
   ``The real question in this case, it seems to me, is not whether
Sukhreet Gabel is a troubled person. Obviously, she has her
difficulties,'' he added. ``The real question is why prosecutors who
know these difficulties ... would prey upon them and use this young
woman to make a case against her mother.''
   He said Myerson's fame as a mover and shaker _ she was the city's
cultural affairs commissioner _ may have led the U.S. attorney's
office to bring the charges.
   ``There's a mentality that a lot of prosecutors have of, if the
target is prominent, it helps you in deciding you want to bring a
case,'' Feldberg said, ``and in this case, they had the most
prominent public woman in New York as a target.''
   Myerson, who Mayor Edward I. Koch credits with helping him win
his job 12 years ago, said after the verdict that she was ``grateful
for the American judicial system'' and thanked the jury for
exonerating her.
   She was not available for interviews on Friday, said her
attorney, Fred Hafetz. ``I think she's just resting up a little bit,
recouping from the trial.''
   Mrs. Gabel said that in her 19 years as a judge, the trial was
``the best judicial experience I've had.''
   Capasso, who is serving a sentence for tax evasion, was returned
to a Pennsylvania prison.
   Hafetz said he didn't know Myerson's immediate plans. He said the
trial generated ``a lot of bad publicity'' for her, but added,
``Hopefully this verdict _ a clear verdict vindicating her _ will
restore her to a position where she is going to be able to make a
significant contribution to our lives.''
   ``She's been through hell ... I wish her only well,'' the mayor
said Friday. ``I believe our 25 years of friendship will continue,''
said Koch, who denounced her as a friend after an investigation he
ordered blasted Myerson for hiring Ms. Gabel.
   The mayor's offer of friendship did not extend to a job offer.
Asked if he would invite her to rejoin his administration, Koch
said, ``I think that's over with. I think she has new fields to
conquer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
