<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Beatles-Movie     12-23 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beatles-Movie,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Old Film Found in John Lennon's Limo</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Museum curators out for a spin
in John Lennon's 1960's-era limousine found a canister of film
stashed under the passenger's seat.
   One scene on the 8-millimeter print shows a man playing a piano
painted in psychedelic colors similar to the paint job on the Rolls
Royce limousine, and curators are hoping their find is misplaced
Beatles memorabilia.
   Lee Manhas, gift shop manager at the Historic Transportation
Centre in suburban Cloverdale, said she was driving the car when the
film was found by museum staff member Roger Giguer.
   ``He said, `There's something here.' He kicked it, reached down
and pulled out the canister. We were amazed,'' she said.
   The 30-minute film has only been viewed on a very small editing
screen and no faces could be identified, said museum spokesman Fred
Davies. He described the film's contents as outtakes, shot possibly
in Boston in the 1960s.
   ``There's sunsets, an eclipse, an old stone church and about
eight men and women inside and outside buildings,'' besides the
piano shot, he said. ``It's a real mystery.''
   Handwritten on the film canister are the words ``Phil Loomis.
Orson Welles Film School.''
   Davies said he planned to invite experts on Beatle history to
look at the film for clues to determine who made it.
   Vancouver businessman Jim Pattison bought Lennon's vintage 1965
Panther V Rolls for $2.9 million, and it has been on display at the
center since Pattison gave the car to the provincial government
after the Expo 86 world's fair.
</TEXT>
