<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     12-23 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KGB and Police Chiefs Say Ethnic Violence Still Plaguing Caucasus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The KGB and national police chiefs on Friday called
for tougher measures to control ethnic violence that still plagues
Armenia and Azerbaijan despite a month of curfews and army patrols
in the republics, Tass reported.
   The official news agency said KGB chief Vladimir Kryuchkov and
Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin, head of police and troops charged
with keeping order at home, met with other officials to review the
special measures taken Nov. 23.
   On that day, a dusk-to-dawn curfew was put in effect in certain
parts of Armenia and Azerbaijan to quell ethnic violence that killed
at least 31 people.
   Residents of Armenian and Azerbaijan, neighboring Soviet
republics in the Caucasus Mountains, have been at odds historically
for cultural and religious reasons. Most Armenians are Christians
while most Azerbaijanis are Shiite Moslem.
   The Soviet prosecutor's office has filed more than 30 criminal
cases in court stemming from the violence, and investigators
continue to uncover more wrongdoing, Tass said.
   ``At the same time, the situation in the republics remains
complex,'' Tass said. ``Incidents of violence, thefts, instigatory
calls for hurting citizens' rights for national signs, for
disobedience to authorities are still being permitted.''
   It said special concern was generated by crimes committed in the
area of northwestern Armenia devastated by an earthquake on Dec. 7.
   Aside from criticizing ``extremists'' and ``hooliganistic
elements,'' a statement released after the meeting blasted law
enforcement authorities for not stopping the violence. It said
unspecified punitive action was taken against some authorities.
   The statement promised that the full force of law will be used to
stop violence and attempts to spread ethnic hatred.
   Earlier, this month authorities in the Armenian capital, Yerevan,
arrested at least six of the 11 members of the Karabakh Committee,
an unsanctioned political group agitating for Armenian control of
part of Azerbaijan.
   In February, Armenians launched a campaign of demonstrations and
strikes to gain control of Nagorno-Karabakh, a predominantly
Armenian territory in Azerbaijan. The central government in Moscow
has refused to accede to Armenians' demands.
   At the end of February, 32 people, mostly Armenians, were killed
in the first major eruption of violence in the dispute. New violence
broke out last month, and more than 180,000 people have fled their
homes and crossed the border of the two republics.
</TEXT>
