<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador     12-23 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Rebels Attack Defense Ministry; Three Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels attacked the
heavily guarded Defense Ministry with car bombs and
catapult-launched explosives on Friday, killing at least three
people and wounding at least 35, officials said.
   The assault on the military headquarters compound and on a nearby
government health clinic appeared to be part of a major rebel
offensive against the U.S.-backed government of President Jose
Napoleon Duarte.
   Also on Friday, unidentified terrorists blew up a biology
laboratory at National University in San Salvador and shot to death
a night watchman, a school official said. The 35,000-student
university, the biggest in the nation, has been the scene of recent
demonstrations by leftist students.
   Witnesses said four car bombs exploded just outside the Defense
Ministry and at a health clinic 50 yards down the road in this
capital city. A 20-foot-high wall surrounds the compound, which also
houses the headquarters of the armed forces joint chiefs-of-staff.
   Defense Minister Gen. Carlos Eugenio Vides Casanova told a news
conference homemade bombs were also launched from catapults. A
military officer, speaking on condition of anonymity, said three
projectiles fell inside the compound.
   Vides said casualties included 25 passengers in a passing bus who
were wounded in the late morning explosions.
   Dr. Alfredo Galan Avalos, director of the clinic, said flying
glass from car bomb explosions injured 10 health workers. About 60
people work in the clinic, which had about 20 patients at the time
of the attack, he said.
   The defense minister said the three people were killed in the
attack and homemade bombs destroyed four vehicles and three
buildings.
   ``These are acts of terrorism, acts of desperation because the
people have rejected them (the guerrillas). This is nothing more
than a bombardment of the civilian population,'' Lt. Alberto
Navarrete, an army officer, told reporters.
   One victim, 35-year-old Luis Andrade, was running from the
initial blasts when another vehicle exploded, killing him instantly,
his mother, 60-year-old Inez Andrade, said. She said the explosion
blew his leg off.
   The mother said she sat stunned on the ground next to her son's
severed limb until a neighbor brought her a plastic bag minutes
later. She said she put the leg in the bag, got up and walked away,
picking up more pieces of her son's body and placing them in the bag.
   Pools of blood, shattered furniture and smashed glass lay on the
clinic floor.
   Ana Miriam Lopez, 52, said had just left a bus and was across the
street when the first car bomb went off.
   ``It scared me out of my wits,'' she said, sobbing. ``My
grandchildren play right over there. By the grace of God, nothing
happened to them.''
   It was the first attack on the Defense Ministry since the
guerrillas launched their war to overthrow the government in October
1979. The conflict has killed an estimated 65,500 people.
   Terrorists set off three bombs at National University, blowing up
a biology laboratory, a school official said, speaking on the
condition of anonymity. They also shot to death watchman Roberto
Aguirre, he said.
   No one claimed responsibility and police said they had no clues.
University Rector Luis Argueta Antillon accused the military, the
government and right-wing terrorists of responsibility, but offered
no evidence.
   Five provincial town mayors resigned on Friday, bringing to 12
the number of mayors who quit in the past three months after
guerrilla death threats.
   The rebels killed nine mayors in 1988, saying they ``executed''
the mayors for their part in installing ``the U.S.-imposed
counterinsurgency plan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
