<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-ReliefPlane     12-23 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Relief Plane,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Blame Yugoslav Pilots for Crash of Relief Plane</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Quake Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yugoslav relief flight to the earthquake zone in
Soviet Armenia crashed Dec. 12 because the pilots set the
Soviet-built plane's altitude instruments improperly, a Soviet
investigator said Friday.
   The crash at Yerevan, the Armenian capital, killed all seven
people on the An-12 transport. It was the second plane crash in the
international relief airlift that followed the Dec. 7 earthquake
that killed at least 55,000 people.
   A plane carrying Soviet soldiers crashed the day before while
approaching to land at the quake-ravaged city of Leninakan, killing
the 78 people aboard.
   Izvestia, the government newspaper, quoted the head of a
commission investigating the Yugoslav crash as saying ground
controllers gave the pilots correct information but they did not
confirm receiving it and the controllers did not request
confirmation.
   Rudolf Teimurazov, the commission chairman, said the pilots did
not set their altimeters or prepare for landing by extending landing
gear and wing flaps, Izvestia reported.
   ``It is absolutely obvious that the Yugoslav pilots were in a
hurry,'' the paper commented. ``This is understandable: they wanted
to deliver the quake relief supplies as soon as possible.''
   Shortly after the crash, the official Yugoslav news agency Tanjug
quoted a Yugoslav pilot who landed at Yerevan later as saying the
accident may have resulted from a misunderstanding between the crew
and ground controllers.
</TEXT>
