<1ST_LINE>r i AM-HamadiTrial     12-23 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi Trial,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Will Ask Another American to Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief judge in the trial of
confessed TWA hijacker Mohammed Ali Hamadi said Friday that another
American witness will be asked to travel to West Germany and testify.
   Richard Young Moon, a physician, sat near U.S. Navy diver Robert
Stethem, who was beaten and killed during the hijacking.
   Hamadi is charged with murder and air piracy in the June 1985
commandeering of TWA Flight 847 to Beirut, in which 39 Americans
were held hostage 17 days. He admits being one of the hijackers, but
denies killing Stethem.
   Chief Judge Heiner Mueckenberger said Moon would be asked to
testify when the trial resumes Jan. 17 after a holiday recess.
   According to court records, Moon sat near Stethem after the diver
was beaten and before he was killed. Stethem was shot behind a
closed curtain and no one has testified to seeing who killed him.
   More than two dozen American passengers and crew have testified
since the trial began nearly six months ago, describing how Hamadi
and the other hijacker, identifed in court records as Hassan
Ezzeddine, beat Stethem and other passengers.
   Also at Friday's session, Mueckenberger discussed a defense
motion made Dec. 13 that President Hafez Assad of Syria and Nabih
Berri, leader of the Shiite Moslem militia Amal in Lebanon, be asked
to testify.
   Gabriele Steck-Bromme, a defense lawyer, said at the time she
wanted Assad and Berri to be questioned about what she called a
pledge by U.S. authorities not to prosecute the hijackers if the TWA
airplane hostages were released.
   Berri was instrumental in negotiating the release and the
hostages were taken to Damascus, capital of Syria.
   Mueckenberger said Friday he did not feel testimony by Assad or
Berri had ``any meaning'' in the case and doubted either would come
if asked.
   U.S. officials denied when the hostages were released that any
deal had been made.
</TEXT>
