<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     12-23 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government To Let State Of Emergency Lapse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government announced Friday it will
allow the 5-year-old state of emergency to lapse next month, hoping
that Sinhalese radicals will stop engaging in violence and join the
democratic process.
   ``It is our present intention not to extend the emergency when it
lapses on Jan. 15,'' the national security minister, Lalith
Athulathmudali, told a news conference.
   He said the government will also consider releasing 2,200
political prisoners and reopening schools and universities closed
for up to three years due to the violence.
   The emergency was imposed in May 1983 in an effort to quell an
insurgency by minority Tamils against the Sinhalese majority that
has left 8,500 people dead. Parliament has extended the emergency
every month since then, giving security forces sweeping powers to
search homes, arrest and detain people without charge and shoot
violators.
   For 17 months, the extremist Sinhalese group the People's
Liberation Front has waged a campaign to overthrow the government,
saying it conceded too much to the Tamils in a 1987 peace accord.
   The accord provides for limited autonomy for the Tamils and
places 47,000 Indian peacekeeping soldiers on Sri Lankan soil.
   The Tamils, who are mostly Hindus, complain they have been denied
jobs and education by the Sinhalese, who run the government and the
military.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent and the predominantly Buddhist
Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the island's 16 million people.
   Prime Minister Ranasinghe Premadasa, a Sinhalese, was elected
president last Monday and called on Sinahlese extremists to end the
violence and join the democratic process. Parliamentary elections
are to be held Feb. 15.
   Athulathumadali said he did not know whether extremists responded
to Premadasa's appeal for peace but added: ``Incidents of violence
appear to be less and there seems to be no clear rejection to the
open, wide-angled request for them to come into the political
mainstream.''
</TEXT>
