<DOCNO> AP881223-0163 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1916EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PolygamistTrial     12-23 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial,0773</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polygamist Clan's Courtroom Battles Over, Year After Bloody
Shootout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEG McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a year after a polygamist clan began
a fatal confrontation with the law, a jury's verdict has ended
another chapter in a saga begun 15 years ago on the family's
northern Utah homestead.
   The homicide convictions of three young clan members, said one
prosecutor, puts to rest the ``legend of John Singer,'' whose 1979
death at the hands of Utah lawmen triggered the bombing of a Mormon
chapel last January and the clan's 13-day armed standoff at their
Marion farm.
   An eight-member 3rd District Court jury in Coalville on Thursday
convicted clan patriarch Addam Swapp, 27, and Singer's son, John
Timothy Singer, 22, of manslaughter in the death of state
Corrections Lt. Fred House, gunned down during a botched arrest that
ended the siege.
   Addam's brother, Jonathan Swapp, 21, was convicted of negligent
homicide. Singer admitted firing the fatal shot and Jonathan said he
also shot his rifle, but Addam Swapp, who was seriously wounded by
an FBI sharpshooter, insisted he never fired.
   ``It's over,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney Dave Schwendiman, who
also prosecuted the trio and Singer's widow, Vickie, in federal
court last spring.
   ``They just simply can't bring John Singer out to justify what
they have done and want to do,'' he said. ``It's over, and if this
year hasn't proved that in spades, nothing will.''
   It was 1973 when John Singer, a German immigrant and
excommunicated Mormon who embraced polygamy and other Mormon
fundamentalist beliefs, pulled his children from public schools he
believed were rife with dangerously liberal teachings.
   But the decision to keep the children out of school embroiled him
in an escalating dispute with the law, and in 1979, one of several
deputies trying to serve an arrest warrant felled him with a shotgun
blast when he purportedly brandished a pistol.
   Clan members believe Singer was shot in the back as part of a
conspiracy among lawmen and the Mormon Church, which banned polygamy
in 1890.
   Vickie Singer kept her six children on the farm, although
Singer's second wife left. In 1980, the farm became home to Addam
Swapp, also an excommunicated Mormon, whose married two of Mrs.
Singer's daughters.
   The ensuing years brought a series of troubles, including feuds
with neighbors over water rights and an accident that left John
Timothy Singer a paraplegic. A federal judge dismissed Mrs. Singer's
wrongful death lawsuit in 1987, fueling the family's distrust of
secular and religious authority.
   Summit County Sheriff Fred Eley said Addam Swapp further
antagonized the community late in last year when he began sending
fiery letters to state and local officials, accusing them of
murdering Singer and containing religious references to bloodshed
and destruction. Eley obtained an arrest warrant after Swapp fired a
gun into the air when Eley went to the farm to talk to him.
   Swapp remained holed up on the farm until the night of Jan. 16,
when he planted 87 sticks of dynamite in the chapel, an act he said
was a divinely inspired signal for Singer's resurrection and the
fall of a corrupt church and state. It was the bombing of the chapel
that touched off the siege that ended in House's death.
   ``John Singer never would have blown up a church or done anything
like that,'' Eley said. ``I could see where John was coming from,
and I saw Addam as nothing more than a terrorist.''
   Sentincing on the state convictions was set for Jan. 20.
   Addam Swapp faces a sentence of five years to life, as does John
Timothy Singer. Jonathan Swapp faces a maximum of a year in jail.
The three already have received federal sentences of 10 or 15 years
for the bombing convictions. Mrs. Singer is serving a five-year
federal term; she was not charged in state court.
   Swapp, who wept as he held two of his sons after the trial, did
not make a public statement after Thursday's verdicts. But his elder
wife, Heidi, said she still believes in her husband's cause and in
his innocence.
   ``This is in God's hands,'' she said. ``Only God knows the
truth.''
   The Singer-Swapp family remains on the farm in Marion, said
Swapp's attorney, Bill Morrison. The family has been peaceful, but
Eley said their neighbors still keep watch for any unusual activity.
   ``How long it will last, I don't know, Eley said. ``I hope it's
over, and maybe they do, too. Maybe they've been through enough.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
