<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash 2ndLd-Writethru a0672 12-23 1144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0672,1177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cockpit Recording Has `Faint Noise' at Point of Disaster</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 38th graf pvs, _An Air India ... UPDATING with nothing
found. Picks up 39th graf, _An unattended ... Minor editing
throughout to TRIM.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos XDUM1,LON1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cockpit recording of Pan Am Flight
103's final minutes ended with a brief, mysterious ``faint noise''
and gave no sign that the pilots knew their Boeing 747 was doomed,
investigators said Friday.
   Conversations captured by the ``black box'' that records all
cockpit activity was normal up to the ``faint noise at the end which
needs a bit more analysis,'' said Paul McKie, a Department of
Transport spokesman.
   Mick Charles of the department's Air Accident Investigation
Branch, who is heading a team of 40 U.S. and British investigators
at the crash site, said: ``We have no evidence whatsoever yet of
sabotage.''
   The plane, flying from London to New York, broke up at 31,000
feet Wednesday night, killing all 258 people aboard and bombarding
the Scottish countryside with flaming wreckage over a 10-mile radius.
   Flowers arrived at the scene Friday. A passenger who had left the
flight at London sent a bouquet to a child flying on to New York,
with the message: ``To the little girl in the red dress who lies
here, who made my flight from Frankfurt such fun. You didn't deserve
this.''
   Suspicions of sabotage were prompted by the inexplicable sudden
breakup of the plane, a claim of responsibility and disclosures that
the U.S. government had been warned of a plot to bomb a Pan Am
flight between Frankfurt and New York in December.
   Flight 103 originated in Frankfurt with a Boeing 727, and
switched to a Boeing 747 from London's Heathrow Airport.
   Soldiers hacked open the nose section, lying on its side in a
field, and removed the bodies of crew members on stretchers and
under tarpaulins.
   From 20 to 30 relatives of victims arrived in Lockerbie, the
Scottish village that bore the brunt of the crash, and 155 bodies
were placed in makeshift morgues in the town hall and ice rink.
   The relatives included at least seven Americans. They were
advised against visiting the wreckage, said Superintendent Angus
Kennedy, a police spokesman in Lockerbie.
   More than 600 police and military personnel spent Friday scouring
the countryside for bodies and wreckage, but only one more body was
found. Kennedy said whether it was of a passenger or ground victim
was not known.
   Fourteen adults and three children were missing in the Lockerbie
area and there was no word on the occupants of three cars hit by
wreckage and gutted on a nearby highway, Kennedy said.
   He said it had been learned the driver of a fourth car was
treated for injuries Wednesday night and released, and the driver of
a fifth car was a villager and counted among the 17 residents listed
as missing.
   Arc lights and heavy lifting equipment were brought in to speed
the search. Searchers moved shoulder to shoulder across fields and
marshes, trying to collect every scrap of evidence.
   A faint smell of aviation fuel lingered.
   During the night, a party of Jewish youths clambered over the
rubble, apparently searching for holy items like prayer books that
might have been with Jewish passengers and require ritual burial.
   All indications were that the plane broke up in seconds, and that
the cockpit never knew of the imminent catastrophe.
   ``There were no abnormal noises on the (cockpit recorder's) tape
until the signals ended abruptly with the aircraft cruising at
31,000 feet,'' said McKie.
   There was ``nothing in the conversations to indicate anything was
wrong,'' he said, adding that no conclusions could be drawn yet from
the noise at the end of the tape.
   On Thursday, Transport Secretary Paul Channon said the plane's
radar blip on the Scottish ground control screens ``split into
several returns'' before vanishing.
   Charles told a news conference the wreckage was ``spread over a
very, very long wreckage trail,'' but added this did not indicate
sabotage. The spread was normal, given the plane's altitude and the
115-knot winds at 31,000 feet.
   People have found papers, clothing and mail up to 70 miles from
Lockerbie. Three teen-age boys found a bundle of $500,000 in
travelers' checks in the hills near their home six miles from
Lockerbie, police said Friday.
   ``To try and prejudge this case would be totally wrong. There are
obviously a number of potential causes for an in-flight breakup. We
are looking for evidence to try and point us in the right direction.
To suggest that it would be one or the other at this stage would be
wrong,'' Charles said.
   President Reagan sent a message to the 2,500 people of Lockerbie
saying: ``Our hearts go out to you on this tragic occasion which
marred what should have been a season of joy.''
   Frank Park of the local district council wrote back: ``Our small
community has suffered much but our sadness is even greater when we
think of the loss of so many people from the United States. Our
thoughts are with their friends and relatives wherever they may be.''
   A newspaper Friday quoted a security source as saying
investigators were taking ``very seriously'' a group's claim of
responsibility.
   The Independent quoted the source as saying the group is thought
to have sought revenge for the July 3 downing of an Iranian jetliner
by a U.S. warship in the Persian Gulf.
   An anonymous caller to The Associated Press in London claimed
Thursday the Guardians of the Islamic Revolution was responsible for
the crash.
   A political dispute arose over the Transport Department's
disclosure that it knew of a bomb threat two weeks before the crash
but did not pass it on to Heathrow or the public.
   U.S. officials told British officials that an anonymous caller to
the U.S. Embassy in Helsinki, Finland, said Dec. 5 that a bomb would
be planted aboard a Pan Am flight from Frankfurt to the United
States within two weeks.
   Transport Minister Michael Portillo said it was ``confidential,
classified U.S. intelligence information and we didn't have the
right to divulge it.''
   He said the warning prompted an assessment of Heathrow security
for U.S. flights. The security was judged to be appropriate.
   Also on Friday:
   _An Air India jumbo jet bound for New York with 250 people aboard
returned to London after Air India in New York received an anonymous
bomb threat, officials said. The plane was evacuated at Heathrow but
the airline said nothing suspicious was found.
   _An unattended suitcase found at Heathrow forced hundreds of
Christmas travelers to evacuate one of four terminals for nearly an
hour, but it was found to contain only clothing, officials said.
   _A British Airways Tristar arrived at Heathrow after making a
10-hour unscheduled stop in Rome because of a bomb threat.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
