<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DartmouthReview     12-23 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dartmouth Review,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Unfairly Punished Review Editors, Lawyer Charges</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of 7th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHARLENE L. FU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVERHILL, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former chairman of Dartmouth's board
of trustees said Friday that he did not influence a disciplinary
panel that suspended two student journalists although he was unhappy
with their publication.
   At a court hearing to determine whether the two stdents should be
reinstated, Norman McCulloch testified his initial reaction to the
off-campus, conservative Dartmouth Review was favorable.
   ``I thought it was extremely important to have a conservative
viewpoint demonstrated and published on campus,'' McCulloch said in
Grafton County Superior Court. ``But I became really disenchanted
when the Review began to go away from a focus on the issues and
began to focus on personalities.''
   McCulloch said, however, that he did not try to influence the
campuswide disciplinary board that suspended former Review editors
Christopher Baldwin and John Sutter for 18 months in March.
   Baldwin, 21, of Hinsdale, Ill., and Sutter, 22, of St. Louis want
Judge Bruce Mohl to let them return to school before their
suspensions expire in September. Mohl is expected to rule before
classes resume Jan. 3.
   They and two other students were accused of harassing music
professor William Cole during a classroom confrontation after a
Review article disparaged Cole's course.
   Cole, who is black, once was described by the Review as looking
``like a used Brillo pad.'' He testified this week that he
considered the latest Review criticisms racially motivated, a charge
denied by Sutter and Baldwin.
   The hearing ended Friday after the judge prevented the school's
lawyer from trying to show that the former editors sought a heavy
penalty in order to generate more publicity for their case.
   Mohl ruled as irrelevant an attempt by Dartmouth lawyer James
Middleton to show that Baldwin and Sutter intentionally sought the
18-month suspension.
   Middleton argued it was ``extremely relevant'' because it was
``important to get a maximum suspension and therefore to get maximum
press exposure.''
   The students' lawyer, Harvey Myerson, disputed Middleton's claim,
calling it ``one of the most extraordinary things I've ever heard.''
   When the hearing began Monday, Myerson said the suspensions had
national implications because of their chilling effect on college
journalists nationwide. But Mohl also called that argument
irrelevant.
   The two students argue that Dartmouth discriminates against
conservatives, disciplining them for infractions more harshly than
liberal students, a charge college officials deny. Two lawsuits, one
in state and one in federal court, have been filed against the
school based on this allegation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
