<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 2212EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-Scene 2ndLd-Writethru a0673 12-23 0731</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Scene, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0673,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Scenes Contrast With a Grim Task</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 9-10 pvs `Indeed on Friday ...' with 2 grafs to
recast reflectling that fate of occupants of three cars gutted by
the falling debris is not known. PICKS up 11th graf pvs: The rest of
...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOCKERBIE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a high school gymnasium against a
backdrop of honor rolls dating back four decades, a Royal Air Force
officer dispatches helicopter crews to hoist bodies and wreckage
from the Scottish countryside.
   In the school's library, where children's paintings are taped to
the book shelves, Pan Am staff cluster around Flight 103's passenger
lists, trying to match bodies to names.
   Outside the town hall, which contains more than 80 bodies, are
typewritten lists of villagers evacuated from their homes when the
Boeing 747 fell from the sky.
   So while the town hall is now a morgue, the red-brick Lockerbie
Academy, the town's only high school, has become headquarters for
the search and investigation operation for Britain's worst ever air
crash.
   The 900 students, from surrounding villages, are on Christmas
vacation.
   Their school has been taken over by the First Battalion of the
Royal Highland Fusiliers, one of Scotland's oldest regiments.
   They have set up operations on the school hall stage. Officers
work under a board bearing the regiment's name and its previous
title, Princess Margaret's Own Glasgow and Ayrshire Regiment.
   People drift by and stop to read the list posted outside the town
hall. A policeman on guard tries to be reassuring. ``Just because a
name isn't there doesn't mean they're dead,'' he tells each person
who looks at the list.
   Indeed, on Friday a Lockerbie woman listed as missing turned out
to be staying with relatives.
   But police list 17 other villagers as missing, and the fate of
occupants of three cars that were gutted by falling debris on the
nearby highway was not known. Authorities updated their list of
missing saying the driver of one car hit by flaming wreckage was
treated for injuries and released, and the occupant of another
vehicle had been counted twice.
   The rest of the 155 bodies collected by nightfall Friday are in
the Lockerbie skating rink.
   Flowers are piling up outside the makeshift morgues. A passenger
who left the flight in London sent a bouquet to a child flying on to
New York with the message:
   ``To the little girl in the red dress who lies here, who made my
flight from Frankfurt such fun. You didn't deserve this.''
   Paper Christmas decorations made by the pupils dangle from
exercise bars in the school hall. Class blackboards carry lists for
dog handlers, helicopter crews and police who scour the countryside
for bodies and debris.
   Soldiers in camouflage uniforms and berets with the distinctive
white cockade of Scottish regiments trudge out with spades or drive
away in army trucks.
   During the night, Jewish youths from Gateshead in northern
England clambered over rubble, apparently looking for fragments of
holy items belonging to Jews on the plane. They were sent here by
the Gateshead Hevre Kadisha, or burial society.
   Police from the Dumfries and Galloway county force, which with
350 uniformed officers is the tiniest in Britain, mingle with police
from forces throughout Scotland.
   Officers from the huge neighboring county force, the 7,000-member
Strathclyde Constabulary, have arrived in the hundreds to help out
in Lockerbie.
   In an upstairs classroom, with lesson timetables and
advertisements for performances of the Scottish National Youth
Orchestra pinned to notice boards, the head of the Dumfries force,
John Boyd, confers with senior officers.
   The largest classroom is packed with rows of computers into which
police and civilian personnel feed every scrap of information
brought back from the crash site in Lockerbie and sprawling out to a
10-mile radius around the town.
   Anything that is found _ from the vital flight recorders
chronicling the airliner's last moments, to a scorched Christmas
card addressed to addresses in the United States _ are logged into
the computers.
   ``It's called Holmes. That stands for Home Office Large Major
Enquiry System,'' said Superintendent Angus Kennedy, Strathclyde's
press officer.
   Kennedy said the local force didn't have such a system, and the
computers were brought from Strathclyde and other forces.
   ``They've never had anything like this _ there's never been
anything like this in Scotland,'' he said.
</TEXT>
