<HEAD>Transport Minister Takes Vacation During Crash Investigation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs to reflect that the total number of dead on
the ground is not yet certain. PICKS up 4th pvs `Channon and his ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGETOWN, Barbados (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Channon, the British
transportation secretary, arrived in Barbados for a Caribbean
vacation Friday. His department is in charge of investigating the
Pan Am crash in Scotland.
   Britain's opposition Labor Party said it was ``unbelievable'' of
Channon to take a holiday during the investigation into Britain's
worst aviation disaster.
   The jumbo jet broke up in the air Wednesday night and crashed
into the village of Lockerbie, killing all 258 people aboard.
   Channon and his wife Ingrid were met on the tarmac by the airport
manager and walked directly to the arrival hall, making no comment.
   He was seen checking in with Mustique Airways and was believed to
be flying to the tiny island about 40 miles away. Mustique, in the
Grenadines chain, is a popular getaway isle for such famous people
as Mick Jagger and Princess Margaret, sister of Queen of Elizabeth
II.
   The British Embassy in Barbados said it had no information on
Channon's visit because he was not on official business.
   In London, the Trade Ministry said he would be kept informed on
the investigation and planned to return soon after Christmas, but
would fly home earlier if necessary.
   John Prescott, the Labor Party transport spokesman on
transportation, said: ``It is unbelievable. It is quite intolerable
and totally insensitive for the transport secretary to leave for his
holidays so soon after Britain's worst aviation disaster, when
bodies are still being retrieved and a major security review is
under way.''
   Prescott said Margaret Thatcher, the Conservative prime minister,
should ``call him back immediately'' and declared: ``Such lack of
judgment should justify his removal.''
   Geoffrey Dickens, a Conservative member of Parliament, said Labor
was ``trying to make capital out of other people's misery and
death.''
</TEXT>
