<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Alert, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0663,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Calls for Increased Security at U.S., Foreign Airports</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs bgng, `McArtor, in,' to reflect changing
information from Scotland on number of people missing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speculation that an explosion may have caused a
Pan American World Airways jet to crash in Scotland has prompted the
Federal Aviation Administration to issue a call for increased
security at airports worldwide, officials said Friday.
   FAA Administrator Allan McArtor told reporters that the security
alert was sent to airlines, foreign governments and major airports
both in the United States and abroad on Thursday.
   He said it was prompted by a combination of factors, including
the Pan Am crash Wednesday, the heavy Christmas travel rush and
``what obviously can be considered a heightening of world tensions''
as it pertains to terrorist activities.
   The alert was not prompted by any single threat or piece of
intelligence information, officials said.
   McArtor, in an interview with a small group of reporters,
declined to discuss specifically the Pan Am crash that killed all
258 people aboard a Boeing 747 jumbo jet and leaving at least 17
people missing on the ground. The plane apparently broke apart in
the air, possibly because of a terrorist bomb.
   The crash came two weeks after the FAA sent the State Department
a bulletin warning that Pan Am might be the subject of a terrorist
bombing on its flights from Frankfurt, West Germany. The Boeing 747
that crashed was Flight 103, which had originated at Frankfurt.
   Disclosure of the FAA bulletin in early December _ the 23rd such
alert this year _ has prompted questions over whether such notices
should be shared with the public.
   President Reagan said earlier Friday that a public warning based
on an anonymous telephone call _ as was the case with the alert
involving Pan Am _ would have been an overreaction. It ``would
literally have closed down air traffic in the world,'' Reagan said
in answer to a reporter's question.
   McArtor praised Pan Am's response to the alert at the Frankfurt
airport, saying the airline had imposed ``a very heightened level of
security.'' He said Pan Am's precautions at London's Heathrow
Airport, from which Flight 103 departed 54 minutes before the crash,
were still under review.
   At Frankfurt, McArtor said, Pan Am briefed gate personnel about
the possible threat, kept ground baggage handlers and caterers
``under constant surveillance'' and checked all luggage by X-ray
instead of only at random. All passengers and their bags also were
matched prior to boarding, he said.
   McArtor said that while there is no hard evidence of sabotage in
connection with Flight 103, he is concerned about the possibility
that a bomb could be placed aboard the jetliner at two airports
where security precautions are among the best in the world and where
a heightened alert was in effect.
   ``If there was a door (of opportunity for terrorists) left open,
we've got to find out what allowed that and close that door,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
