<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0662 12-23 0552</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Writes Ortega On Strengthening World Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs UPDATING with Contras' Christmas message
and details; govt. technicians saying strategic deep-water port hurt
by hurricane. Pickup 12th graf `Also on...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect George Bush has written
President Daniel Ortega saying he wants to work toward strengthening
world peace, the leftist Sandinista government said Friday.
   The Nicaraguan rebels issued their Christmas message Friday,
vowing not to lay down their arms until there is democracy.
``Certainly it will be a sad Christmas but the near future is filled
with hope,'' said the Contras, as the rebels are known.
   A statement from Ortega's press office said Bush's letter was in
reply to a message of congratulations Ortega sent Bush on his
election in November.
   The New York Times recently quoted Ortega as saying he would
present a peace proposal to Bush but insisted any talks with the
United States center on security issues, not Nicaragua's internal
politics.
   For the past eight years, the United States has pressured the
Sandinistas to undertake democratic reforms and to cut their
military ties with Cuba and the Soviet Union. Washington has
supported the Contras since 1981 as part of that campaign.
   The Sandinistas came to power in a 1979 popular revolution that
overthrew rightist President Anastasio Somoza, promising to install
a ``democratic, pluralistic'' government.
   U.S. officials and opposition leaders accused the Sandinistas of
pursuing repressive policies, including national emergency laws of
1980-87 that imposed press censorship and restricted individual
freedoms.
   In 1981, the Reagan administration cut off all economic aid to
Nicaragua.
   Three years ago it imposed a trade embargo, saying Nicaragua was
a beachhead from which to spread communism in Central America.
   U.S.-Nicaraguan talks in 1985 to explore ways of improving
relations ended in deadlock.
   Friday's statement, published by the Sandinista newspaper
Barricada under the title `Message From Bush To Daniel,'' said
Ortega received the vice president's letter on Thursday.
   ``Among other concepts, President-elect Bush said he
enthusiastically looked forward to working to strengthen world
peace,'' it said.
   The Contras' message, read by telephone from the group's offices
in Miami, said the rebels will only lay down their arms ``in
exchange for a real democracy.''
   ``Our combatants maintain their discipline and are ready to
defend the honor of the nation,'' the Contra statement said. ``It is
not Nicaraguan to try to impose a slave regime when Nicaragua wants
liberty.''
   In other developments, government technicians speaking on
condition of anonymity said work on an eastern port that could
receive huge arms shipments was dealt a serious setback by
sedimentation from Hurricane Joan in October.
   Nicaraguan economists have said the government, strapped by a
severe economic crisis, does not have the resources necessary to
finish the deep water port known as The Bluff.
   Also on Friday, the pro-government newspaper El Nuevo Diario said
the Soviet Union donated a TU-154 jetliner and granted state-run
Aeronica airline credits to buy two AN-32 passenger planes. It put
the cost of the three airliners at $52.8 million.
   The TU-154 can carry 141 pasengers will be used international
routes. The AN-32s will be used on domestic flights, replacing older
American planes which cannot be serviced due to lack of spare parts
arising from the U.S. trade embargo.
</TEXT>
