<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 2247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DuelingSantas     12-23 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dueling Santas,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cadillac Santa Prompts Mercedes-Benz Copycat To Help Homeless Too</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A self-styled Santa driving a Mercedes-Benz
copied his Cadillac-driving counterpart Friday and doled out $10
bills to a hoard of Skid Row homeless.
   The cigar-smoking Samaritan, wearing a bright red, three-piece
suit and a crimson fedora, ``said he read about the Cadillac Santa
and thought he could do better,'' said Clancy Imislund, spokesman
for the Midnight Mission.
   The Mercedes man's outpouring of altruism followed by a day the
seventh annual visit to the mission by a secretive philanthropist
known as the Cadillac Santa, who also shares holiday cheer with
street dwellers in the form of cold, hard cash.
   The latest well-heeled Santa handed out about $3,000, while the
Cadillac-driving benefactor spent about twice as much. The Cadillac
Santa gave out more largely because the homeless have learned to
gather and wait for him after seven years.
   The Mercedes Santa's warmth made up for his gaudy outfit,
Imislund said.
   ``With a red suit, red tie and red fedora, it was the most
God-awful getup you could imagine, but his heart was in the right
place and nobody cared what he was wearing,'' he said.
   ``He was ho-ho-hoing like nobody's business, and just like the
other one, wouldn't reveal who he is.''
   The Midnight Mission serves 1,650 meals a day to homeless men,
women and children, Imislund said.
