<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:MississippiBurning ADV26   12-23 1150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Mississippi Burning, ADV 26,1180</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Dec. 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Civil Rights Movement Comes to the Screen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILLEL ITALIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the summer of 1964, 1,000 young volunteers
from mainstream America arrived in Mississippi to help register
black voters. They were idealistic and committed, believing their
enthusiasm and good intentions could make a difference.
   But it was a time when Martin Luther King Jr.'s ``dream'' had not
yet stemmed the hate and violence of segregation: During that season
of the Mississippi Summer Project there were 1,000 arrests, 30
bombings, 35 churches burned, 80 people beaten and at least six
murders.
   Three of those murders are the focus of Alan Parker's new movie,
``Mississippi Burning,'' a fictionalized account of the slaying of
James Chaney, Andrew Goodman and Michael Schwerner.
   The story of that racially explosive summer when Goodman, a
student at Queens College, and Schwerner and Chaney, members of CORE
(Congress of Racial Equality), disappeared and were killed is told
through the eyes of two FBI agents, portrayed by Gene Hackman and
Willem DaFoe.
   This was the intention of screenwriter Chris Gerolmo who thought
the case was a ``good story'' that would be interesting to tell from
the perspective of the investigators.
   ``I never understood this to be Hollywood's `civil rights'
picture,'' he said. ``It's an exciting story about something
important.
   ``You see our moral failures and greatness. It allows us to see
America at its very worst and also to see people who displayed great
moral courage. That's a real story.''
   However, what emerges on the screen is more a detective story
than a portrait of a great struggle, and that has some critics and
civil rights workers miffed. The heroes are not those who at times
sacrificed their lives or well-being to ensure black civil rights,
but the FBI.
   ``It was unfortunate that it was so narrow in scope that it did
not show one black role model that today's youth who look at the
movie could remember,'' said Myrlie Evers, commissioner of Public
Works in Los Angeles, whose husband, Medgar, a field secretary for
the NAACP, was shot to death by white segregationists outside their
home in 1963.
   ``In the state of Mississippi, not one leader was mentioned _ not
Rev. (George) Lee, who gave his life so that people could register
and vote, ... no (activist) Fannie Lou Hamer. Certainly no Medgar
Evers, who was the pioneer, the motivator of the civil rights
movement in Mississippi.''
   She also took issue with Parker's portrayal of the agents as
compassionate (Dafoe marches with mourners at Chaney's funeral).
   ``I don't remember the FBI agents we came in contact with as
being concerned with the health and welfare of the blacks,'' Evers
said. ``We were more or less harassed by them.''
   And she challenged the filmmakers' treatment of blacks: ``The
fear that you saw in the expression of the actors who played the
roles of blacks was certainly accurate during that time, but to
simply show fear and no courage is very, very sad.''
   Mary King, a white Southerner who worked in the Summer Project
and knew the slain volunteers, talks about the FBI in her book,
``Freedom Song,'' published last year by William Morrow and Co.:
   ``Practically everyone working in the civil rights movement knew
from firsthand experience of the duplicity of the FBI. In many
instances, FBI agents could be seen watching a demonstration while
fraternizing with sheriffs and local law officers. ... It has now
become commonly accepted that some of these agents were themselves
members of the Ku Klux Klan.''
   Despite her misgivings, Evers said ``Mississippi Burning'' (the
name of the FBI file on the case) was nevertheless a powerful film.
   ``The beatings, the lynchings, the burnings, I remember them,''
she said. ``There was a flood of remembering; I could almost reach
out and touch the screen and feel the pain. But my pain was
doublefold _ not only what I saw on the screen ... but also the
neglect in telling the entire story.''
   The film could be a contender in the upcoming Academy Award race,
and has already won awards from the National Board of Review of
Motion Pictures for best director, best actor (Hackman) and best
supporting actress (Frances McDormand).
   It takes place in 1964, the year President Lyndon Johnson signed
the Civil Rights Act, and when King won the Nobel Prize for Peace.
It also was one of the most racially violent years of the decade
with riots, beatings, bombings and murders.
   The date is June 21: Chaney, Goodman and Schwerner are stopped by
a group of white police and civilians while driving to Philadelphia,
Miss., to investigate the burning of a black church and some
beatings. The whites are openly hostile; one sticks a gun in the
driver's ear and pulls the trigger.
   The trio had gone to Mississippi where only 5 percent of the
black population, which made up 45 percent of the state, was
registered to vote.
   A few days after they failed to check in with the project, as
they were required to do when in the field, Schwerner's charred
station wagon was discovered in Bogue Chitto Creek, 15 miles north
of Philadelphia. Their bodies were found in a crude grave on a
nearby farm on Aug. 4. The three had been shot, and Chaney's skull
had been fractured from a severe beating. In December, 21 whites
were arrested. Murder charges were dropped in state court, but six
were later convicted in federal court for violating civil rights
laws.
   Gerolmo interpreted some of the story himself. For instance, the
identity of the person who tipped off the FBI about where the bodies
were buried remains unknown. In the movie, though, the informant
turns out to be the deputy sheriff's wife (McDormand). Gerolmo
considered it a logical plot twist.
   ``The wives were often a source of information,'' he said.
   Gerolmo is the son of Frank Gero, a theater manager and producer.
His brother, sculptor Mark Gero, is married to the actress Liza
Minnelli. He was born in Chicago and attended Harvard University
where he taught filmmaking before going into off-Broadway theatrical
production. His first movie, ``Miles From Home,'' was a box-office
bomb.
   A New York grade schooler when Chaney, Goodman and Schwerner were
killed, the incident greatly affected his way of thinking.
   ``It was the first time I ever considered that our country could
be wrong,'' he said. ``My mother was active in the civil right
movement. She marched from Selma to Montgomery, and we used to
discuss it around the house.''
   With ``Mississippi Burning,'' he hoped to depict American life in
general. Filmmakers John Ford and Frank Capra were his inspirations.
   ``Capra, Ford, they took on the task to say what America is,''
Gerolmo said. ``It has something to do with taking responsibility.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
