<NOTE>$Adv06-08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Jan. 6-8, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Veronica Hamel Is Israeli Woman in Miniseries Thriller</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the manner of ``Casablanca,'' the NBC
miniseries ``Twist of Fate'' was filmed with different endings.
   ``The story was very cleverly orchestrated so that it could be
cut three different ways,'' said Veronica Hamel, formerly of ``Hill
Street Blues,'' who stars in the international thriller.
   ``I'm happy with the choice they made, because it was my choice.
It's good that people can creatively agree and pull their resources
together. I felt very good working on this, which is not always the
case.''
   Hamel stars with Ben Cross, Bruce Greenwood, John Glover and
Sarah Jessica Parker in this story told against the background of
World War II, the Holocaust and the founding of Israel. The
four-hour miniseries, which airs Sunday and Monday, is based on the
novel ``Pursuit'' by Robert L. Fish.
   ``It's a good yarn with a lot of twists,'' said Hamel. ``It's not
just about the Holocaust. It's about people and relationships.''
   The show, as the title indicates, is indeed filled with twists.
   Briefly, German SS officer Helmet Von Schraeder (Greenwood),
fleeing Allied prosecution, has his identity changed through plastic
surgery and poses as Ben Grossman, a Jew (now played by Cross).
Interned in a concentration camp, he is befriended by and gains
respect for his fellow prisoners. Eventually he becomes a founding
father of Israel.
   Greenwood returns later in the miniseries in a dual role as Ben's
grown son who discovers the awful truth about his father and tries
to bring him to justice. Meanwhile, former Nazi colleagues learn the
father's secret and attempt to blackmail him into helping with their
terrorist scheme.
   Hamel plays Deborah, the Jewish woman Ben marries.
   ``As soon as I read the script I liked the feel and texture,''
said Hamel. ``I wanted to climb into her skin. I liked her passion.
She wasn't an appendage to a man. She had her own very strong views.
   ``He meets Deborah when he leaves the prison camp and goes to
Palestine,'' said Hamel. ``She is completely unaware of his past.
She has a philosophy that is a strong as her love. In fact, her
philosophy comes first. She becomes a doctor, but she's not as
political as Golda Meir. But at the end when I'm old, I look like a
cross between Golda Meir and Indira Gandhi.
   ``I have a lot of padding to make me look thicker. That helps,
having all those layers. I have to buy it first, then the audience
will buy it. The first time I saw myself on the screen I started to
giggle.''
   The miniseries was filmed on location in Yugoslavia, where Hamel
got a lot of action playing a member of the Israeli Army. ``This is
probably the closest I'll ever get to playing Harrison Ford,'' she
said. Working in Yugoslavia, she said, was ``like being catapulted
out of your life.''
   The two-part miniseries originally was scheduled for December,
but NBC decided to hold it until after the holidays.
   Hamel, a native of Philadelphia, was a leading model before she
turned to acting. She made her stage debut in an off-off-Broadway
show, ``The Big Knife.'' After several years in dinner-theater
productions, she moved to Los Angeles in 1975 and landed guest shots
on such shows as ``The Rockford Files,'' ``Dallas'' and ``Family.''
   At one point she was cast in ``Charlie's Angels,'' at the time
called ``Harry's Angels.'' She withdrew from the series before it
went into production and the role went to Jaclyn Smith.
   Hamel, who only recently returned from Yugoslavia, is now busy
with her own projects.
   ``I'm looking for a writer for a project I will co-produce and
star in,'' she said. ``It's a two-hour film for TV, and it's not a
pilot. I don't want to do a series. I've done that. It would be hard
to find another as good as `Hill Street Blues.' You have to sign for
seven years and that's a long commitment. It's like a marriage.
`Hill Street' was a class act.
   ``I want to do some movies. But it takes years to get things off
the ground. I have an idea for a feature. I'm looking for a
development deal. I spend a lot of time reading scripts and books.
It's hard to just sit down and read for enjoyment.''
   Hamel devotes part of her time to Stuart House, a center for
sexually abused children. She is on the board of directors. She also
has worked for six years with a rape treatment center.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Jan. 6-8</NOTE>
