<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0556</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s plea bargain to
dodge a criminal indictment brought relief to some exhausted
staffers, but has incited skepticism in Washington and has outraged
dissident employees.
   Sources familiar with internal criticism of the decision by the
huge Wall Street investment banking firm said Thursday the agreement
aimed at settling the biggest securities fraud case in history had
generated a good deal of bitterness and doubts about the future.
   Others said Michael Milken, Drexel's high-yield bond executive
and a key target of the criminal investigation, felt betrayed by the
Drexel decision, which weakens his defense.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The financial markets shrugged off the news that
Wall Street powerhouse Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. had struck a
historic plea bargain with federal prosecutors.
   Even in Drexel's own backyard, the market for high-risk,
high-yield ``junk bonds'' that the investment firm pioneered, news
of the settlement of fraud charges caused nary a ripple Thursday.
   Conventional bonds as well as stocks also failed to show a
reaction. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 4.28
points to 2,160.36.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department reports that orders for
``big ticket'' durable goods, excluding the volatile defense
category, climbed 1.8 percent in November, a healthy increase which
economists took as a sign of continued strength in the new year.
   When defense orders are included in Thursday's report, total
durable goods orders edged up only 0.1 percent in November to a
seasonally-adjusted $122.89 billion.
   That followed a giant 2.9 percent rise in October.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission has testified he is suspicious of opinions written by
hired financial advisers on the fairness of proposed leveraged
buyouts.
   David S. Ruder, offering his personal opinion Thursday, said the
investment banks and others providing such fairness opinions often
receive higher fees if the buyout goes through.
   Ruder also told the House Energy and Commerce telecommunications
and finance subcommittee the SEC is reviewing all aspects of
leveraged buyouts.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 5,000 Polaroid Corp. employees
have signed a petition that sends a clear message to hostile suitor
Shamrock Holdings Inc.: Thanks, but no thanks.
   The petition, which includes signatures from about 60 percent of
Polaroid's worldwide work force, also was designed as a protest
message that corporate takeovers are potentially damaging to
employees.
   ``We don't believe (Shamrock's) takeover of Polaroid is in our
best interests,'' Richard Duffy, a 30-year Polaroid employee and
member of the steering committee for the petition drive, said
Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Macmillan Inc. says the buyout firm Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. has terminated its proposed purchase of four
Macmillan units for $400 million, but the publisher still expects to
find buyers for the properties.
   Macmillan, which was acquired for $2.5 billion last month by
Britain's Maxwell Communication Corp., said Thursday that Kohlberg
Kravis indicated it was dropping the deal due to rising interest
rates and problems in arranging financing for the purchase.
   But a Kohlberg Kravis spokesman said the firm backed out of the
deal because of restrictions set by Macmillan and Maxwell.
</TEXT>
