<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0574</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The final defendant in the giant Washington Public
Power Supply System securities-fraud trial has settled with
class-action plaintiffs for $20 million.
   The settlement by Blyth Eastman PaineWebber Inc., which had acted
as a financial adviser to WPPSS, was confirmed Thursday by Blyth
Eastman attorney James Hagan.
   The end of the trial came nearly six years after the first
lawsuit was filed in the giant legal action that grew from WPPSS'
record default on $2.25 billion in bonds sold to finance two nuclear
power plants.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC Sports has signed an agreement with
Cablevision Systems Corp. to put the Olympics on U.S. cable
television for the first time, in a pooling of TV resources worth an
estimated $300 million.
   The agreement could create several hundred hours of pay-per-view
coverage from the 1992 Barcelona Summer Games in addition to NBC's
planned 160 hours over commercial air waves, NBC Sports President
Arthur Watson said Thursday.
   It was reported earlier this month that NBC was trying to lay off
on cable television about $75 million of its $401 million total
payment for the Barcelona Games.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Trade Commission has issued
complaints against six of the nation's largest book publishers for
allegedly discriminating illegally against independent bookstores by
selling books at discounted prices to major bookstore chains.
   The complaints issued Thursday allege that the six publishers
sell books at lower prices to large bookstore chains, including the
nation's three biggest: Waldenbooks Inc., B. Dalton Bookseller and
Crown Books Corp.
   The complaints were issued against: Harper & Row Publishers Inc.;
Hearst Corp. and William Morrow and Co. Inc.; Macmillan Inc.; Putnam
Berkley Group Inc.; Random House Inc.; and Simon & Schuster Inc.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department is investigating a
revised joint operating agreement involving the Miami Herald and the
Miami News, according to a department spokesman.
   The preliminary investigation will delve into whether there might
be a violation of antitrust laws, Justice spokesman Mark Sheehan
said Thursday.
   Sheehan declined to comment when asked whether the department
would ask that the Miami News be kept open past Dec. 31. He said
there have been instances in which ``we will ask the parties to
freeze the status quo while we sort out the facts.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union and China have bought more
grain from the United States, including wheat sold to Beijing at
subsidized prices, the Agriculture Department reports.
   Moscow's order was for an additional 1 million metric tons of
corn for delivery under a recently extended supply agreement between
the two countries, the department announced Thursday. China bought
400,000 tons of wheat under the subsidy program.
   The latest sales by private exporting companies brought total
corn sold to the Soviets to almost 8.03 million tons in the
agreement's sixth year, which began Oct. 1.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined slightly Thursday. The Dow Jones
average of 30 industrials slipped 4.28 points to 2,160.36.
   The dollar rose against most major currencies. Gold prices edged
higher.
   Bond prices finished mixed.
   Coffee futures prices fell sharply; precious metals futures
continued to rise; grains and soybeans were mixed; livestock and
meat futures were mixed; energy futures rose; and stock-index
futures retreated.
</TEXT>
