<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0044EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     12-23 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Durable Goods Orders Rise; Markets Quiet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy is headed into 1989 with healthy growth in orders for
``big ticket'' durable goods, according to a government report.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that durable goods orders
climbed 1.8 percent in November, not counting the erratic defense
category.
   The report had little effect on the financial markets.
   Including defense orders, total durable goods orders edged up
only 0.1 percent in November to a seasonally adjusted $122.89
billion. That followed a giant 2.9 percent rise in October.
   The overall figure was inflated by a big jump in military orders
in October and then depressed when military orders returned to more
normal levels last month.
   Discounting the swings in defense, orders in the civilian
category climbed 1.8 percent in November, the best showing since a
5.2 percent August increase. Civilin orders had risen only 0.2
percent in October.
   Analysts said they were impressed by the strength in civilian
orders, and said the orders should keep U.S. plants operating busily
through the first half of 1989.
   ``This was an impressive gain and it should pretty much insure
that the economy will keep growing next year,'' said Michael Evans,
head of a Washington forecasting firm.
   Financial markets were quiet Thursday heading into the Christmas
holiday.
   On Wall Street, the stock market posted a modest loss. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials dropped 4.28 points to 2,160.36.
   In the bond market, prices edged up slightly as the yield on the
Treasury's benchmark 30-year bond stood at 8.93 percent.
   The dollar drifted higher against most major currencies in
extremely thin trading. It stood at 1.7729 West German marks and
124.68 Japanese yen in late New York trading.
   Oil prices continued rising. On the New York Mercantile Exchange,
the February contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of U.S. crude, rose 19 cents to $16.49 a barrel after rising
15 cents Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     12-23 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investor optimism that oil prices will continue
rising has strengthened the energy futures market in light,
pre-holiday trading.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the February contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, rose 19
cents to $16.49 a barrel Thursday after rising 15 cents Wednesday.
   Madison Galbraith, an analyst with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures,
said traders were optimistic that prices would rise, and sellers
Thursday were unable to bring the market lower.
   ``We don't have the sentiment that our customers want to be
sellers,'' Galbraith said. ``The market is overall friendly.''
   Traders were upbeat that the price of crude could go to $17 or
$18 a barrel if the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
successfully reduces its production levels, Galbraith said.
   Among refined products traded on the mercantile exchange, the
January contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline settled at 46.57
cents a gallon, up 0.87 cent from the close Wednesday.
   January wholesale home heating oil rose 0.56 cent to 52.48 cents
a gallon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0050EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel Bjt   12-23 0716</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel, Bjt,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Employee Reaction Mixed, Dingell Skeptical of Pact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A historic plea bargain that would spare Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. from a criminal indictment has incited a mixed
reaction among its staff and skepticism by a key Washington
lawmaker, who suggested the $650 million penalty slapped on the Wall
Street giant might not go far enough.
   Rep. John Dingell, the Michigan Democrat who chairs a committee
with oversight authority in the securities industry, said Thursday
he would have to see details of the settlement before drawing
conclusions.
   ``Main Street has less reason to trust Wall Street,'' he said.
``When the details of the settlement come out, we'll find out
whether Main Street has reason to trust their government.''
   He also said: ``I have no reason to believe that Main Street will
be satisifed by anything less than the most serious punishment.
Currently the public regards markets as a crap shoot and has been
avoiding them like the devil avoids holy water.''
   The agreement announced Wednesday would require Drexel to plead
guilty to six felonies and pay a record $650 million in fines and
restitution to settle as-yet unspecified charges, most likely
stemming from its relationship with Ivan Boesky, the now-imprisoned
inside trader who fingered the firm.
   In addition, it would require Drexel to provide investigators
with evidence of possible wrongdoing by its high-yield bond
financier Michael Milken and others.
   Although Drexel senior executives expressed relief about the
settlement and predicted the firm would thrive, sources familiar
with internal criticism of the decision said other employees felt
embittered and concerned.
   ``There's not going to be a mass exodus, but I think in time
significant people will leave,'' said one of the sources, who spoke
on condition they not be identified. ``I think suicide is a little
strong, but I think it's like cutting off your arms and legs.''
   The plea bargain marked a stunning turnaround for Drexel, which
had asserted its innocence since being implicated by Boesky more
than two years ago and had denounced him as a convicted felon and
doublecrosser.
   Others said Milken, a key target of the criminal investigation
spawned by Boesky, felt betrayed by the Drexel decision, which
weakens his own defense.
   Milken has maintained his innocence and has reiterated that he
would fight any indictment. But the sources said that if he were
indicted he would terminate his relationship with Drexel, which
Milken helped grow into one of the most aggressive and profitable
firms.
   At the same time, the agreement took tremendous pressure off
chief executive Frederick Joseph and other senior managers, who had
been urging colleagues to swallow their pride and settle the case so
the firm could leave the protracted ordeal behind.
   The agreement also raised the prospect that former White House
chief of staff Howard Baker, whose Tennessee law practice has been
advising Drexel for months, would become chairman as part of a
long-term recovery strategy, sources familiar with Baker-Drexel
discussions said.
   Baker, the onetime Tennessee senator who has been conferring in
New York with Drexel aides almost every other week, was visiting the
firm a day before the settlement was reached, the sources said.
   ``Clearly the decision yesterday (Wednesday) removes one of the
major obstacles,'' said one source. ``Now you can see the
opportunity to talk in more detail about such a role.''
   Baker's spokesman Thomas Griscom declined to comment on Baker's
discussions or speculation about his selection as chairman.
   ``They have continued to talk and we expect that to go forward
for the next several weeks,'' Griscom said. Drexel spokesman Steven
Anreder said, ``We echo comments about discussions with him but
there's nothing wider on the table.''
   The settlement agreement still requires approval from senior
Justice Department officials and the Securities and Exchange
Commission, which sued Drexel, Milken and others three months ago on
civil charges of conspiring with Boesky to profit on inside
information, manipulate stock and commit other frauds.
   Sources familiar with the agreement said these other agencies
must approve the agreement by mid-January.
   Chiles Larson, a spokesman for the SEC in Washington, declined to
comment on the agreement or on the status of possible discussions
with Drexel. Anreder, Drexel's spokesman, also declined to comment
on any SEC discussions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
