<DOCNO> AP881223-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0051EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel-Clients Bjt   12-23 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel-Clients, Bjt,0705</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Picks Up Pieces After Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After settling the nation's biggest securities
fraud case, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. now faces the crucial task
of retaining its clients, who include many well-known takeover
strategists.
   The beleaguered Wall Street firm received some staunch support
from a number of corporate clients Thursday, one day after it
agreeing to plead guilty to six fraud charges and pay the government
a record $650 million penalty.
   But some clients said privately they still needed to review
whether the plea-bargaining arrangement would change their close
business relationship with Drexel.
   ``I don't think anything at this point is that clear,'' said a
spokesman for one client, which did not want to be identified.
   In announcing its plea agreement late Wednesday, Drexel avoided
what could have been a lengthy, costly trial that threatened to
slowly destroy the firm. The government had spent two years
investigating Drexel's relationship with Ivan F. Boesky, the former
stock speculator was accused of insider trading.
   Although the $650 million settlement is the largest ever in a
securities fraud case, Drexel said it may have cost more in lost
business and legal fees had it continued to fight the federal
charges. Frederick H. Joseph, Drexel chief executive officer, said
the company already has lost about $1.5 billion in business and paid
out $175 million in legal expenses.
   The settlement, though, does not protect Michael Milken, Drexel's
high-yield ``junk bond'' whiz and another key target of the criminal
probe. Milken repeatedly has asserted his innocence.
   Drexel now faces the formidable task of retaining its key
clientele, even without Milken, if it hopes to remain one of the
most powerful and profitable investment banks on Wall Street.
   Milken has generated billions of dollars in revenue for Drexel
through junk bond underwriting, much of which has been used to
finance some of the biggest corporate takeovers of the decade.
   Loyal clients have included such takeover strategists as Carl
Icahn, Ronald O. Perelman, Saul Steinberg and William Farley.
   ``It's obviously a serious blow to Drexel,'' said Farley,
chairman and chief executive of Chicago-based Farley Industries,
which contemplates using Drexel-floated junk bonds to buy
Westpoint-Pepperell Inc.
   Farley said Drexel has assured him it will be able to fulfill its
role in the financing. He said he was confident the firm could
finance the acquisition of Westpoint-Pepperell ``under any scenario
you could describe, and that obviously includes without Drexel.''
   A Drexel spokesman said Thursday that the firm would continue
reassuring its clients that the government settlement would not
interfere with any of its current or future deals.
   ``We have a program of ... communication with employees and
clients, which we consider to be our principal constituentcies,''
said Steven S. Anreder, a senior vice president for the New York
firm. ``The people I've spoken to have indicated their support.''
   Among the staunch supporters have been such small,
growth-oriented companies as Red Bank, N.J., real estate developer
Hovnanian Enterprises Inc.
   ``We feel indebted to Drexel,'' said Hovnanian President Ara
Hovnanian. ``They helped us a great deal with our financing and
that's why we'll be standing with them in their difficult times.''
   Hovnanian said Drexel's $100 million in junk bonds enabled it
grow more than six-fold over the past six year.
   Thomas Reed, spokesman for Shamrock Holdings Inc., which hopes to
take over Polaroid Corp. with the help of Drexel junk-bond
financing, said his firm would maintain its relationship with Drexel.
   ``Shamrock is gratified that Drexel's put the whole thing behind
them. It's been a very difficult experience, but it resolves any
uncertainties, real or imagined, that may have existed on Wall
Street concerning Drexel's ability to operate,'' Reed said.
   Harold Simmons, billionaire chairman of Dallas-based Valhi Inc.,
was equally as supportive.
   Simmons said he used Drexel to float junk bonds three times, most
recently in February when he increased his stake in NL Industries, a
company of which he is now chairman.
   ``I'm sure we'll be doing business with them in the future,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
