<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Dun&Bradstreet     12-23 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dun & Bradstreet,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business Information Concern Announces Layoffs, Consolidations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dun & Bradstreet Corp. plans to discontinue some
businesses and product lines and to make workforce cuts under a
major restructuring aimed at strengthening its leadership in the
business information industry.
   The company said Thursday that restructuring costs were expected
to offset the $450 million after-tax gain it will get from the sale
of its Official Airline Guides business to British publisher Robert
Maxwell.
   Dun & Bradstreet, the world's biggest marketer of business
information and related services, said it had completed the sale of
Official Airline Guides to Maxwell for $750 million.
   That business includes transportation and travel guides, travel
magazines such as Frequent Flier, which has a circulation of about
350,000, and an on-line ticketing, reservation, schedule and fare
information service.
   Maxwell also has an option to acquire D&B's Thomas Cook travel
agency business.
   Dun & Bradstreet stock closed up 12{ cents at $54 a share on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Bill Doescher, a spokesman for Dun & Bradstreet, declined to
comment on specifics of the planned restructuring, or what
percentage of the company's 60,000-member worldwide workforce would
be affected.
   Dun & Bradstreet stated in a news release that its restructuring
would include:
   _employee reductions and relocations in a number of unspecified
businesses as a result of automation and reorganization;
   _discontinuance and consolidation of certain businesses and
operations;
   _consolidation and streamlining of computer and production
facilties worldwide;
   _phaseout of the manual collection of household panel information
by Nielsen Marketing Research.
   ``These are continuing steps in the long-term process of
strengthening our competitive advantage and worldwide leadership
positions in key markets for information services,'' stated Charles
W. Moritz, Dun & Bradstreet's chairman and chief executive.
   Dun & Bradstreet, which owns the Nielsen marketing and television
research companies, Moody's Investors Service credit rating firm and
Donnelley marketing and directory publishing businesses, has been
acquiring and selling businesses in order to focus more on its key
markets for information services.
   Dun & Bradstreet agreed to acquire IMS International Inc., a
major market research concern, last February in a stock swap valued
at $1.77 billion. The restructuring costs also include costs of the
termination of IMS International's South African operations.
   The company also has announced plans to acquire Commercial Credit
Co.'s American Credit Indemnity Co. business credit insurance
subsidiary for $140 million, and Chase Manhattan Corp.'s Interactive
Data Corp., a securities research firm for $140 million.
   Dun & Bradstreet posted a profit of $375.9 million, or $2.01 per
share, on revenue of $3.13 billion during the nine months ended
Sept. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
