<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Drexel-BeverlyHills     12-23 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drexel-Beverly Hills,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Milken's Beverly Hills: Financial Nerve Center Amid Posh Botiques</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drexel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly a continent away from Wall
Street but dead center in its latest insider-trading scandal, junk
bond king Michael Milken works on an opulent avenue lined with tony
boutiques and stately hotels.
   The decision of his employer, Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., to pay
a record $650 million fine to settle criminal securities fraud
charges has reportedly split the company's ranks over the fate of
Milken. But there was little outward sign of that turmoil Thursday.
   Employees arriving for work _ the few who would acknowledge a
reporter _ refused to talk about the case. Attempts to get into
Drexel's unobtrusive offices were rebuffed by uniformed guards who
staff the reception desk of the building on Rodeo Drive, the
shoppers' Mecca.
   Milken has said through spokesmen that he is prepared to fight
criminal charges believed pending against him. According to some who
saw him socially during the many months the Drexel investigation has
been publicly unwinding, Milken appears to have retained his
customary enthusiasm for business and extensive charitable interests.
   ``He's not a defensive-type guy,'' said Richard Riordan, a Los
Angeles attorney and investor and friend of Milken's who last saw
him 10 days ago at a charity event.
   ``He acts like nothing has happened and his whole time and effort
is spent on the thing at hand,'' Riordan said. ``My guess is he's a
tough guy ... I think he's going to keep doing business as usual.''
   The very fact of Drexel's presence in this enclave of the rich
and famous is testament to Milken's importance to Drexel, and his
willingness to flout convention. Not only is Beverly Hills out of
Manhattan, it's a good 10 miles from the Los Angeles financial
district.
   Drexel's offices are spread through two low-rise gray marble
buildings that also house the aristocratic Gump's department store,
a clothing boutique and a savings and loan office.
   Across Rodeo Drive is the ornate Beverly Wilshire Hotel, where
Nancy Reagan stays when she's in town. Up the way are shops of
Cartier, Tiffany & Co. and Van Cleef & Arpels jewelers, where
President Reagan bought the first couple's wedding ring.
   Inside the office, Milken and his lieutenants line up buyers and
sellers of high-risk, high-yield junk bonds. Much of Drexel's junk
bond business depends on this network, with previous issuers of
bonds often being tapped to buy someone else's new issue.
   Milken is said to have tired of working in New York and to have
persuaded Drexel that the business could be done by telephone from
anywhere.
</TEXT>
