<2ND_LINE>BC-Greece-Bank Commissioner,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Head Of Investigation Into Bank of Crete Scandal Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government-appointed bank commissioner
investigating the biggest financial scandal in Greece's history,
died Friday from a heart attack.
   Spyros Papadatos' death occurred the day he was scheduled to
release a list of depositors, including state enterprizes, at the
Bank of Crete, as part of his ongoing investigation.
   Papadatos, a 53-year-old official of the central bank, was
appointed to investigate the widening scandal at the Bank of Crete
on October 18.
   In a preliminary report Papadatos had disclosed that at least
$300 million of bank funds were either missing or mismanaged and
accused the bank's chairman, George Koskotas, of fraud and
embezzlement.
   Koskotas was suspended as bank chairman, but fled the country on
Nov.6 and eventually went to the United States where he was arrested.
   The 34-year-old Koskotas, married to an American citizen, remains
in a Boston, jail awaiting an extradition hearing.
   The financial scandal has implicated ranking members of Premier
Andreas Papandreou's socialist government, prompting seven ministers
to leave. Several of the ministers quit to protest the government's
handling of the investigation alleging that a coverup was underway
in order to protect senior socialist party officials.
   Police said Papadatos was declared dead upon arrival at an Athens
hospital after he suffered a heart attack at home.
</TEXT>
