<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Norway-Oil     12-23 0127</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Norway-Oil,0135</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Norway To Cut Oil Output By 20.8 Million Barrels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norway's oil put during the first half of
1989 will be cut by 115,000 barrels per day from earlier production
plans, the government told parliament Friday.
   The Ministry of Oil and Energy said daily production from January
to June will average 1.44 million barrels, down from the 1.55
million barrels called for in field operators' original plans.
   Daily production during the first and second half of 1988
averaged 1.03 million and 1.12 million barrels respectively.
   Though not a member of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, Norway is voluntarily holding production down in order to
bolster prices.
   OPEC members agreed last month to cut production to 18.5 million
barrels a day.
</TEXT>
