<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 0907EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Chips     12-23 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Chips,0269</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Instruments, Hitachi to Jointly Develop Computer Chips</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Instruments Inc. and Hitachi Ltd. have agreed
to jointly develop technology for a new generation of computer
memory chips, Hitachi officials said.
   The agreement announced Thursday calls for jointly developing
16-megabit D-RAMs, or dynamic random access memory chips, by
exchanging technology.
   A 16-megabit DRAM can hold 16 million bits of information,
equivalent to about 64 pages of an English-language newspaper, and
16 times the size of the 1-megabit DRAMs commonly used in today's
high-performance computers.
   ``Each company will have access to the other's D-RAM technology
as it relates to 16-megabit development,'' Hitachi said in a
statement.
   ``We are very happy to enter into this relationship with
Hitachi,'' William P. Weber, Texas Instruments' executive vice
president, said in a statement. ``Both of our companies bring unique
technological skills in D-RAMs.''
   He said the agreement, which only covers technology related to
16-megabit chips, will be expanded to cover other future generation
technology. The three-year agreement is extendable, a Hitachi
official said.
   Kazuo Kimbara, Hitachi's group executive, said, ``This agreement
combines the 16-megabit development efforts of two of the world's
leading semiconductor technology companies.''
   Toshiba Corp. and Motorola Inc., both leading chip makers, signed
a similar agreement in May 1987. The two firms formed a joint
venture in Fukushima, northern Japan, to produce 256-kilobit DRAMs
and 1-megabit DRAMs.
   Analysts said each company will benefit from the agreement, with
Texas Instruments gaining Hitachi's leading technology in chip
production while offering its accumulated know-how in building
microprocessing units.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
