<HEAD>Machinists, Management Set New Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines and the Machinists union plan to
return to the bargaining table on Jan. 6 for intense federal
mediation aimed at ending a year-old contract snafu which management
claims is helping destroy the carrier.
   Federal mediator Harry Bickford said Thursday that the
negotiations were aimed at settling the dispute without declaring an
impasse that would trigger a 30-day cooling-off period.
   National Mediation Board Chairman Walter Wallace will participate
in the talks, which are expected to last at least a week at an
undisclosed location.
   Negotiations have bogged down over the Machinists' refusal to
accept any major pay cuts. Machinists leader Charles E. Bryan has
charged that Eastern management wants to provoke a strike as a
union-busting tactic.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said management believes the best
way to reach a settlement with its largest labor union is by
imposing a 30-day deadline.
   ``We believe that mediation would have a much better chance if a
deadline were set,'' Matell said. ``The absence of a deadline has
been the most critical missing link.''
   Matell said Eastern will make a strong effort to reach a
settlement in the talks next month. ``We want it to succeed, and we
will work hard to make the negotiations successful,'' he said.
   Bryan declined to discuss the upcoming mediation.
