<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0305</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market headed higher today in light
pre-Christmas trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 6.43 to 2,166.79 in
the first half hour of the session.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 3 to 2 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 501 up, 335 down and
545 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 12.69 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Wall Streeters were expecting a quiet day as many investors opted
to get an early start on the long holiday weekend.
   Brokers also said money managers at investing institutions had
pretty much finished their maneuvering for the year.
   However, stocks did attract a few nibbles from buyers as the
market opened. There has been a lot of talk lately of accumulating
stocks before New Year's to try to benefit from the so-called
January effect.
   Academic researchers have published many studies about an evident
tendency of stock prices to rise in the first month of the year.
Whether that phenomenon will persist in 1989, of course, remains to
be seen.
   Gainers among the blue chips included USX, up [ at 28|; Sears
Roebuck, up [ at 41|, and American Telephone & Telegraph, up \ at
29\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.23 to 155.73. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .32 at 300.65.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average dropped 4.28 to
2,160.36.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 10 to 9 on the
NYSE, with 690 up, 773 down and 517 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 150.51 million shares, against 147.25
million in the previous session.
</TEXT>
