<HEAD>Financial Institution Suspends Three in Profits Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boston Co., a unit of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.,
said it has suspended three top officers while it investigates
discrepencies in its 1988 financial report.
   F. Gregory Ahearn, a senior vice president, said today that
earnings may have been overstated by $10 million to $15 million.
   He said the company suspended with pay three of its executives
until a review of the financial results from a special committee of
outside directors was completed.
   Ahearn declined to name the executives. However, an article in
today's Boston Globe quoting unidentifed sources as saying James N.
von Germeten, president of Boston Co. and chairman of its
subsidiary, Boston Safe Deposit and Trust, was among those suspended.
   The others were Michael J. Walsh, Boston Co. chief financial
officer, and Joseph F. Murphy, an executive vice president, the
newspaper said.
</TEXT>
