<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed In Light, Pre-Christmas Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed, then
turned slightly lower today in light, pre-Christmas trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts predicted little price movement due to the absence of
many traders. The exchange was scheduled to close at noon CST and to
reopen on Tuesday morning.
   ``I predict it'll be a dull, quiet trade for the most part,''
said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in
Chicago.
   Rain overnight in the Brazilian soybean belt lent a weaker tone
to all the markets, he said.
   But losses in the corn market were limited by the Agriculture
Department's announcement late Thursday that the Soviet Union had
purchased 1 million metric tons of U.S. corn.
   Wheat futures were supported by expectations that the USDA would
announce a wheat offer to the Soviets after Friday's close,
Lespinasse said.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to } cent lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.38} a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1\ cents lower with March at $2.83\ a bushel; oats were
\ cent to 1 cent higher with March at $2.33 a bushel; soybeans were
unchanged to 2 cents lower with January at $7.91 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were slightly higher in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .30 cent to .40 cent higher with February at
74.20 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent to .45 cent higher
with January at 84.02 cents a pound; live hogs were .12 cent to .43
cent higher with February at 47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .18 cent to .40 cent higher with February at 44.40 cents a
pound.
   Livestock futures settled mixed on Thursday while pork bellies
finished sharply lower.
</TEXT>
