<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Advance On Export Talk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures made strong gains and grain
futures closed moderately higher Friday on the Chicago Board of
Trade amid rumors of new export business with the Soviet Union.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department announced a sale of
750,000 metric tons of U.S. corn to the Soviets, confirming one of
the rumors that swept the grain pits during the shortened session.
The markets closed at noon and will reopen Tuesday morning.
   Talk also circulated that the USDA was preparing to offer the
Soviet Union 2 million metric tons of U.S. wheat at subsidized
prices, and that the Soviets had already purchased as much as 1
million metric tons of U.S. soybean meal, analysts said.
   ``These rumors, although not necessarily believed, kept sellers
on the sidelines,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader with Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Soybeans advanced despite bearish predictions for weekend showers
in the South American soybean belt.
   ``The gains were rather impressive given the rain in the South
American forecasts, so I think the market's acting very well,''
Lespinasse said.
   At the close, wheat was } cent to 2\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.41 a bushel; corn was \ cent to
2\ cents higher with March at $2.84\ a bushel; oats were 3\ cents to
5 cents higher with March at $2.37 a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents
to 8 cents higher with January at $7.98 a bushel.
</TEXT>
