   The stock market showed a small gain today in
very quiet pre-Christmas trading.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 7.50 to 2,167.86 by
2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 8 to 5 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 812 up, 503 down and
550 unchanged.
   Wall Streeters were expecting a quiet day as many investors opted
to get an early start on the long holiday weekend.
   Brokers also said money managers at investing institutions had
pretty much finished their maneuvering for the year.
   However, stocks did attract a few nibbles from buyers as the
market opened. There has been a lot of talk lately of accumulating
stocks before New Year's to try to benefit from the so-called
January effect.
   Academic researchers have published many studies about an evident
tendency of stock prices to rise in the first month of the year.
Whether that phenomenon will persist in 1989, of course, remains to
be seen.
   American Brands, rumored to be a potential takeover target,
jumped 8| to 66\. One unconfirmed report was that Unilever was
preparing to offer as much as $90 a share for the company's stock.
   Rexene Corp., which said Thursday that it was engaged in talks
with a possible acquirer, climbed 6 to 24\.
   Gainers among the blue-chip and technology issues included Philip
Morris, up 1[ at 101; American Telephone & Telegraph, up [ at 29[;
Digital Equipment, up 1\ at 97\, and International Business
Machines, up ~ at 123].
   Lin Broadcasting rose 3~ to 69} in the over-the-counter market. A
group including McCaw Cellular Communications said it plans to ask
for regulatory approval to increase its stake in the company.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks gained
.56 to 156.06. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up 1.17 at 301.50.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 64.41 million shares with two
hours to go.
