<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: There will be no BC-Dollar-Gold</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended the week slightly higher Friday
against all key currencies except the British pound in abbreviated
pre-holiday trading.
   Gold prices also rose. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold closed at $418.25 a troy ounce, up 65 cents from late Thursday.
   Trading throughout the world was described as extremely quiet in
the absence of much market-moving news and with nearly all traders
getting an early jump on the three-day Christmas holiday weekend.
   ``Trading doesn't exist anymore,'' said one London dealer.
``Anyone who takes a position now is either very foolish or very
brave.''
   The dollar lost ground against the British pound.It cost $1.80125
to buy one pound in London, more expensive than Thursday's $1.7990.
Sterling fetched $1.8020 in New York, up from $1.79875.
   On Friday, the British government reported that the merchandise
trade deficit in Britain narrowed to $3.61 billion in November from
a revised $5.4 billion the previous month.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar closed at 124.95 yen, up 0.33 yen. In London it slipped
back to 124.70 yen. Later, in New York, the dollar stood at 124.80
yen, up from late Thursday's 124.675.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Thursday's
rates, included: 1.7755 West German marks, up from 1.77285; 1.4985
Swiss francs, up from 1.49475; 1.19625 Canadian dollars, unchanged
from 1.19625; 6.0640 French francs, up from 6.0510; and 1,307.50
Italian lire, up from 1.306.25.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Thursday: 1.7760 West
German marks, up from 1.7735; 1.4980 Swiss francs, up from 1.4970;
6.0690 French francs, up from 6.0540; 2.0060 Dutch guilders, up from
2.0035; 1.19625 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1959; and 1,309.80
Italian lire, up from 1,306.00.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery stood at $418 a troy ounce, unchanged from late Thursday.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $417.75 an ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $417.25. In Zurich, gold closed at a
bid $416.30 an ounce, down from $417.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.86 to close at a bid $416.59
an ounce.
   Silver prices declined. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $6.135 a troy ounce from $6.160 Thursday.
In London, silver closed at $6.12 an ounce, down from $6.15.
</TEXT>
