<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1503EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-23 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Copper Posts Strong Gains On Supply Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Copper futures prices surged Friday in a shortened, pre-holiday
session on New York's Commodity Exchange as concerns about tight
supplies strengthened their grip on the volatile market.
   On other futures markets Friday, precious metals, grains,
soybeans, energy, livestock and meat futures all advanced while
coffee fell slightly.
   Most markets closed at noon local time and will not reopen until
Tuesday morning. Trading activity was uniformly light as many
traders got an early start on the long Christmas weekend.
   Copper settled 1.1 cents to 3.2 cents higher with the spot
December contract at $1.605 a pound and the more actively traded
contract for delivery in March at $1.393 a pound.
   Prices advanced despite the Commodity Exchange's report of a
hefty increase overnight in its warehouse stocks of copper. Comex
copper stocks rose by 1,376 tons to 9,582 tons.
   Analysts said they expected the stocks report to put pressure on
the copper market, which saw the spot price hit a record high of
$1.6475 a pound Dec. 8 on tight-supply fears.
   Instead, said New York-based analyst Bernard Savaiko of
PaineWebber Inc., ``we closed stronger on lingering ideas that
there's supply tightness that is not going to go away, especially if
the economy remains resilient going into the first quarter of next
year, which is normally the strongest period from a consumption
standpoint.''
   He said market players believed the rise in Comex stocks was
temporary and that some traders were surprised the copper market was
not following last year's pattern of leaping higher each day as the
end of the year approached.
   ``But there's still a lack of production and strong demand, so
while the pattern may not be repeating last year's exactly, the
fundamentals are still strong,'' he said.
   Also on the Comex, gold settled 30 cents to 70 cents higher with
February at $421.60 a troy ounce; silver was .20 cent to 1.1 cents
higher with March at $6.275 a troy ounce.
   Soybean futures made strong gains and grain futures closed
moderately higher Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid rumors
of new export business with the Soviet Union.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department announced a sale of
750,000 metric tons of U.S. corn to the Soviets, confirming one of
the rumors that swept the grain pits during the shortened session.
   The USDA confirmed another rumor when it announced it had
targeted the Soviet Union for 2 million metric tons of U.S. wheat at
subsidized prices.
   And the USDA also said it had increased the amount of grain the
Soviets could buy annually under the two nations' long-term grain
agreement to 16 million metric tons from 12 million metric tons.
   One rumor that was not confirmed was that the Soviets had already
purchased as much as 1 million metric tons of U.S. soybean meal,
analysts said.
   ``These rumors ... kept sellers on the sidelines,'' said Victor
Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat settled 1 cent to 2 cents higher with March at $4.40{ a
bushel; corn was \ cent to 1} cents higher with March at $2.84\ a
bushel; oats were 3 cents to 5 cents higher with March at $2.37 a
bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 8 cents higher with January at
$7.96{ a bushel.
   Coffee futures prices slipped on New York's Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa
Exchange on news that a Brazilian dockworkers' strike had ended. The
strike began Dec. 13.
   Despite the strike's end, though, analysts said near-term
availability of coffee remained extremely tight, a bullish factor as
cold weather in the Northern Hemisphere brings coffee consumption to
its annual peak.
   Coffee settled .02 cent to 1.73 cents lower with March at $1.4937
a pound.
   Oil futures prices gained more ground on the New York Mercantile
Exchange in light, pre-holiday trading.
   Market sentiment has been upbeat in recent days, with many
traders increasingly confident that OPEC members will abide by a
production-cutting agreement forged last month.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 12 cents to 19 cents
higher with February at $16.61 a barrel; heating oil was .46 cent to
.79 cent higher with January at 53.14 cents gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .29 cent to .72 cent higher with January at 46.86 cents
a gallon.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .47 cent
to .67 cent higher with February at 74.37 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .32 cent to .70 cent higher with January at 84.22 cents
a pound; live hogs were .05 cent to .73 cent higher with February at
47.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .15 cent to .43 cent
higher with February at 44.50 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
