<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1512EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Chubb-DroughtSuit     12-23 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chubb-Drought Suit,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Join Chubb Group In Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for farmers who sued Chubb Corp. in a
dispute over 1988 drought insurance now have joined with Chubb
against the remaining defendant in the class-action lawsuit.
   Chubb, an insurer based in Warren, N.J., recently agreed to a $48
million settlement with lawyers representing 8,800 farmers in 10
states whose rain insurance applications were rejected this summer.
   Stanley Chesley, a lawyer for the farmers, said Thurday he and
Chubb lawyers have drafted a common plan of litigation against the
remaining defendant in the lawsuit, Good Weather International Corp.
   Good Weather insurance agents allegedly sold about $350 million
worth of Chubb drought-insurance policies that Chubb refused to
honor.
   The farmers' lawyers have asked unspecified damages against Good
Weather, saying it violated its contract with Chubb by overselling
policies.
   Chubb also has sued Good Weather separately for $68 million,
saying the policies should not have been sold.
   Chesley said the farmers and Chubb plan to split any settlement
award. Chubb would get a third of whatever it wins from Good
Weather, and the farmers would get two-thirds.
   The two lawsuits will be tried together early next year in
Cincinnati before U.S. District Judge Carl B. Rubin, who approved
the recent $48 million Chubb settlement.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
