<HEAD>A&P To Acquire Borman's Inc.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Great Scott! is cq in 6th graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RABY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Aassociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Great Atlantic and Pacific Tea Co. Inc. has
agreed to buy Borman's Inc., a Detroit-area supermarket company, for
$75.6 million, the companies announced Friday.
   A&P will pay $27 a share in cash for each of Borman's 2.8 million
outstanding shares, the companies said in a joint statement.
   A&P's offer is subject to a number of conditions, including
approval by Borman's shareholders.
   Borman's operates 79 Farmer Jack food markets in the Detroit area.
   A&P, the nation's fourth-largest supermarket company, has 40
outlets in the Detroit area and a total of 1,183 supermarkets in 26
states and Canada.
   The merger would make A&P the dominant food retailer in
southeastern Michigan, giving it control of 119 stores and about 40
percent of the market.
   The next biggest chains in the Detroit market are Kroger with 25
stores and Great Scott! with 24 stores.
   Analysts have said A&P could achieve significant savings by
taking over its biggest competitor.
   Also Friday, Borman's reported a loss of $9.7 million in the
third quarter ended Nov. 5, on sales of $239.2 million. That
compared with a loss of $15.9 million, on sales of $219.9 million,
in the same period a year earlier.
</TEXT>
