<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AmericanBrands Bjt   12-23 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-American Brands, Bjt,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Brands Stock Shoots Up On Unilever Takeover Rumor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Brands Inc. was closed Friday for the
Christmas holiday, but that didn't stop Wall Street from briefly
sending the tobacco company's stock up 22 percent on rumors of a
takeover by Unilever, the British-Dutch consumer products
conglomerate.
   Both companies declined to discuss the rumors, citing policies
against commenting on speculation. One rumor said Unilever might pay
as much as $90 a share for American Brands.
   American Brands got as high as $70.25 a share and was at $67.12{
in late trading on Wall Street, up $9.50, or 16 percent.
   Allan Kaplan, an analyst for Merrill Lynch & Co., said the rumor
was hard to substantiate. ``I've called a number of arbitragers that
are very well tuned in and nobody knows,'' he said.
   If it came through, a purchase by Unilever would continue the
trend of foreign takeovers as well as the trend of mergers in the
tobacco and food businesses. In one such case, Pillsbury Co. last
week submitted to a takeover bid by Britain's Grand Metropolitan
PLC, a liquor distiller.
   American Brands, based in Old Greenwich, Conn., is a perennially
mentioned takeover candidate. Earlier this year it fought off a
takeover bid by E-II Holdings Inc. with the ``Pac-Man'' defense, in
which it bought the would-be acquirer. It later sold most of E-II to
Riklis Family Corp.
   E-II's offering price for American Brands last spring was $55 a
share. But Kaplan said he estimated that the breakup value of
American Brands was about $95 a share, based on an estimate that
investors would be willing to pay about nine times its operating
cash flow minus debt.
   Unilever and American Brands met once before, in 1986, when
Unilever came in as a white knight to rescue Chesebrough-Pond's Inc.
from a $2.8 billion hostile takeover offer from American Brands. It
bought the company for $3.1 billion.
   American Brands, with revenue of about $10 billion a year, has a
broad product line but makes most of its profits from its cigarette
brands, which in the United States are Lucky Strike, Tareyton, Pall
Mall, Carlton, and the new Malibu. It owns Gallaher, the biggest
British tobacco company.
   In distilled spirits, American Brands sells Jim Beam and Canadian
Windsor whisky, De Kuyper cordials and Gilbey's gin and vodka. It
owns Franklin Life Insurance Co.; Master Brands, which makes Master
locks; Cushnet, the maker of Titleist golf balls; Acco World Corp.,
maker of Swingline staplers and Wilson Jones office supplies; and
Waterloo Industries, the biggest distributor of toolboxes.
   Unilever, with annual revenue of more than $30 billion, is one of
the world's biggest consumer products companies and has 300,000
employees worldwide, including 20,000 in the United States.
   In the United States, Unilever's main companies are
Chesebrough-Pond's, which makes Vaseline, Q-Tips and Ragu products;
Lever Brothers, maker of All, Surf, Wisk and Sunlight cleaning
products and Imperial, Promise and Shedd's margarines; Lipton, which
makes tea and soup; and National Starch and Chemical, which sells
starch for the food industry and specialty chemicals.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
