<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1652EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-AirFares     12-23 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Fares,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Some Fares Much Higher After Northwest-Republic Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air travelers in the Minneapolis-St. Paul area
paid much higher fares to some destinations in the year after the
local market became dominated by one airline, according to a report
published Friday.
   In a review of 27 routes where competition was reduced by
Northwest Airlines' 1986 merger with Republic Airlines, average
fares rose on 23 routes, sometimes by more than 40 percent, the Star
Tribune reported.
   On all Northwest flights in and out of the Twin Cities, a
separate study shows the average fare rose 18.5 percent, six times
the national average, in the year after the merger, the newspaper
said.
   Northwest, based in Eagan, Minn., disputes the findings. Airline
officials said no broad conclusions could be drawn using isolated
fare comparisons. The airline generated new data showing that
Northwest flights were less expensive than similar flights from
other airports by other carriers.
   In addition, Northwest's study found, passengers flying to the
Twin Cities saved money over those connecting to other destinations.
Northwest also said that, like most airlines, it was earning thin
profit margins.
   Many factors help explain fare increases. But Alfred Kahn, the
architect of U.S. airline deregulation, said the broad pattern
indicated in the newspaper's study of Northwest's fares appears to
conform with ``every major study with which I am familiar.'' When
airline concentration increases, he said, fares tend to rise.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881223-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1756EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv24-25   12-23 0575</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 24-25,0603</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 24</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 24-25</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Junk Bond' Market Watchful in Wake of Drexel Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The historic settlement of fraud charges by Wall
Street powerhouse Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. isn't expected to
bring a major shakeup in the market for ``junk bonds'' pioneered and
dominated by Drexel.
   Still, market players are taking a cautious, wait-and-see
attitude.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani announced this past Wednesday
that Drexel had reversed itself by agreeing to admit guilt to six
felonies and pay a record $650 million fine to settle the biggest
securities fraud case in history.
   Expectations of a Drexel settlement had grown in recent days, and
the $180 billion market for high-risk, high-yield junk bonds wasn't
taken by surprise. In fact, bond traders seemed relieved that the
business was over after dragging on for two years and the investment
firm had decided not to wage a risky fight.
   A ``flight to quality'' out of junk bonds and into conventional
securities, which had been predicted in some quarters as a result of
the Drexel debacle, failed to materialize.
   Prices of high-yield bonds were mostly little changed and even
slightly higher in some cases in quiet trading.
   But a sort of edgy calm appeared to hang over the market as
traders looked toward the new year and post-settlement prospects.
   ``Most people are taking a wait-and-see attitude,'' said Robert
Levine, president of high-yield asset management at Kidder Peabody &
Co.
   Market players are watching for further developments in the
government's investigation that could prompt some junk bond traders
at Drexel to leave the firm.
   ``This isn't over,'' said a market expert who asked not to be
identified. He noted anxiety that the investigation could envelop
some of Drexel's clients, who include many well-known takeover
strategists.
   Some of those clients said privately this past week they still
needed to review whether the plea-bargaining arrangement would
change their close business relationship with Drexel.
   That, traders fear, could potentially affect Drexel's ability to
continue to sell mammoth junk bond issues, such as the one being
used to help finance the $24.5 billion leveraged buyout of RJR
Nabisco Inc. by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.
   The market points to the Nabisco issue as evidence that Drexel is
still a force to be reckoned with.
   The other players in the junk bond market _ notably Merrill Lynch
Capital Markets, Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., Goldman Sachs &
Co. and First Boston Corp. _ might lack the clout of dominant Drexel
in selling huge issues, some experts suggest.
   ``I don't really think we're going to see a sea change in the
market,'' said Ray Lemanski, director of high-yield securities
research at Prudential-Bache.
   There shouldn't be a major change in terms of the volume of junk
issues coming to market or their prices and yields, Lemanski said.
But he and other observers conceded that some segments of the market
could be affected by traders leaving Drexel.
   In addition to ``mega'' issues like Nabisco, junk bonds at the
other end of the spectrum, worth less than $100 million or so, also
could present a problem, analysts say. That's because the effort and
expense involved in researching the companies issuing small bonds
has kept all the players except Drexel from bothering with them.
   Some of the smaller issues ``could come under pressure,''
Lemanski said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 24-25</NOTE>
</DOC>
