<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Lockheed     12-23 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lockheed,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dallas Investor Simmons Files to Boost Stake, Says No Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALABASAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. said Friday it had shored
up its takeover defenses after Dallas investor Harold C. Simmons
disclosed he might boost his stake in the aerospace company.
   But Simmons said he considered his stake in Lockheed, builder of
the Stealth fighter and other military hardware, an investment only.
   ``It's not that big a deal. ... We have no intention of trying to
buy the whole company,'' Simmons said in a telephone interview.
   Simmons' Valhi Inc. filed notice Dec. 7 under the
Hart-Scott-Rodino Act that he intended to boost his Lockheed stake
beyond $15 million, the trigger point for the act's disclosure
provisions.
   Lockheed spokesman Bob Slayman refused to say if changes in the
company's 2-year-old ``poison pill'' shareholder rights plan were a
direct response to Simmons' move.
   At the time of the filing, Valhi said it owned 375,000 of
Lockheed's 59.5 million outstanding shares, or 0.63 percent.
   Simmons said the filing was intended to give him leeway to buy
more Lockheed stock with money anticipated from the planned sale of
his Amalgamated Sugar Co. to a British firm. However, that $300
million deal fell through, he said.
   The investor said he had not discussed the matter with Lockheed
officials.
   A Lockheed board vote to tighten the firm's takeover defenses was
taken Thursday, two weeks after the filing, Slayman said.
   The revised plan allows present shareholders to buy newly issued
stock at a discount if an outsider buys 20 percent or more of the
common stock.
   Such poison pill plans are intended to dilute the holdings of a
potential buyer, making a takeover prohibitively expensive.
   Lockheed, with headquarters in this Los Angeles suburb, has
88,000 employees in California, Georgia, New Jersey, Texas and New
Hampshire. The nation's fourth-largest defense contractor, Lockheed
had sales of $11.3 billion in 1987.
   In the first three quarters of this year, it reported a net
profit of $520 million on sales of $7.6 billion, with the profit
figure boosted significantly by sale of a subsidiary.
   Projects include the top-secret F-117A Stealth fighter, the
Trident II nuclear missile, the C-5B transport plane and work on
military communications, satellites, and the Strategic Defense
Initiative or Star Wars. The company also is a subcontractor for
design work on NASA's space station project.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
