<FILEID>AP-NR-12-23-88 1810EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AutoSales Bjt   12-23 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mid-December Sales Rise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. reported a 35.9 percent leap in car
sales in mid-December as overall sales of U.S.-made cars and light
trucks jumped 14.4 percent ahead of the same period in 1987,
automakers reported Friday.
   U.S. makers and foreign companies manufacturing in the U.S. said
they sold an average of 34,919 vehicles a day in the eight selling
days from Dec. 11-20, up from 30,522 a day in the same period a year
earlier.
   The Big Three U.S. automakers alone reported selling at a
slightly slower 33,081 vehicle-a-day rate but that was up 15.3
percent from 28,689 a day in mid-December 1987.
   Sales moved at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 8.2 million
vehicles, up from 7.2 million a year earlier.
   A year ago, with the Oct. 19 stock market crash still fresh in
their minds, people were gun-shy about large purchases, said
Jeanette Garretty, analyst with Bank of America in San Francisco.
   ``Generally, things have been a lot more stable in these last few
periods of 1988,'' she said.
   In the latest period, Ford said it sold 6,764 cars a day, up from
4,977 a day a year earlier. Ford said its truck sales of 4,118 a day
were up 21.5 percent from 3,391 a day in the year-ago period.
   Chrysler Corp. reported the greatest increase in light-truck
sales, a 28.1-percent jump to 3,177 a day from 2,481 in the 1987
period. Chrysler said its car sales reached 3,375 a day, up 20.5
percent from 2,801 a day.
   General Motors Corp. said its car sales rose 4.7 percent to a
10,365-a-day average, up from 9,896 a year earlier, and truck sales
increased 12.7 percent to 5,282 a day from 5,144.
   Sales of all U.S.-made cars and light trucks reached 11,322,465
for the year to date.
   Sales, now in the final period of the calendar year, appeared
unlikely to approach the record 16.3 million of 1986, second-best
15.7 million of 1985 or third-best 15.4 million of 1978.
   ``I don't see a real kick in sales here at the end of December,''
Garretty said. ``But it's a good year. Everybody will take it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
